<HEAD>19 Hospitalized After Chemical Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chemical fire in an electronics plant Tuesday released an acid gas, and 19 people were hospitalized, authorities said. The fire that started in chemical processing equipment at <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dielectrics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s circuit board plant filled the sky with hydrogen bromide fumes before being brought under control around 4:30 p.m., said <PERSON> Cathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Shonk </PERSON> of the Fremont Fire Department. Hydrogen bromide is an acid gas that is extremely irritating to the nose and throat when inhaled, <PERSON> Shonk </PERSON> said. The cause of the fire was being investigated. Orange smoke filled the plant's halls. The fire department evacuated about 100 employees and 225 workers from the <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a training center next door to the factory in an industrial park. The 19 injured were taken to hospitals in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hayward </PERSON>, cities along the eastern shore of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>. Four people were listed in stable condition at <LOCATION> Kaiser </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Hayward </LOCATION>. The hospital would not disclose the nature of their injuries. Nine patients were taken to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, where they were given 15-minute decontamination showers and awaited examinations for possible respiratory damage, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> McAuliffe </PERSON>. Six people treated at <LOCATION> Saint </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Hayward </LOCATION> for irritation to their eyes and throat were in stable condition and were expected to be rele