<HEAD>Truck Driver Critically Injured In Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire that started while a tank truck was loading gasoline destroyed a fuel storage facility and 275,000 gallons of oil, burning the vehicle's driver critically, officials said. The fire sent up a column of smoke that could be seen for at least 20 miles. Five hours after the blaze broke out, flames still were shooting 50 feet in the air, but fire officials said the fire was under control and would be allowed to burn itself out overnight. Firefighters planned to be on the scene into the morning, said <LOCATION> Clarke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Fire Chief <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON>. The fire at Lay's Petroleum Products, a <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> facility which has four above-ground storage tanks, apparently was started by the truck, <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> said. The driver, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Coile </PERSON>, apparently gunned his engine several times as he backed toward a filling area, sucking fumes into his exhaust pipe and touching off the blaze, <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Coile </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Danielsville </LOCATION> was taken to <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in critical condition and airlifted to <ORGANIZATION> Humana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, said a <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> said the tank truck exploded, but all of the storage tanks held. Also destroyed were a motor home, a warehouse containing 5,000 55-gallon drums of oil and the company's office building, <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> said. There was no immediate damage estimate.
