<FIRST>r i PM-BeirutBar     05-03 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beirut Bar,0941</SECOND>
<HEAD>In West Beirut, Backstreet Bar An Oasis During Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Behind the red door on Makhoul Street in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, there's a watering hole where the regulars huddle to share a drink, seek shelter from the shelling, and maybe sing along to a Sinatra tune. Here's what the `` war clientele'' were up to on a recent night:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hunched over a beer in the Backstreet Bar, the only tavern in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> that has stayed open throughout the <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> fighting, a doctor was decribing the horrors of the casualty ward after recent ferocious shelling. Around the Lebanese doctor, a veteran of more bad nights than he can recall in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s relentless bloodletting, the tavern was filled with about 40 people drinking from <PERSON> Habib </PERSON> <PERSON> Ne'aimeh </PERSON>'s well-stocked bar during a lull in the shelling Ne'aimeh has kept his bar open six nights a week during the fighting. `` When the shelling gets heavy I turn up the music,'' he said, standing behind his red and black bar on a recent night. `` These people are not as relaxed as they try to appear. They're drinking more.'' The doctor works at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, once one of the best medical centers in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Now, after 14 years of civil war, it's short of medicine and trained staff. It has taken several direct hits in recent fighting. `` One night 15 people were brought in,'' he said, clutching his beer tightly. `` Four of them were dead. `` There was a baby. We thought its mother was among the dead and we did n't know what to do with it,'' said the doctor. `` Suddenly, this woman appears out of nowhere as one of our people is trying to soothe the baby. Turns out it's the mother.'' That story had a happy ending. But for thousands of other Lebanese, the last seven weeks have brought only death, injury, devastation or confinement in bunkers and basements. Nearly 300 people have been killed and nearly 1,000 wounded since March 8 in almost non-stop battles between army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mainly Christian forces and an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse Moslem militiamen. Ne'aimeh's coterie of customers, what he calls his `` war clientele,'' regularly make it to the Backstreet through the darkened alleys, past packs of dogs scavenging through rotting, rat-infested garbage, to the red door in <LOCATION> Makhoul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>. Shortages have forced Ne'aimeh to trim his menu to cold cuts, cheeses and grilled steaks. His customers, flung together by the war, are a bizarre group of people who for their own reasons have hung on in the Lebanese chaos and the kidnappings. As more than 150,000 people have fled the city amid the carnage in recent weeks, the Backstreet has become an oasis for this disparate group. There are Swiss from the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, Spanish and Belgians from the French-based Medecins Sans Frontiers agency, a couple of Russians, the odd Bulgarian or two and some Lebanese. Ne'aimeh is a <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, one of several thousand who live in the Moslem sector. Most are leftists, with little in common with the Maronite Catholics, who make up the vast majority of the Christians trapped in their enclave in east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the mountains and coastal strip running north. His only waiter is a Sunni Moslem _ the others refuse to leave their underground shelters to go to work _ and the cook's a Shiite Moslem. Despite their different religious preferences, they're a tight team, a microcosm of what's possible in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> if the warring sects and factions could only get their act together. This night at the bar, everyone's having a good time, letting it all out. But there's an undercurrent of apprehension. The laughter sometimes has a brittle edge to it. Everyone knows someone who's been killed or wounded or lost a relative, or whose home has been hit in the bombardments. They've all wondered whether the next rocket or shell to fall will have their name on it Most are skeptical things will get better, and many are trying to leave <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. As the sound system belted out <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> singing `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' everyone joined in the line `` I want to wake up in a city that never sleeps'' _ enjoying the irony that the shelling makes sleep a luxury few get in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. At that moment, the bar's generator sputtered and gave out About 11 p.m., rockets began to arc across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line, three miles of unrelieved devastation, where Christians and Moslems have faced each other from sandbagged positions and gutter apartment buildings for 14 years. `` Incoming or outgoing?'' a young woman asked as an explosion thundered nearby. `` Incoming, I think. I saw the flash,'' a young man answered hesitantly. `` Anybody got a radio?'' someone said. `` What's it say?'' A Lebanese reporter working for a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> news organization tuned his transistor radio to the Christian-run Voice of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` Shells hitting the Christian side,'' the reporter said. `` It's outgoing. `` That's OK then,'' the young man replied. Then the radio said the source of the shelling had been pinpointed to west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The young man lost his poise, told Ne'aimeh he'd pay his tab later, and left. He knew the Christian army gunners were probably at that moment training their 155mm howitzers on the area around the Backstreet Bar to retaliate.
</TEXT>
