<FIRST>u i PM-BorderSpat     05-03 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Border Spat,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>India And Nepal Fuss and Feud at Border Point</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 SIRISIAR BRIDGE, On the <LOCATION> Indian-Nepalese </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Border </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ A friendly sort of friction has set in at this crossing point between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the political and military giant of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, a tiny and landlocked kingdom. For more than a month, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> has been defying and exasperating <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> by refusing to renegotiate trade agreements on <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s terms. As a result, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has imposed a partial blockade and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> is suffering severe shortages of fuel needed to operate motor vehicles, provide electrical power and cook food. Medicines, baby food and other essential goods also are in short supply. The problem is as tangled as the traffic jam of bullock carts, horse-drawn carriages and bicycle-powered rickshaws trying to negotiate the narrow wooden bridge over the <LOCATION> Sirisiar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> without getting stuck in the cracks between the creaking planks. The bullocks' long, pointed horns scrape and snag on the rickshaws' cloth canopies, much as the government officials in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION> are scraping and snagging in the political impasse. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, population 880 million, perceives <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> as an ungrateful neighbor, seeking preferential treatment for itself while refusing to grant <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> reciprocal privileges. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, population 17 million, sees <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> as a bit of a bully, trying to thwart Nepalese efforts to diversify its trading partners. Officially speaking, the Indian blockade is not total. Practically speaking, its effects come close to being total. `` This is not a blockade. You can see the trucks are moving,'' customs collector <PERSON> Asit </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitra </PERSON> said in the Indian border town of <LOCATION> Raxaul </LOCATION> as a score of vehicles lumbered over the bridge to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, hauling burlap bags of salt, cases of baby formula and brand new _ but empty _ tanks for cooking gas. `` The goods are coming in, but not as they were,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Vimal </PERSON> <PERSON> Srivastav </PERSON>, three miles up the road in the Nepalese town of <LOCATION> Birganj </LOCATION>. At the <LOCATION> Birganj </LOCATION> customs yard, the goods are unloaded from Indian trucks. But the porters are sleeping in the midday heat atop the cartons they normally would be transferring to Nepalese trucks. The diesel and gasoline to run the trucks 75 miles north to <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>, the Nepalese capital, no longer arrive from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, itself a net importer of petroleum products. `` It's like you get the torch -LRB- flashlight -RRB-, but not the battery,'' said <PERSON> Pashupati </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaha </PERSON>, a hotel owner in <LOCATION> Birganj </LOCATION>. When the bilateral trade and transit treaties expired March 23 with no replacements in the offing, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> closed 13 of the 15 official crossing points on the 1,095-mile border. Only Raxaul and <PERSON> Jogbani </PERSON> remain open. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> wanted to renegotiate the two treaties separately, one governing trade with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the other covering vital transit rights from <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION> to the border for non-Indian imports. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> sought a single treaty to safeguard its own trade with <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> has little to offer foreign trading partners, apart from goatskins and a few spices. But it imports machinery, housewares, textiles and food in addition to pharmaceutical and petroleum products. For the last two years, about 40 percent of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s imports were Indian. Fifteen years ago, more than 80 percent were Indian. Especially of concern to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are recent Nepalese efforts to expand trade with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s longtime regional rival and the only other country with direct land access to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s pique heightened last fall when <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> purchased anti-aircraft guns and other weapons from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, prompting two questions in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>: Why was <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> making purchases from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and why did the tiny <LOCATION> Himalayan </LOCATION> monarchy, which has about 35,000 men under arms compared to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 1.4 million, need anti-aircraft guns, anyway? <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> considers its trade and defense needs its own business. `` Trade has its own nature,'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shailendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Upadhyaya </PERSON> told a reporter in <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION> this week. `` Trade will increase normally with any country with which we receive a fair deal.'' One more nettle is <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s decision requiring the 150,000 Indians in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> to obtain work permits, while <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has made no similar requirements of the estimated 5 million Nepalese in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. In addition, <PERSON> Birganj </PERSON> had long been a shopper's delight for Indians, whose own country prides itself on self-sufficiency and imports little of the Western and Japanese goods widely available in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. The Nepalese joke about their ability to sell just about anything with a foreign label to Indian visitors. <PERSON> Shaha </PERSON>, the Birganj hotel owner, remarked, `` You can blame <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> for this. The Indians can find some of these things cheaper in <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION>, but they want to come to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and buy. Some merchants import saris from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, stamp ` Made in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>' on them, and the Indians are very happy to buy.'' `` The Nepalese will buy seven or eight times what they need of something, import it through <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>, then smuggle it back across the border to sell it in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>,'' an Indian government official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
