<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Analysis     05-03 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Analysis,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Cease-Fire Gives Government A Reprieve</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The surprise declaration by Sudanese rebels of a monthlong cease-fire reprieves the <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> government's beleaguered troops and boosts an international effort to save 100,000 people facing starvation It also raises hopes for an end to six years of civil war that drains $ 1 million a day from the coffers of one of the world's poorest countries Monday's announcement by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, comes at the height of his greatest success of the war _ a six-month string of victories that has government forces reeling. Rebel fighters also have been intensifying pressure on the strategic southern capital, <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>. Its fall could have determined the war's outcome by forcing the government from its largest stronghold in the embattled south. But at least as important, the cease-fire could boost the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' struggling operation to transport more than 100,000 tons of food and supplies to the south before heavy rains start this month. Last year, relief officials say up to 500,000 southerners died in the fighting or from war-induced disease and famine in villages isolated by flooded roads and airstrips. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, a U.S.-educated renegade army colonel, said the unilateral truce will hold only so long as the government refrains from redeploying or reinforcing its troops. He said it could be extended. Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> welcomed the move. `` Each step taken by <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> toward peace will be reciprocated by two steps from the government,'' he said in a May Day speech. Only last month, <PERSON> Garang </PERSON> rejected a U.N.-proposed `` month of tranquillity'' to allow the $ 132 million relief operation easy access to 2.3 million war-affected southerners. Instead, he guaranteed safe conduct for specific relief convoys. But attacks by unidentified armed groups, bureaucratic hassles, inadequate transport infrastructure and bad planning have hampered the operation. Only 37,000 tons of food was delivered in April. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials say they will continue until the rains cut transport routes. `` I think the overriding reasons behind this decision are political, but they are bound to be connected with the relief effort,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, the regional director of <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> who conducts most <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> negotiations with the rebels. `` We're keeping our fingers crossed, but it ought to help the operation if only by easing things and reducing the level of anxiety,'' <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. Military experts in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> interpreted the rebels' rejection of the original truce as evidence of unwillingness to impede their battlefield winning streak. Since then, <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> has come under army pressure and approved a tentative peace plan, which the rebels welcomed with cautious optimism. The cease-fire `` was the next logical step in the peace process,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>, a lecturer at <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Reading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a specialist on <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> who returned from <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> last week. `` Now it's up to the government to arrange for further steps,'' <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>'s broadcast said all his forces will remain in their positions `` to wait for the government to implement the requirements of the Sudanese peace initiative.'' A joint technical military committee then would work out a comprehensive cease-fire, he said. The agreement's most politically sensitive clause calls for the suspension of harsh Islamic laws in force since late 1983. The mainly animist and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> rebels took up arms against the Moslem-dominated government a few months earlier, demanding autonomy for the south. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>, the leader of a Sudanese Moslem sect, approved the suspension last month, leaving the way clear for a constitutional conference. In the two years that the rebels have won an upper hand in the war, southern civilians have suffered as both sides used food as a weapon. <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>, a city of dusty streets and thatched-roof mud huts whose population is swollen by refugees to five times its normal 30,000, has been besieged for more than two years. Rebels intensified their attacks these past few months. `` The <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION>'s military successes created a very difficult political situation for them,'' said <PERSON> Woodward </PERSON>. `` If they took over the major towns in the south ... it would mean a de facto separation of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, and it would be much more difficult to try and negotiate a peaceful settlement for a united <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Now, they negotiate from a position of strength.'' Military sources in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> say about 20,000 troops are holed up in the middle of <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>. One source estimated the army's strength at 75,000 and the rebels at 57,000. But government troops are outnumbered in the war because only 10,000 soldiers remain in major southern towns other than <LOCATION> Juba </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Cairo-based correspondent <PERSON> Dalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Baligh </PERSON> recently returned from an assignment in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>.
