<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     05-03 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Just Three Weeks After Election, LA Mayor Faces Political Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> won a fifth term three weeks ago, it should have been a time of celebration for the 71-year-old sharecropper's son. Instead, he found himself facing what's become the political crisis of his career. After 16 years of an administration free of personal scandal, the usually bland and steady <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> is the subject of a conflict-of-interest probe for accepting thousands of dollars in consulting fees from banks that did business with the city. He says he was unaware of the business ties when he accepted the money. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> also is under fire because his daughter was employed by a project to which he helped funnel nearly $ 400,000 of city money, the Task Force for Africa-Los Angeles Relations. He said he was unaware she had been hired. The allegations, which began surfacing at the end of the campaign, have tarnished the nice-guy image of <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, a former police lieutenant dubbed the Teflon Mayor for his ability to escape blame for the city's gang, growth and pollution problems. Other mayors have had bigger problems. Political allies of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> have committed suicide or gone to prison. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> admitted a close personal relationship with a woman not his wife. <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> has been slapped with a paternity suit by a former city employee. But for <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, probably the blandest of big-city mayors, it's a major embarrassment For politically dull <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> it's a rare taste of a scandal at the very top. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> has scrambled to defuse the controversy by placing his investments _ which range from an estimated $ 101,000 to $ 1 million _ in a blind trust. He has established an ethics panel _ which announced Monday it wo n't investigate <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> and will instead rewrite the city ethics code to restore public trust in city government. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> also has retained lawyers from <LOCATION> Manatt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phelps </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rothenberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> political insiders that is handling the ethics defense of House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. He is refusing comment until a city investigation is completed. But allegations surface daily. On Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> reported that <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was allowed to hold $ 600,000 in city money for three months in 1987 without paying interest. It said the account was set up by <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. Two months after the situation was discovered, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> started earning $ 18,000 a year as a consultant to the bank. He has since returned the money, saying he was unaware <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> had business ties with the city. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, the city's first black mayor, won a fifth term April 11, barely escaping a runoff with challenger <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> and drawing the lowest turnout in decades. `` Unquestionably the issues that have been raised over the course of the last three weeks have raised some doubts in the minds of some people,'' <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> said. Supporters predict, however, he will survive the controversy. `` He's a super-quality guy. He has never done anything the least bit questionable on anything,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Riordan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coliseum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and a Republican who supports the Democratic <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. `` He's so perfect that people want to knock him off his hill and find his imperfections,'' he added. <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, who made headlines by buying back semi-automatic weapons from the public, said: `` I think the quicker we get to the bottom of this matter the better everything's going to be. Business at City Hall is stopped. It's at a standstill.'' In addition to examining <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s relationships with Far East and the African task force, investigators are focusing on <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> was paid at least $ 71,000 to serve on its board while it did business with the city. He resigned the post the day after his election.
