<HEAD>Pittsburgh School a Model Against Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Educators hope a new program will make a middle school a model for race relations and improved academics. The restructured school _ to be called the <ORGANIZATION> Prospect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Multiracial </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Multicultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Multiethnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> _ is to offer programs to encourage students to respect other races and teach staff members how to instruct students of other races, officials said Tuesday. `` Perhaps it will improve race relations throughout the entire city,'' said Principal <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Pipkin </PERSON>. `` It will be the model where we develop programs, policies and practices for district-wide use,'' <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said no new students or staff members would be added to the present <ORGANIZATION> Prospect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in the city's <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> neighborhood. She said the new programs are to begin next fall. School Superintendent <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said the idea came from principals and consultants who studied city schools last fall. He said concerns about racism stemmed from occasional fights in schools and the disproportionate number of black students who are suspended or referred to special education classes. `` I would n't say it's at this point a serious problem, a crisis situation, but we do n't want it to get to that level,'' <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said. Of about 39,600 public school students in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, 52 percent are black and 48 percent are white, officials said.
