<HEAD>Farmer's Life Savings Rots Underground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The old Chinese habit of shunning banks has caused an 82-year-old farmer to lose most of his life savings to mildew, an official newspaper reported today. When <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexiang </PERSON>, who had buried his life savings of about $ 1,200 in his courtyard five years ago, dug up the money recently he discovered it was moldy `` almost beyond recognition,'' the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported. The farmer in northeastern <LOCATION> Liaoning </LOCATION> province was only able to salvage $ 400, which he exchanged for new bills at a local bank, it said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which has a surplus of cash in its overheated economy, is suffering from a shortage of funds for investment because many people, fearing runaway inflation, traditionally refuse to put their money in the bank. Personal caches like <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON>'s account for an estimated $ 133 billion. The interest rate on one-year deposits was raised last year from 7.2 percent to 8.64 percent, but fails to keep pace with 36 percent inflation.
</TEXT>
