elsewhere to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nevadans voted 3-1 Tuesday to approve a $ 52 million mining tax hike, but balloting was close on a plan to double the money <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> can borrow for new state construction. With 25 percent of 609 precincts counted, the mining tax proposal was favored 26,692-7 ,966 The vote on the construction measure was 18,363 for and 17,051 against. Election officials around the state predicted low voter turnouts, ranging from 30 to 40 percent of the more than 383,000 people eligible to vote. `` It's nothing great but it's steady,'' <ORGANIZATION> Carson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> Clerk-Recorder <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> said of early voter turnout, which he estimated at about 30 percent. Recent polls indicated the mining tax would win approval. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and key lawmakers warned that without approval of the plan, the state would face fiscal chaos. Had the measure lost, officials said, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> would be in session an extra month slashing budgets and raising taxes to make up for the loss of the anticipated mining tax revenues, expected to be $ 52 million over a two-year period. The law would allow the state to impose a 5 percent tax on the net proceeds of mines. The ballot question was the result of an agreement struck during the 1987 Legislature between the mining industry, lawmakers and then-Gov. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>. The other question on the ballot would double the money <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> can borrow for new state construction. The governor's proposed budget includes money generated by state bond sales for new prison and university construction projects. Officials have argued that without doubling the constitutional limit on bond debt to 2 percent of the assessed value of all taxable land, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> will have to pay cash for such projects. But opponents argue that while <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> needs the bond money, lawmakers who wrote supporting and opposing arguments for the proposal intentionally neglected to mention that the state must repay new bond sales through higher property taxes.
