<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has closed down for its annual weeklong series of spring holidays, including one created by the government this year just to encourage the industrious workforce to let its reputation slide a bit. For many, the annual `` Golden Week'' started Friday, giving them the rare opportunity to take up to nine days off in a row. For others, time off began today, the first of three consecutive official national holidays. April 29, which fell on Friday, has been a holiday for more than 60 years, marking the birthday of the late Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>. After his death Jan. 7, its name was changed to Greenery Day. Constitution Day falls on May 3 and Children's Day on May 5. This year, the government has made May 4 a national holiday also, to encourage more people to take consecutive days off. `` It's different from foreign countries. Japanese generally ca n't take several days of vacation at one time,'' said <PERSON> Reiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomizawa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest travel agency. `` People even used to work every other day during Golden Week until the government made May 4 a holiday this year,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tomizawa </PERSON> said. `` It's just the national character of the Japanese to work hard without vacations.'' But government officials believe the Japanese should devote more time to leisure activities and spend more money on both them and imports in order to reduce the nation's huge trade surplus. Earlier this year, the government instituted a shortened five-day work week every other week for government employees. It is enouraging private business to follow suit. A record 17.7 million Japanese, or 14.7 percent of the population, are gong on trips of more than one night this week, and an all-time high of 365,000 are taking advantage of the high value of the yen to go overseas, according to a survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. The most popular family destinations this year are <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, Guam and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, the bureau said. Young, single `` office ladies'' are turning toward <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the agency said. They usually save money by living at their parents' home, and they have a reputation for being big holiday spenders. Japanese are spending an average $ 2,107 on travel abroad, up 8.7 percent, and $ 394, up 8.9 percent, for domestic travel, according to the agency's study. Many workers, however, see Golden Week as a time to lounge around at home and avoid the jammed highways, hot springs, and mountain resorts. `` It's too crowded and expensive to do anything,'' said <PERSON> Katsuya </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirai </PERSON>, 33, who works in the sales department of a Japanese automaker. `` And it's before our June bonus, so I do n't have any money right now.'' `` I can afford to take the family for a day trip to a safari park near <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuji </LOCATION>,'' he says. `` But my wife says she wants to eat out every night.'' Hotels across <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> report room shortages during the week because of the Japanese influx, especially in popular destinations such as <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and even <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, until recently suffering from a hotel glut. `` To make matters worse, some hotels in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> are becoming disenchanted with tour groups, the mode of travel particularly favored by the Japanese,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keizai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s main economic newspaper. `` They are starting to focus on individual guests, where the profit margins are higher and the noise level is lower.''
