<HEAD>Business Groups Complain About Workers' Insurance Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business representatives contend that American workers would be better off if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> repealed a new law aimed at barring health-insurance discrimination against lower-paid employees. `` We remain skeptical that it does anything to improve or extend coverage of health care,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, a Californian speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday. <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> legislation to revise the law would be an improvement, but that the best course would be outright repeal. `` It will still be a new impediment and disincentive to employers, especially smaller employers, to provide health insurance,'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said. Similar objections were raised by other business representatives who testified before the tax panel. But spokesmen for the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> and the accounting profession leaned toward revising the law, known as Internal Revenue Code Section 89, rather than repealing it. `` Prompt congressional action is needed to alleviate the problems employers are experiencing in complying with Section 89,'' said <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trier </PERSON>, tax legislative counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` We believe the -LRB- revision -RRB- bill represents a major step forward in achieving these goals.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> advocates a complete revision of present law, which he called a complicated mess. The law, enacted in 1986, aims to ensure that tax-deductible health insurance plans do not discriminate in favor of higher-paid employees. The statute requires employers to subject their health plans to complex tests to determine whether they discriminate. Some employers say the complexity, paperwork and cost _ $ 50 per worker, by one estimate _ are so onerous that they will find it easier to drop their health plans rather than try to comply with the law. Business has made repeal or modification of the law a major goal this year. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has heard so many complaints that 300 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members and close to a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have signed bills to repeal the law. Most members of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> have signed the revision bill, whose chief sponsor is Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill. The complaints have been heard by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, too. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> announced Monday that employers would not have to test their health plans for compliance before Oct. 1; the law originally had a Jan. 1, 1989, deadline. The federal government forgoes more than $ 30 billion a year in taxes on the value of employer-financed health coverage. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s bill would eliminate most of the complicated testing by requiring employers to provide to at least 90 percent of their lower-paid workers health insurance costing the employees no more than $ 10 a month for a single plan or no more than $ 25 for family coverage. <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, legislative representative for the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, praised <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s bill but said the labor federation questions whether it would make it possible for working families to qualify for coverage. He recommended that a worker's out-of-pocket spending for medical expenses be limited to $ 3,000 a year and that the $ 25-a-week maximum premium under the bill be reduced. The committee was asked to provide special exemptions for state and local governments, since such employers pay no federal taxes and, thus, receive no tax deduction for the costs of workers' insurance <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, said at least 27 states require workers to pay more than $ 10 a week for a single health policy or more than $ 25 weekly for a family plan. Overall, <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> said, while congressional concern about the $ 30-billion-a-year subsidy for health plans is understandable, `` We believe that the burdens of the law far outweigh the benefits in the public sector.''
