<FIRST>r a PM-Broadcasters-FCCChairman     05-03 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broadcasters-FCC Chairman,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Patrick Performs Swan Song Before Appreciative Audience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> concluded its annual gathering with a rousing call to arms by outgoing <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> to resist government intrusion into radio and TV. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, who led the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s repeal of the `` fairness doctrine'' that required broadcasters to present opposing views of public issues, said Tuesday that broadcasting has a constitutional duty to express opinions. `` You are all members of the press, no less than the editorial boards of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and The Wall Street Journal,'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said. `` We, the members of the public, want to hear what you have to say, we deserve to know your opinions.'' But, he added, `` You are powerful, and for that reason we in government have just cause to fear you.'' At the same time, he said, government has `` no cause to attempt to regulate your speech. Stand firm against any attempt to do so.'' Even though the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> lifted the fairness doctrine from broadcasters in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is almost sure to reinstate it this year, posing a veto fight with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and a likely Supreme Court test. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s speech outlining the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s accomplishments was interrupted a number of times by applause from the broadcasters and exhibitors who descended on this gambling mecca for a four-day meeting. <ORGANIZATION> NAB </ORGANIZATION> said there were a record 50,136 registrants this year, and 709 exhibitors plied a wide range of broadcasting hardware. High-definition television predominated, with more than 22,000 square feet of exhibit space and numerous technical and regulatory panel discussions devoted to the multibillion-dollar television of the future. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> thanked his audience for their `` unflagging support'' of his policies against a hostile <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and non-broadcast media during his six years at the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have tried to foster competition at the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> by lowering barriers to entry, and by permitting broadcasters to compete as freely as those with whom they compete _ namely cable,'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> announced last month he had resigned from the agency, where he has been chairman for the past two years, but would stay on until his replacement is confirmed. The 37-year-old <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> native said he would leave government, but has announced no future plans. In addition to repealing the fairness doctrine, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> during <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s tenure reinstated rules giving broadcasters exclusive rights to programming in their broadcasting areas over cable outlets, he said. He advocated further protection from the cable TV industry through a requirement that cable systems pay for the over-the-air programs they feed to their subscribers. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> noted how the FCC revised the means by which stations renew their licenses to bar sham competitors who just want money to drop their challenges to a station's license. And he noted the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision last year to make sure that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standard for high-definition television will not render obsolete the huge investment TV stations have in current equipment. American industry is racing to adopt standards with which to build an HDTV system and stave off the expected appearance in the next couple of years of foreign-made HDTV VCRs and movies. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said broadcasters still faced many challenges: fiber-optic cable and telephone entry into video programming; competition from foreign media; further loss of audience; the shifting of advertising from video to point of sales.
</TEXT>
