<HEAD>Bush to Use Commencement Speeches to Spell out Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will spell out the conclusions of his wide-ranging foreign policy review in the next few weeks in a series of commencement addresses dealing with <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> relations, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, the White House says. `` Basically it will point out the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> view of the world and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' role in it and our attitude toward other countries,'' White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` There will be some differences with existing policy although the general thrust will not be too different,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` It's not clear to me there will ever be any written reports'' about the review, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` These speeches may in effect be the most definitive enunciation of the results of that review.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is scheduled to give five commencement speeches this month, beginning with a May 12 address at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the topic of that speech will be foreign policy, although it is not clear what the focus will be. A May 21 speech at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> will spell out <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s view of East-West relations and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strategy for dealing with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the spokesman said. Then, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will use a May 24 speech at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, to discuss the strength of <ORGAN