<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Motorcade     05-03 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Motorcade,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Motorcades Tricky Business in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> travels to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, he gets there quicker than <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> but slower than <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. That's because <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has eliminated one link in the trip used by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> _ a fast helicopter ride into <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> from a nearby airport, usually <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>. Instead, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> prefers to travel within <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by motorcade. And that means he must land at the most distant of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s three major airports _ Kennedy Closer-in <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> wo n't accommodate Air Force One, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707. And he ca n't use <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, across the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, for security and national defense reasons. A motorcade trip from <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> would require the president's motorcade to pass through a tunnel under the river, and that would put the chief executive out of radio contact with the rest of the world _ unless special communications cables were laid through the tunnel, deemed by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> not worth the expense or effort So <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has been to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> twice as president, travels through the nation's most populous city entirely by motorcade _ producing monumental traffic tie-ups as he goes. For last Sunday's trip, when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> participated in a re-enactment of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s inauguration 200 years before, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> traveled by motorcade all the way from <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> to Wall Street in lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, a trip of about 35 minutes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision not to use a helicopter to get into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was based on `` his preference to save money,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. `` At a time when we're facing budgetary constraints, it's one way he could have an impact,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said it was not clear how much was really saved by such a step, however. Usually, four helicopters were involved when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> traveled from <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, usually to a helipad at the Battery _ one helicopter for the president and his top aides, one for the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, another for lesser-ranking staff, and a press chopper. At least some of the helicopters had to be flown up from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. However, official motorcades through <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> are, to say it mildly, interesting. They are sometimes chaotic, hectic, frightening, exhilarating _ and always gridlock-forming. As president, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> gets streets barricaded for him along the motorcade route. That presents an unusual sight to anyone familiar with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s usually clogged streets _ block after block of temporarily empty pavement. Of course, side streets and entrance ramps along the way become hopelessly clogged with stopped traffic. As vice president, and as a candidate, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did n't always rate such treatment, and his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> motorcades often had to vie with and fend off other traffic. Sirens and flashing lights seem to have less effect on traffic in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> than in other cities. Cars, buses and cabs frequently dart in and out of the path of non-presidential motorcades. When a motorcade slows down too much, or too much of a gap opens between cars, pedestrians and bicyclists often stream perilously across the street between the gaps. During a campaign visit last spring, a vehicle in then-Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s motorcade struck a cab trying to edge into the flow of traffic, crumpling its side. The motorcade kept moving, the cab driver shaking his fist and hurling epithets. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> motorcades `` usually produce a higher percentage of hand and finger gestures,'' asserts one White House staff member. Is saving the cost of helicopters worth the added cost of more police officers along motorcade routes, and the jangled nerves of those caught in traffic jams? `` You have to try to strike a balance,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. And, he noted, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> only took choppers from the airport into the city _ he still had to travel by motorcade within <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. Although it takes <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> longer than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to get to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> site, he's still a lot swifter than the nation's first president _ whose steps <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> retraced last Sunday. It took <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> a week in 1789 to travel from <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vernon </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> near what is now the nation's capital, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which was then the nation's capital. And he did it by horseback, coach and barge.
</TEXT>
