<HEAD>Explosives-Detection Bill Advances In House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill that would give airlines and airports $ 270 million for devices to detect plastic explosives goes before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee Thursday, after a subcommittee rejected Republican efforts to make airlines pay half the cost. The legislation requires installation of the sophisticated units in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign airports that are considered vulnerable to terrorists. It does the same thing as a <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> order last month, which would have airlines pay the full cost of the units. The bill, passed Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, would take the $ 270 million from an aviation trust fund without budgeting new money. The fund has accumulated more than $ 6 billion in fees collected from airline passengers for airport improvements. Republicans tried to amend the measure to require that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines pay half the cost, but the bill received no opposing votes when it passed with full federal funding for the security devices. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last month ordered airlines to install the sophisticated bomb-detection machines at high-risk airports. Both the order and the legislation call for detection systems such as thermal neutron devices that have been tested by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said Tuesday he expects the first machine to be installed in July at <LOCATION> John </LOCATION> <LOCATION> F. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and the second at an airport in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. He said several more should be in place before the end of the year. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> last week meeting with officials of other governments about aviation security as a result of the Dec. 21 bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> that killed 270 people. He said the administration feels the airlines should pay for additional security, using revenue from security fees collected with passengers' tickets. The legislation would provide up to 100 percent grants to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines and airports which would own, operate and maintain the detection units expected to cost about $ 1 million each. The airline grants also would cover installation in high-risk foreign airports. Subcommittee chairman Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Minn </LOCATION>., argued that the government should pay for the devices that would examine checked-in baggage because the government, not airlines, has been the target of terrorists Other governments will be paying for security units used by their airlines, which would put them at a competitive advantage, <PERSON> Oberstar </PERSON> said. Republicans argued that airlines have always paid for security equipment at airports, and the subsidy could lead to other moves to use federal money to help airlines.
