<HEAD>Air Force Gives More Details on B-2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> general has offered a surprising amount of detail about the new B-2 stealth bomber, disclosing it will have great range, an ability to land almost anywhere and a payload of 25 tons of bombs. The plane's capabilities will be such that had the B-2 been available in 1986, when <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> bombers attacked <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, `` just three to four B-2s could have done the job direct from stateside bases,'' said Gen. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>. More than 100 combat and support aircraft from the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> were used for that bombing mission. The B-2 would require at most two tankers to fuel it during the mission, <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>, in making his revelations last weekend, said little about the cost of the B-2 or of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>'s recent budget decision to postpone the start of production by a full year But he asserted to a meeting of aviation reporters in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, that the B-2 was nothing less than a `` quantum leap into the 21st century'' that was essential to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future strength, thanks to its ability to slip behind enemy lines without being detected on radar. <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> appeared before the reporters on Saturday. A text of his remarks was released later at the Pentagon. Not only is the B-2 destined to become a key part of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s nuclear arsenal, but it offers a capability to deliver conventional weapons that is unmatched among manned bombers, <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> said The Libyan bombing raid `` could have been conducted with greater tactical surprise and vastly less risk of life,'' he said. Among <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON>'s disclosures:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ The B-2 will be capable of flying more than 6,000 nautical miles _ or 6,900 statute miles _ without refueling With one mid-air refueling, it will be able to fly more than 10,000 nautical miles or 11,500 statute miles. _ The plane will have a maximum takeoff weight of more than 350,000 pounds and will be able to carry up to 50,000 pounds of either nuclear or conventional bombs Specifically, it will be able to carry 16 large nuclear weapons, 20 smaller nuclear bombs, or up to 80 conventional 500-pound bombs. The B-52, the mainstay strategic bomber, carries 60,000 tons of bombs. _ The plane is designed to operate with minimal support equipment and can land on any runway that's just 40 feet wide, meaning `` it can operate from any airfield that can handle a 727 commercial airliner. `` With one air refueling, operating from just four bases _ two stateside and two overseas _ the B-2 could cover any point on the world's land mass on a non-stop radius mission carrying a full conventional payload,'' <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> said. `` Those possibilities could deter a great deal of adventurism.'' <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> also announced the first flight of the B-2 would probably occur in about two months, but only when the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> was convinced the plane was ready. The B-2, built primarily by <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is a futuristic-looking gray-and black `` flying wing'' designed to evade enemy radar and deliver nuclear weapons. It resembles a huge, tailless manta ray, with wide sweeping wings blending smoothly into a rounded cockpit and engine housings on the top side. The stealth gets its name from the claim that it will be extremely difficult to detect by enemy radar, due to the extensive use of exotic composite materials; its lack of sharp surface angles; and a cross-section that offers a very small profile to radar. Before <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>'s decision to slow production, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had estimated 132 of the planes would cost $ 68.1 billion. Even if money spent on research and development is set aside, that amounts to production costs of $ 305 million per plane.
