<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elections for borough offices never draw long lines at the voting booth, but this year's contests set a new standard for apathy. Candidates outnumbered voters in Monday's election, when only 21 people voted for the 22 candidates. Nearly all the voters were either running for office or were relatives of the candidates. Every two years, the borough, which administers the center of the southwestern <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> town, stages elections that generate little opposition or interest. No political affiliations are noted on the ballot. The positions include board of tax review, zoning commission, fire inspector, tax assessor and tax collector. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>, a candidate for burgess, a borough council, said a persistent drizzle may have kept the throngs home this week. The winners? Everyone. Even Clerk <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>, who forgot to put her name on the ballot, kept her post. She received 13 write-in votes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House budget document usually makes for dry reading, but it's well-thumbed this year. Hidden among thousands of items are several gags. On page 243, between spending for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> and salaries for state employees, are 15 sports trivia questions. A word jumble asking arcane questions is on another page. On the cover, a newspaper cartoon shows a threadbare pauper examining his empty pockets _ a visual reference to the no-frills spending plan the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved Monday. `` There's not enough in there to take seriously. It's what's not in there that's got everybody upset,'' said Appropriations Chairman T.K. <PERSON> Wetherell </PERSON>. `` I thought everybody would read it this year for a change.'' The $ 22.7 billion spending plan also has buried in it an offer of $ 10 and a free turkey dinner to the first member of the capital press corps who finds it. The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, was the winner but declined the reward.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What's in a name? In this rapidly developing community, there're omelette makings for some. Huevos -LRB- Egg -RRB- Circle and Jamon -LRB- Ham -RRB- Lane are some of the street names in the same neighborhood of <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Viejo </ORGANIZATION>, which has grown from scratch to 75,000 people in 23 years. The <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> heritage of the area has inspired some fanciful names for places and streets. The original <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Viejo </ORGANIZATION> was established under a Spanish land grant. `` The story was told that when they decided to have a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> theme for the community _ <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> walls, Franciscan bells, Spanish-themed architecture _ they decided all streets would have Spanish names,'' said <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetzel </PERSON>, director of corporate communications for the <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Viejo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, professor of <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> at <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fullerton </ORGANIZATION>, said some of the names are silly. `` Unfortunately people do n't often have a clear sense of what it means to use another language, so they use it impressionistically,'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said. `` It just sounds ` Spanishy.' The other thing is that people have a tendency to seek the exotic, and foreign names are exotic.'' The race to name streets included one called <LOCATION> Rabida </LOCATION>, -LRB- rabid -RRB-. Other names: Via Fabricante -LRB- Manufacturer Street -RRB-, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charco </LOCATION> -LRB- The Puddle, near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCA