is `` an outstanding human being ... but his public service has been in law enforcement,'' said <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>. `` He is better suited for deputy drug czar or deputy <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> director, and not as chief policy maker on civil rights enforcement in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in light of no litigatory experience or policy experience, unless you're making the assumption that anybody with black skin has the qualifications,'' said <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, who is black. `` I do n't make that assumption and I find it offensive when people do make that assumption.'' <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> lawyer, has been an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, sheriff of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and the chief executive for that county. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said the assistant attorney general position `` is a law enforcement job and needs someone with a law enforcement background and management background.'' Among those supporting <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> are some members of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> and the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, a black Democrat from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, said a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> fight by civil rights groups to block the <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> nomination `` would be a useless one, maybe even counterproductive.'' He invited members of the caucus to meet informally with <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> on Tuesday afternoon.