<HEAD>20 Years After, Zapites Brace Again For A `Happening'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Folks in Zap still shudder when they recall the day 20 years ago when 2,000 drunken college students rioted on Main Street and set a bonfire, causing $ 3,000 in damage. Saturday, a new generation of students plan a sequel. But <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlegel </PERSON>, organizer of Zip to Zap II, promises a more sedate celebration, one she hopes can erase hard feelings that have festered in the town of 300 people since 1969. `` I want to show them that people are different and things like this can work out,'' said the 21-year-old junior at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION>. `` We are mending fences in a way.'' The school newspaper, The Spectrum, organized the first Zip to Zap for a spring fling. But chaos erupted that May day and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was called in to disperse the rowdy students. Although many Zap townspeople are apprehensive about college students again invading the quiet hamlet, <PERSON> Schlegel </PERSON>, the editor of The Spectrum, believes Zip to Zap II not only will restore her newspaper's image. It also will provide an economic boon to the town about 90 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION>. `` It all started as a Spectrum picnic in Zap 20 years ago,'' she said. `` We have gotten a bad rap from it, and I just want to show that things can work out. People can get together in a gathering and it does n't have to be a disaster. ... I do n't think the drinking is the same as it was 20 years ago.'' <PERSON> Schlegel </PERSON> harbors no fears that Zip to <PERSON> Zap </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> will get out of control, calling today's college students more mature and less radical than their 1960s' counterparts. `` I do n't think we are going to be starting street fires,'' she said. <PERSON> Schlegel </PERSON> expects up to 1,000 students from campuses across <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> to descend on Zap for 11 hours of free rock' n' roll plus some volleyball games. Six bands have volunteered for the show, which starts at 1 p.m. in a pasture near the town, she said. Zap is gearing up to handle 2,000 people, said <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a civic organization with 20 active members. <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON>, 29, barely remembers the May 10, 1969, event, when she was living with her family in nearby <LOCATION> Beulah </LOCATION>, but said: `` Everybody was scared, seeing it on television.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Mercer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> expects to have about 15 officers in Zap on Saturday and <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> officers also will be around, Deputy Sheriff <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Nodland </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We really do n't foresee that ... it is going to get out of hand,'' he said. Townspeople in Zap are split on whether another batch of college revelers should even be let into town, <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> said. Some want the town barricaded. `` They harbor the bad memories,'' she said. She does n't expect a repeat of the disturbance but remains cautious. `` When people are intoxicated, moods swing. If we knew this was an annual event, we would know what to prepare for. But with a 20-year gap in it, it leaves anything and everything up in the air,'' <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> said. The town is hoping to cash in, however. At least seven portable food stands will be set up, <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> said. And the <ORGANIZATION> Zap </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> had 500 souvenir T-shirts printed with the message: `` I Zipped to Zap and had a blast.''
