<HEAD>ABA Says no Deal with Thornburgh on Judicial Screening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> misstated the position of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> when he said its judicial screening panel has agreed to stop considering the political and ideological views of candidates for the federal bench, say two leaders of the organization. <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Raven </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION>, both disagreed Tuesday with <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s description of what has been produced by discussions with the attorney general about judicial screening. The issue is sensitive because <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s choice to be deputy attorney general, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiske </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, could face tough questioning by conservative senators about the job he did running the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> screening committee. Also, there are some 50 vacancies on the federal bench. The two <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> officials said there is no agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> said the panel has only `` expressed a willingness'' in discussions with <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> to delete a clause from the guidelines that says political views and ideology are not considered `` except to the extent that they may bear upon the other factors'' considered by the screening panel. `` I do n't think we have reached any agreement on the exact language'' of any change to be made, <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> said. Earlier Tuesday, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> had told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> committee during this decade has begun assessing the `` ideological or political views of prospective nominees.'' As a result of discussions, the attorney general said, the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> will `` restrict their examination and assessment only to those areas where they have special expertise.'' `` We are pleased that the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> standing committee has seen fit to withdraw from an area not only contentious but in my view improper for their consideration _ that is to say the political and ideological views of the prospective nominees,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>, a special assistant to <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, said that he understood the agreement was based on an `` exchange of letters'' last week following `` personal discussions between <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> leaders and top aides to the attorney general.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to return to pre-1979 language that said `` The committee does not attempt to investigate or report on political or ideological matters with respect to the prospective nominee.'' <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> said the only letter he is aware of was one he wrote April 4 to the attorney general summarizing their conversation that day. <PERSON> Fiske </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s choice for his deputy, has not been formally nominated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. But Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, charged in an April 17 letter to the president that <PERSON> Fiske </PERSON> shared the names of prospective nominees with liberal groups, `` thus enabling those groups to target conservative candidates even before their nominations were made public.'' At Tuesday's hearing, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> resulted `` through the efforts largely of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiske </PERSON>.'' His remark appeared calculated to mollify <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> and other conservatives. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> said he had discussed the issue and others with <PERSON> Fiske </PERSON> but `` I did n't realize I was in any negotiation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> has been accused by liberals and conservatives of considering political views when rating a nominee's qualifications for the judiciary. The rating is delivered during <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation hearings. Charges from conservatives that the process was being politicized surfaced in 1987 after the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> committee disclosed that four of its 15 members dissented from a recommendation that <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> was qualified to sit on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in both political parties have expressed dissatisfaction with the process. Some senators have called for the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> committee to reveal the sources of its information about candidates and how each member voted on a nominee. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is considering a legal claim that the Federal Advisory Commission Act requires the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> panel to meet in public. Such a requirement, the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> says, would inhibit its ability to gather information from professional peers of judicial candidates.
