<HEAD>With PM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural center in the provincial city of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, attacked 26 times by radical students since 1981, will be moved and temporarily closed, news reports said today. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> McLoughlin </PERSON> said the center that he directs would close May 10 to move to an as yet undetermined location, according to <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION>, the South Korean news agency. But officials at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> denied that the center, 180 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, would close even temporarily. A spokesman said the question of a new location was still under study in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been considering a move since early this year after repeated attacks by radical students yelling anti-U.S. slogans and hurling firebombs and rocks. Anti-U.S. sentiment is relatively high in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> because of the bloody military suppression of pro-democracy civil uprising there in May 1980. About 200 people were killed and more than 1,000 others injured in the nine-day uprising. Many opposition and dissident figures claim the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> shares responsibility for the bloodshed by acquiescing to a South Korean government plan to ruthlessly quell the uprising. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> denies the charges.
