<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher Reaches 10th Anniversary Of Election That Brought Her
To Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years ago today an election swept Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to power, and she continues to prevail over a divided opposition despite a recent poll indicating a lot of voters are fed up with her. There was no word today from 10 Downing St. of any special events to mark the anniversary, which television, radio, newspapers and magazines have marked with numerous programs and articles in recent weeks. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, 63, is the century's longest continuously serving British prime minister and the headquarters of her <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has printed a glossy booklet called `` The First 10 Years'' glowing with praise for her. She is now midway through her third term following Conservative victories in the 1983 and 1987 general elections. Despite indications of growing dislike among many voters of her strong-willed personality and right-wing policies, she has said she plans to try for a fourth term. A series of polls released this week indicate most Britons want Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to step down soon and think her right-wing revolution has gone too far. But while they said they do n't like her, the likelihood is they will go on voting for her because they respect the woman who has always led what The Economist weekly calls a `` reluctant nation.'' The Economist noted, for example, that virtually throughout Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s tenure, Gallup soundings have never registered more than 24 percent support for a basic <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> doctrine: tax cuts rather than increased state spending, particularly on welfare. The soundings published Sunday and Tuesday are part of a nationwide assessment of `` Thatcherism'' prompted by the anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s 1979 election triumph over Prime Minister <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Callaghan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> took office the following day, May 4. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first woman prime minister had been elected by a nation weary of strikes and inflation and yearning for strong government to reverse national decline In the opinion polls, she scored high for qualities such as determination and courage. Her most popular policies, the polls showed, are curbing the trade unions and allowing public housing tenants to buy their homes. Britons see their country as having gained respect abroad, while becoming a more aggressive, violent and selfish society. A leader who set out to wipe out socialism from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> also appears in most soundings to be presiding over a nation that has not taken her message to its heart. A Market and <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> poll published Tuesday in The Independent, a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> daily, showed only 30 percent support for the notion that `` private interests and a free market economy should dominate.'' According to a <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> poll in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s liberal Observer newspaper, 58 percent think 10 years of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> is enough. And 66 percent agreed with the statement, `` Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has gone too far in her policies.'' But just 7 percent of the 1,040 voters questioned by <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> actually expected Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to resign within the next few years. The soundings also showed a generally subdued reckoning by voters of the <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> revolution. For example, just 37 percent of the 1,001 voters questioned by Gallup for the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> said they thought that overall <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is now a better place to live in. And while 67 percent dislike Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> personally, 63 percent respect her. The polls also showed most Britons think the country has become more violent, citing soccer hooliganism and street crime. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who has won big majorities of around 42 percent of the vote while the left-of-center is split, continues to be the party leader most think would be the best prime minister. And when it comes to casting a vote, she ends the first 10 years with 2 to 3 point lead over Labor in most soundings.
