<DATELINE>LOWDEN, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A great horned owl swooped down and scratched the face of a 6-year-old boy riding a bicycle, and doctors fear he may lose his left eye. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON> underwent several hours of surgery at <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after Friday's attack, and doctors told his family a decision will be made this week whether they can save the eye. The youngster was listed in fair condition Tuesday. A family friend, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberholser </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> was riding his bike near his home in <LOCATION> Lowden </LOCATION>, an eastern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> town of 700 people, when the owl struck. `` The owl hit him right in the face and a talon hit him directly in the eye,'' Ms. <PERSON> Oberholser </PERSON> said. `` It made a T-shaped cut. Originally, I do n't think anyone thought they could save the eye, but yesterday they said he could see light through it.'' <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> said the attack probably was made by a female owl protecting her young. `` We ca n't verify it, but we assume there was a baby owl on the ground when the youngster went by on the sidewalk,'' he said. `` Whenever young are around, animals become very protective. But I've never heard of great horned owls attacking someone to this extent.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said authorities destroyed both owl parents, not knowing which one attacked and fearing the bird might attack again. He also said officials were forced to destroy the offspring. Great horned owls, named for their large ear tufts, are protected birds but are not considered endangered or threatened.
