<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion     05-03 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Use Poems, Visuals to Illustrate Cold Fusion Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Physicists are resorting to poems and visual aids like a blade of grass to help illustrate the problems they found in two chemists' claim of achieving nuclear fusion in a jar. `` Tens of millions of dollars are at stake, dear sister and brother, because one scientist put a thermometer in one place instead of the other,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyerhof </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> recited to reporters Tuesday at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Meyerhof said the excess heat that the researchers attribute to cold fusion was caused instead by incorrect temperature measurements. He said the device the researchers used failed to distribute temperature evenly. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> chemist <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and his collaborator, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southampton </ORGANIZATION>, startled the world March 23 by announcing they had achieved fusion at room temperature. Most efforts to achieve fusion, the nuclear reaction that powers the sun, have required staggeringly high temperatures. Cold fusion could open the door to a clean, cheap and virtually unlimited source of energy. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> said they did it by placing palladium and platinum electrodes in a flask of deuterium oxide, or heavy water, and applying electric current. Deuterium is a heavier isotope, or cousin, of ordinary hydrogen. The researchers claimed the nuclei of the deuterium atoms fused, releasing neutrons and producing four times more heat than invested. But in an informal show of hands, the scientists on a panel at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> meeting Tuesday voted 8-1 that they were 95 percent confident the excess heat was not produced by nuclear fusion. However, the panel also voted 6-3 against ruling out that experiments in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and elsewhere had produced neutrons. `` The bottom line is we see nothing anomalous in any of their experiments and have identified what we believe are serious errors in the experiment,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Koonin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Koonin </PERSON> was part of a three-member <ORGANIZATION> Caltech </ORGANIZATION> team that tried to duplicate the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> experiments. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Skiff </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> physicist, said that after attempting to duplicate the results for two weeks he was certain cold fusion had not taken place. `` It appears the work by <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> is very sloppy,'' Skiff said. `` They should have presented their research in the scientific community before going public with it,'' he said. `` The public debate on this matter makes science look bad because of the complicated process of verification.'' One of the few physicists to hold out hope for cold fusion, <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, said his experiments had produced neutrons but at a level much lower than the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> experiment claimed. Cold fusion needs further study, but is only a little understood effect, he said. He used a blade of grass to illustrate his point. `` I do n't think it will grow into a tree,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` I think it will grow into a pleasant little flower in the garden of physics.'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleishmann </PERSON> have not responded in detail to this week's criticism in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> But <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> did say: `` The absence of neutrons does not concern us in the slightest. We could n't be happier. We and other scientists will soon tell them why this is so.'' <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> officials also defended the research. `` It's difficult for me to believe people of <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>' and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>'s caliber could forget to put a thermometer in the right place or something basic like stirring,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brophy </PERSON>, the university's vice president for research. `` It does n't shake my confidence. It's never nice to be criticized. However, when you're out in front, the wind can be cool sometimes.
</TEXT>
