 Thunderstorms moved across northern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> today, dumping heavy rain and hail, while Midwesterners awoke to another chilly morning. The most severe thunderstorms were near <LOCATION> Ranger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where funnel clouds were spotted Tuesday night. The town is about 70 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. Baseball-sized hail fell near the town, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Heavy wind blew over two semi-trailer trucks on Interstate 20 near Ranger, authorities said. Also in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, thunderstorm winds destroyed a barn in northern <LOCATION> Parker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, tore off a roof of a country club and overturned several mobile homes in <LOCATION> Comanche </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Winds were recorded up to 80 mph. Thunderstorms also were over southern <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and central <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. Rain showers developed from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to central <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, and showers fell over the lower Great Lakes region. <LOCATION> Waco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, had more than an inch of rain in the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT, while Limestone, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> each recorded nearly two-thirds of an inch in the same period. A high pressure system with a cold air mass was centered over northern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, creating chilly temperatures from the upper and middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> across the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the Appalachians. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s northern mountains had a fros