<HEAD>Emigration Highest Since 1979, But Less Bound for Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in April soared to its highest level in 10 years, according to figures released today by an agency that helps to resettle the emigrants. However, the share of those bound for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> fell to a new low. <PERSON> Regina </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucault </PERSON>, spokeswoman of the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migration </ORGANIZATION>, said 4,129 Jews arrived at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> transit center from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in April, compared with 3,893 in March. Only 87 of them, or 2.1 percent, said they wanted to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Most were heading for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said Ms. <PERSON> Boucault </PERSON>. Last year the share of Soviet Jews bound for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was still 7.1 percent. In 1987, before the Palestinian uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> strip it was as high as 24.4 percent. Since the beginning of 1989, 12,864 Jews have left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, according to ICM figures. On Tuesday, the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Soviet Jewry reported an emigration total of 4,557 Jews for April. The ICM figures only account for those Soviet Jews who pass through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. The program for Jewish emigration from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began in 1971 and reached a peak in 1979 when 51,328 were allowed to leave the country. This dropped sharply when <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> chilled East-West relations.
