<HEAD>Clash Over Anti-Pollution Plan Brings Down Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: ADDs one graf to UPDATE with representation in Dutch parliament.
^By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Disagreement over a multibillion-dollar plan to clean up the country's environment has brought down the 7-year-old center-right government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Ruud </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>. The Christian Democrat on Tuesday announced the resignation of his Cabinet after a right-wing junior partner objected to his proposal to end $ 325 million in income tax deductions for people who drive their cars to work. Political observers predicted <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON> would form a coalition with the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, second only to the Christian Democrats in the number of parliamentary seats it holds. <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>' action headed off a possible motion of no confidence threatened by the junior coalition partner, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>. `` Environmental policy certainly needs to be paid for, but why just by those who live at some distance from their jobs?'' said <PERSON> Joris </PERSON> <PERSON> Voorhoeve </PERSON>, the right-wing party's leader in the 150-seat Parliament. <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>' announcement came at the end of a tense 7 -LCB- - hour parliamentary debate on a $ 3.65 billion government plan to cut pollution of the country's atmosphere to 30 percent of current levels by the year 2010 `` If only we could motivate one in ten -LRB- car-driving commuters -RRB- to change their habits ... that would have a very large effect on the congestion, on mobility, on the environment,'' <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON> said. The crisis also reflected years of irritation among Voorhoeve's party at steadily losing decision-making power to the charismatic <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>, who enjoys immense popularity in this nation of 14.6 million people The 49-year-old prime minister said he planned to meet with Queen <PERSON> Beatrix </PERSON> today `` to offer the resignation of all the ministers'' in the Cabinet. In Dutch constitutional practice, the government will continue in office with caretaker status until early elections later this year. After the elections, it can take several months until a new government is formed. Parliamentary elections had been scheduled for May 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have been in virtually every postwar Dutch government and are likely to be the centerpiece of the next one. Never in postwar Dutch history has a political party garnered sufficient votes to govern alone. The 8-year-old <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON> government has aimed to cut the $ 13 billion budget deficit and 11 percent unemployment rate. In recent months, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has accused <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON>' party of backing off from a pledge to cut corporate and private taxes and slash social security, education and health care outlays. But the issue that prompted the government's resignation was a <PERSON> Lubbers </PERSON> proposal to end the tax break for car-driving commuters in a bid to reduce car exhaust fumes and highway congestion by forcing motorists to take mass transit. Voorhoeve also objected to a proposed $ 270 million increase in the tax on diesel fuel that would mainly hit the trucking industry, one of the mainstays of the Dutch economy. Under the anti-pollution plan, farmers also would have to pay toward cleaning up deposits of manure produced by their livestock, deposits that contribute to acid rain. The plan would set levies for polluting industries and contain proposals for cleaning up hundreds of toxic waste dumps. Voorhoeve's move to topple the government had the support of the 52-seat <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> opposition, and the 54 <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> would not have been able to hold off a no-confidence vote. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has 27 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, while 12 seats are held by three opposition parties and five seats by three right-wing parties that are generally supportive of the government.
