<HEAD>Sihanouk Sets Conditions to Return to Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the Vietnamese troop pullout from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is independently confirmed and the constitution rewritten to his satisfaction, Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> says he will return home as head of state. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, leader of the guerrilla coalition resisting the Vietnamese-backed government, said today that he expects to decide before November if his conditions have been met. He made the comments at a news conference on the second day of peace talks in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>. An international commission, to be named at a conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on July 24-25, must first make sure the Vietnamese withdrawal is genuine, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has promised to pull out its remaining troops by Sept. 30. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s other demands include a four-party interim government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> until elections can be held, and constitutional guarantees for a multiparty political system. The proposed interim administration would include the present Cambodian government of Premier <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s non-communist followers, anti-communists from former Premier Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> has been trying to persuade <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> to abandon the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and return home as head of the the government he headed until being ousted in 1970. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGAN