<HEAD>Pope Visits Depressed Mining Region Of Zambia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KITWE, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> traveled today to the depressed <LOCATION> Copperbelt </LOCATION> mining region of central <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s poorest and most indebted nations. The pope conducted a two-hour, open-air Mass at an abandoned airport at <LOCATION> Kitwe </LOCATION>, the second-largest city in this southern African nation of 7.5 million people, three-fourths of whom are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>. In the near distance, behind the Papal podium, smoke stacks at a copper smelting plant billowed black smoke into clear tropical skies. Church choirs sang hymns to the throb of African tribal drums as the pontiff, in an open `` popemobile'' rode through a crowd of 100,000 pilgrims. A hymn, written for the Mass in the local <PERSON> Bemba </PERSON> dialect, described the pope as `` our hero.'' With arms outstretched, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> blessed groups of women chanting and ululating, a traditional means of expressing joy. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, his face reddened by the tropical sun, paid tribute to white priests who set up the first Roman Catholic missions in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> nearly 100 years ago. Today, there are 1.7 million Catholics in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. Tens of thousands of pilgrims, mainly from northern districts of this nation, waved yellow-and-white <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> flags and wore sari-like cloths emblazoned with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s portrait. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Copperbelt </LOCATION> diocese of <LOCATION> Ndola </LOCATION> that covers <LOCATION> Kitwe </LOCATION> said in a brief welcoming statement that the pope is visiting the mining region at a time of economic hardships. The fall in world copper prices left <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> with `` an enormous national debt,'' severe unemployment and social problems, he said. Copper prices slumped in the 1970s. Current foreign debt of $ 5 billion drains about two-fifths of all export income, 90 percent of which is derived from sales of copper. On his arrival in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> on Tuesday, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> lashed out at white-ruled <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s system of apartheid or racial separation, describing it as an unacceptable system. Zambian President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON>, in his welcoming speech, also assailed apartheid and said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s visit would strengthen <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>'s resolve to work for peace in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` in a spirit of dialogue and reconciliation and not confrontation.'' <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON>, 65, is chairman of the African Frontline States, a grouping of six black countries spearheading efforts to end apartheid. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the main guerrilla-backed movement fighting <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s government, have said they would like to meet the pope while he is in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s external headquarters. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials said no talks were planned, but they did not rule out the prospect of an informal meeting. The pope is on the third leg of a four-nation tour of African and <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> states. He leaves <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> on Thursday for neighboring <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION>.
