<HEAD>Colleagues of Slain Activist Say Suspicion Falls On Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Colleagues of slain anti-apartheid activist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> today offered a reward for the arrest of his killers and advised police officials to look within their own ranks for suspects. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, a university lecturer and outspoken critic of the government's policy of detention without trial, was shot outside his home Monday by an assailant in a passing car who fired a shotgun from close range. Also today, six mortar bombs were fired at an army radar installation near the border with <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, damaging living quarters but causing no injuries. Regarding <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, police have released sketches of three unidentified white men suspected of involvement in the killing and have offered a $ 4,000 reward for information leading to arrests. Today, the University of the Witwatersand, where <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> taught anthropology, offered an additional $ 4,000 reward. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Charleton </PERSON>, the chief administrator of the multiracial university, said it was `` deeply disquieting'' that police had made no arrests in connection with a series of previous attacks and vandalism aimed at staff and students. Anti-apartheid activists who worked with <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> announced at a news conference that his funeral would held Saturday. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, a prominent human rights advocate, called for an investigation into the possible existence of death squads formed to kill government opponents. `` There may be no more profitable place to start such an investigation than within the ranks of the police themselves,'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. `` This is the body which has the expertise, the information and the wherewithal to carry out such acts so professionally.'' <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Valli </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosa </PERSON>, a leader of the banned <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA