<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A white businessman tied a black farm laborer to the back of his truck and dragged him more than half a mile on dirt and tar roads until he died, a witness testified at a murder trial. The witness, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that his employer, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON>, 53, tied laborer <PERSON> Molefe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tholi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nzima </PERSON> by the neck to the tow bar of his truck. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON> said his employer then drove the truck through water, down a dirt road and along a paved road until he swung onto his own property, where the victim's head slammed into a cement block. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON> testified in <LOCATION> Witbank </LOCATION>, east of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, on Tuesday. He said that on Nov. 18, 1987, he and <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON> were looking for someone who had been stealing chickens from <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON>'s farm in <LOCATION> Ogies </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Witbank </LOCATION>, and had received permission from a white neighbor to question his laborers. <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON> threatened a woman at <LOCATION> Nzima </LOCATION>'s house with a gun, then tied <PERSON> Nzima </PERSON>'s arms, body and legs with nylon rope, winding the rope four times around the man's neck before attaching him to the tow bar, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON> said. After <PERSON> Nzima </PERSON>'s head hit the block, <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON> poured water on the victim to revive him. But <PERSON> Nzima </PERSON> muttered something and died, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nzima </PERSON>'s bloodied body was taken to a police station. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rensburg </PERSON> said <PERSON