<HEAD>Chemical Fire Sends 19 to Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire at a high-tech company sent an orange-brown cloud of poisonous gas mushrooming into the sky, forcing an evacuation and sending 19 people to hospitals. Those taken to three hospitals from Tuesday's accident at <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dielectrics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> complained of burning lungs and skin and shortness of breath. Hospital officials said no one was seriously injured and most were released Tuesday night. More than 500 workers were evacuated from nearby businesses when a dried resin containing the chemical bromine ignited in a ventilation pipe and produced highly toxic hydrogen bromide gas, officials said. The smoke from the fire contained nitrogen cyanide, bromide, and carbon monoxide, officials said. `` You just go down your bad-news list and you'll find all these substances there,'' said Inspector <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON>. `` The materials can be deadly, depending on the combination of gases.'' Advanced Dielectrics manufactures electronic circuit boards. The fire was the second in as many days at a high-tech firm in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, which is about 30 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. A blaze on Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Trend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> sent 13 employees of a neighboring firm to the hospital when a solvent combined with hydrogen peroxide and ignited. All 13 were treated and released at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>.
