<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the nation. April 27 <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> -LRB- Ariz. -RRB- Citizen on abortion: The activists are so positive about abortion. They hide behind their chosen `` pro'' words, protected against doubts. Pro-choice. Pro-life. Caught between two extremes that have split the nation in a moral civil war are the majority of thinking Americans, fed up with simplistic shock rhetoric and self-serving doublespeak. Their pro-word is protest. ... Pro-abortion groups warn of `` back-alley deaths'' by abortion butchers if abortion is outlawed. They beg sympathy for the poor unwed mother or rape victim for whom an abortion is the difference between life and death of hope and opportunity. At the other extreme are the anti-abortion marchers who shock with pictures of well-advanced fetuses. They describe women who have abortions as murderers, and compare 1.6 million abortions each year to history's most appalling genocide. Both sides tell sophisticated lies. If the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> allowed the states to decide ..., there would be no need for back alley deaths. ... The Missouri law being reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> does n't outlaw abortion It restricts state support. Most abortions are done in private clinics. And most women who obtain abortions are not rape victims, nor are they poor. The implication that some see abortion as a convenient birth control of last resort is morally repugnant, and belies the stereotype favored by pro-abortion propaganda. But equally unjust is the `` abortion on demand'' cliche that justifies state interference to halt alleged `` casual carelessness'' with human life and let government make our moral decisions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
