 April 29 The Journal, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ulm </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, on the USS Iowa: The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has acted properly in convening a board of inquiry into the explosion aboard the USS Iowa that claimed the lives of 47 seamen. ... While we may never learn the cause of the disaster, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has acted wisely, we believe, in imposing a moratorium on the firing of all its 16-inch guns. It is now up to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to go one step more and conduct a thorough review of the need to retain these old ships like the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> in service. What we have here is World War I technology aboard a World War II ship attempting to defend a nation headed into the 21st century. The USS Iowa and its sister ships are nearing the half-century mark. The technology of those 16-inch guns requires sailors to hand carry 110-pound silk bags of gunpowder to load the guns. We do not question the unmatched capacity for sustained firepower that these ships can deliver, but the question should be asked if maybe they were better suited for helping contain brushfire wars in various parts of the globe and be replaced for general combat. For the billions of dollars we spend on defense, we think it's time we think about retiring aging battleships that present a risk of life for our own servicemen
