<HEAD>Third Incident of Food Tampering Reported in Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The third incident of food tampering in less than a week has surfaced in central Illinois, as pinlike objects were found in vending machine candy, authorities said today. A shoe-store employee at <LOCATION> Hickory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mall </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Forsyth </LOCATION>, just north of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, bit into a piece of candy and cut his mouth on a sharp object Tuesday, said Sgt. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's police. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentry </PERSON>, 26, spit the candy into a sink, <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said. After waiting on customers he looked back into the sink and found metal that could have been `` a broken-off straight pin or needle,'' <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said. A co-worker later found another pinlike object in a piece of the candy-coated peanuts, <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said. Seven machines in the mall that serve up handfuls of the candy were locked up pending investigation, <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, investigators say they believe that pins reportedly found in <LOCATION> Heinz </LOCATION> baby food jars in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> are isolated incidents. The company's baby food was removed from store shelves in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> Tuesday after a complaint Monday night. <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> grocers returned <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> baby products to their shelves Tuesday after an incident of food tampering was reported there last week. Nobody was hurt in either baby food case. Police in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, about 35 miles east of <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, said Monday that authorities had no objections to restocking because there was no evidence the tampering occurred at the point of production. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, a division of H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the criminal investigation in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> is continuing, as tampering is a federal crime. There is a `` 99-to-one'' chance that the <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> complaint will be found to be isolated and a `` copy-cat'' of tampering cases in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> U.S.A. </PERSON> has no connection to the <LOCATION> Heinz </LOCATION> company affected by tampering in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, where some 300 cases of contamination were reported, including food found with glass shards, razor blades and caustic soda.
