ting with Thai Prime Minister <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> <PERSON> Choonhavan </PERSON> and also stressed the importance the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> places on protection of copyrights _ perhaps the only major friction in otherwise strong relations between the two countries. Earlier this year, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s major export market, denied the country $ 165 million in duty-free exports. The action was taken after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> complained the Thais had failed to honor intellectual property rights, for instance copying patented drugs. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is weighing whether to further blunt Thai exports by imposing additional trade restrictions. Thai government spokesman <PERSON> Suvit </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoadmanee </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> as telling <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not take drastic action on the issue because overall relations, including anti-narcotics cooperation, were good. He noted that most recent negotiations had gone well. <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Suvit </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should regard <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> as a `` springboard'' for trade with <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and noted there was room for increases in trade and joint ventures between <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also conferred with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Siddhi </PERSON> <PERSON> Savetsila </PERSON> and had an audience with King <PERSON> Bhumibol </PERSON> <PERSON> Adulyadej </PERSON>. The vice president and his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, were to be guests at a banquet tonight. While <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> met with the prime minister, a half-dozen university students attempted to hand to the vice president an open letter protesting any implementation of further restrictions, claiming it would amount to `` overt intervention of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s internal affairs. Thai security kept the students from entering <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> were meeting, and the students circulated the letter among reporters and others. Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Pong </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarasin </PERSON> said he was `` more relaxed than 30 days ago after having received reports about the latest status of negotiations on trade-related issues.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> arrived here from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. He leaves Thursday for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> where he will monitor clean-up efforts from the March 24 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> oil spill in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> met with Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> during a visit designed to strengthen ties between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the island republic. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said Tuesday's meeting with <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was fruitful and the two discussed `` every single issue I can imagine.'' He said he was impressed by <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s `` economic miracle ... and booming economy.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also saw <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chok </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s defense minister and deputy prime minister. At that session, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> raised the subject of the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> government's restrictions on the circulation of the U.S.-owned <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and Far Eastern Economic Review, according to <PERSON> Goh </PERSON>'s private secretary, <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jee </PERSON> <PERSON> Say </PERSON>. `` I did bring this up,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said afterward. `` We have a difference of opinion on this ... We still hope that they will change,'' but he added it was up to the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> government. <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> reiterated his government's position that foreign newspapers are circulated in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> `` not as a right, but as a privilege granted by the government on terms set by the government,'' according to <PERSON> Tan </PERSON>. The government allows papers to circulate in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> so long as they do not engage in domestic politics, <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> said. In 1987, the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> government severely restricted the circulation of both publications, a move that prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> to shut down all distribution here. Editors from both papers have denied allegations by the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> government that they meddled in local government. Restrictions on the press as well as human rights concerns have strained U.S.-Singapore relations at times over the past years. Last year, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> expelled an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> diplomat, claiming that he was interfering in domestic politics in his contacts with the opposition. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> denied that charge. It also has criticized <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> in the past for detaining political opponents. While in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> the vice president also played golf, his second stint on the greens of his <LOCATION> Asia-Pacific </LOCATION> trip. The round was cut short after five holes because of rain.
