<FIRST>r w AM-JeffersonLecture     05-03 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jefferson Lecture,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Novelist Says Science, by Ignoring Language, Is `Incoherent'</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 8 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Novelist <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> said Wednesday that modern science is `` radically incoherent'' because it has failed to bridge the gap between mind and matter by recognizing the importance of human language. Delivering the 18th annual Jefferson Lecture of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanities </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> urged creating a new `` science of man'' that focuses on the words and meanings of language, the only place, he said, where mind and matter intersect. `` We do not find it odd that there is only one science of chemistry and neurology but, at last count, more than 600 different schools of psychotherapy, and growing,'' <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> said in text of his speech. `` We accept the explanation that, after all, the mind is vastly more complicated than a molecule of sodium chloride or even a nerve cell,'' he said. `` That may be true, but it does n't explain why the physical sciences are converging whereas the psychic ` sciences' are diverging; that is, getting nuttier,'' he said. <PERSON> Percy </PERSON>, an award-winning novelist from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and a former physician, delivered his lecture, titled `` The Fateful Rift: The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fault </LOCATION> in the Modern Mind,'' before 1,000 invited guests. The Jefferson Lecture, given by an eminent scholar every year since 1972, is the highest federal honor for outstanding achievement in the humanities. It carries a stipend of $ 10,000. <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> said science ignores or fails to deal with the relation between the human mind and the physical world. Contemporary psychology, he says, deals with visible, measurable entities such as neurons and synapses and mental phenomena such as `` self'' or `` ego'' without linking them. However, he said, `` an increasing number of people are beginning to know that a different sort of reality lies at the heart of all uniquely human activity _ speaking, listening, understanding, thinking, looking at art.'' <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> said this reality, `` man's unique behavior of language and symbol-mongering,'' eventually must be confronted by science as a natural phenomenon that explains humanity. Art, poetry and novels `` ought to be taken very seriously indeed, since these are the cognitive, scientific ... statements that we have about what it is to be human,'' <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> said. `` The humanities, in a word, are not the minstrels of the age whose only role is to promise ` R & amp; R' to tired technicians and consumers after work,'' he said. `` Rather are the humanities the elder brother of the sciences, who sees how the new scientist got his tail in a crack when he takes on the human subject as object and who even shows him the shape of a new science.''
</TEXT>
