<SECOND>AM-Tax Freedom Day,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Come Friday, You'll Be Working for Yourself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thursday is `` Tax Freedom Day.'' Once you put in your eight hours, you'll be working for yourself the rest of the year. The <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> calculates the average American will have to work 124 days this year _ the same as in 1987 and 1988 _ just to pay federal, state and local taxes. Thursday is the 124th day of the year. Tax Freedom Day has never fallen later in the year. This year's date is also the same as in 1981, before President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> agreed on a 23-percent across-the-board cut in individual income tax rates Economists for the foundation, a nonpartisan <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> research group, say the value of that tax cut has been offset by more than a dozen subsequent federal tax increases and by higher state and local taxes caused partially by cuts in federal programs. The foundation's calculations are based on the assumption that all taxes, including those collected by businesses, ultimately are paid by individuals.
