<HEAD>Rodriguez Announces Pay Raises After Election Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pay raises announced, latest
results. Pickup 5th pvs, `Some losers...' Deletes pvs grafs 8-10 to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> today ordered pay raises of 30 percent to 70 percent for public employees and the military after his overwhelming victory in presidential and congressional elections. The salaries of brigadier generals will jump 70 percent, from $ 448 to $ 761 a month. Captains' salaries will go from $ 248 to $ 421, and sergeants will earn $ 209, up from $ 123. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, who toppled dictator <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> in a coup Feb. 3, also announced 30 percent pay raises for public employees and 49 percent increases for workers in clinics and hospitals. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> announced the retirement of up to three dozen army generals, some of them <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> loyalists, as part of a shakeup to allow younger officers to move up in rank. `` Within a few days, or within the month of May, I'll give you the list of those who have left -LRB- retired -RRB- and those who have been promoted to general,'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> told reporters as he left the National Palace. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said today that of 898,829 votes counted so far, <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> received 667,434, or slightly more than 74 percent. His governing <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> won control of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the vote. `` I am pleased and happy that I have the affection of the people, and they showed their confidence in me,'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said when asked about the results. Some losers fumed about voting irregularities, but Paraguayans seemed satisfied with the triumph of <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, a longtime <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> aide who has respected civil liberties and promised democratic reforms since taking power. `` You could n't expect any other result because the people are very grateful to him for putting his life in danger to bring us freedom,'' said <PERSON> Susana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jara </PERSON>, 50, a fruit vendor in the public market. `` Half of the vote for <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> was a ` thank you' for overthrowing <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Aldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuccolillo </PERSON>, editor of the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> Color that reopened last March after being shut down five years ago by the former regime. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Vera </PERSON>, presidential candidate of the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Febrerista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, noted the election's many `` irregularities,'' but said <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> obviously won `` by a landslide.'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> has pledged to support reforms of the Constitution, electoral law and the penal code. He also promised not to seek re-election in 1993. The balloting was to choose a successor to finish the five-year terms of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> dissolved after the coup. The partial, official tally gave the governing <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> 67.2 percent of the vote for the 36-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the 72-member Chamber of Deputies. Unofficial tallies gave the <ORGANIZATION> Colorados </ORGANIZATION>, in power since 1947, similar winning margins. The runner-up in the presidential balloting, <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, has complained of `` shameful irregularities'' in the voting. On Tuesday, he met with other party