 A military jet crashed today during a training flight, and the pilot died from injuries suffered when he ejected moments before the plane went down, <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The single-seat AV-8 Harrier crashed about 9 a.m. near a training airfield at the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recruiting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> spokesman 1st Lt. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozloski </PERSON> said. The pilot died later at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Hospital in <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, authorities said. The pilot, whose name was withheld pending notification of relatives, was assigned to the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kozloski </PERSON> said. The pilot was one of 25,600 Marines and sailors participating in the `` Solid Shield'89'' training exercise, which began today along the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and is scheduled to run until May 20. The Harrier jet, capable of vertical take-offs and landings, had taken off from Page Field at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kozloski </PERSON> said. No weapons or explosives were aboard the jet, which crashed 100 feet from the end of the runway and sparked a fire, <PERSON> Kozloski </PERSON> said. No injuries were reported on the ground and the fire was brought under control, <PERSON> Kozloski </PERSON> said. Three pilots have died in 14 Harrier jet crashes since May 1988, said 1st Lt. <PERSON> Tamara </PERSON> <PERSON> Skipton </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, where all the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military's Harrier jets are based. The jet's predecessor, the AV-8C, was introduced by <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 and used by the British during the <LOCATION> Falkland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> war.
