<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business productivity rose at an annual rate of 0.5 percent in the first quarter of 1989, with manufacturing workers significantly increasing their per-hour output, the government reported Wednesday. Overall output in non-farm business rose at a rate of 3.6 percent in the first quarter while hours worked climbed 3.1 percent, leaving the half-percent productivity gain, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The department revised the fourth-quarter non-farm productivity gain to an annual rate of 1 percent, up from the 0.1 percent initially reported. All of the figures were seasonally adjusted. The gains were marked in manufacturing: Productivity improved 3.8 percent in the first quarter from the final three months of 1988 because manufacturing workers increased their output by 4.6 percent while the number of hours worked grew by only 0.8 percent. The data essentially confirmed figures in the government's recent reports on the gross national product and employment costs Productivity _ output per hour for all workers _ is an indicator of the efficiency of American business. Because of labor shortages, particularly in skilled jobs, economists have been predicting wages will rise faster and significant productivity gains will be needed to curb inflation. Still, there were signs in Wednesday's report that wage gains are not outpacing inflation in general. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that hourly compensation in non-farm business rose 5.7 percent in the first quarter but real hourly compensation, which takes into account the increase in consumer prices in that period, grew by only 0.3 percent. For all of 1988, hourly compensation adjusted to factor in consumer inflation rose a revised 0.4 percent, the department said. In manufacturing, real hourly compensation lagged 0.6 percent behind inflation in 1988 and 1.2 percent behind in the first quarter compared to the fourth quarter of 1988, according to the government data. In a separate gauge, the government reported that unit labor costs _ obtained by dividing compensation by output _ rose 5.2 percent in the first quarter from the previous three months and 4.9 percent compared to the first quarter of 1988. The improved productivity in manufacturing in the first quarter included a gain of 3.6 percent for durable goods and 4 percent for non-durables. The report included revised productivity data for 1988, with the government reporting overall non-farm productivity improved 1.5 percent over the year as output increased 5.2 percent while total hours worked grew 3.7 percent. The government reported overall business productivity _ including farming _ increased at a 3.5 percent annual rate in the first quarter, but that figure is heavily influenced by the agricultural rebound after last year's drought. Productivity had declined 1 percent in the overall business category in the final quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
