<HEAD>Soviet: Importing Publications Just a `Commercial Issue'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Importing books and other publications to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is `` purely a commercial'' proposition, unhindered by political considerations, a high-ranking Soviet official said Wednesday. <PERSON> Dmitry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamleev </PERSON>, deputy head of the Soviet state committee for publishing and the book trade, also said exchanges between Americans and Soviets in the publishing world are booming thanks to glasnost. `` There is no problem with political issues now,'' <PERSON> Mamleev </PERSON> said at a news conference during a 35-nation forum on the flow of information between East and West. `` This is purely a commercial issue now.'' <PERSON> Mamleev </PERSON>, who introduced himself as a journalist, said 12 joint ventures have been created recently for distributing books. He cited only Soviet-Polish and Soviet-Bulgarian examples of cooperation, however. He denied that censorship existed in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, saying the only ban was on publication of state secrets. Due to glasnost, the new Soviet policy of openness, all publishing houses were `` independent,'' he said. Despite a paper shortage, he said, 2 -LCB- billion books and 84,000 new titles were being published every year. Speaking of exchanges with Americans, <PERSON> Mamleev </PERSON> said, `` two years ago we started at a level below zero _ today I do n't know how many of my publishers are in the States, there are so many.'' As part of the limited importation of foreign magazines and newspapers begun last fall, he said 1,000 copies of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> recently went on sale. The newspaper <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> is set to follow and his committee is negotiating an exchange of the science magazine Omni for its Soviet counterpart, Science in the U.S.S.R. Until recently, Soviet customs inspectors searched the bags of arriving tourists to confiscate Western publications. On Tuesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation member <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> criticized the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s decision to allow the public to attend the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> International Book Fair in September for only two days of its seven day-run. Ms. <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> expressed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern that `` this period will not be long enough to accommodate the many Soviet citizens who depend on this biennial event to acquint themselves with world literature.'' She also cited the case of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryabakon </PERSON>, a Russian Orthodox Christian, whose religious literature was confiscated upon his return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in December, despite official <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media articles announcing the lifting of all limitations on importing such material. She said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegates hoped that the positive changes toward freedom of expression seen in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and `` to some extent'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would also reach other <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries where they were needed, such as <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. The month-long conference, known as the Information Forum, ends next week.
