<HEAD>Bush Rules Out Talks With Soviets Over Short-Range Nuclear Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Bush statement, picks up with 3rd graf
pvs, I tried. Removes last 6 grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today ruled out negotiations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on short-range nuclear missiles, saying such talks `` would be a mistake.'' He said the weapons must be kept in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and made more powerful in order to deter Soviet attack. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined his position to Prime Minister <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlem </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> in an hour-long White House meeting. She stressed a need to find `` commmon ground'' with West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, who wants the missiles scaled back and eventually eliminated. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, suggested the disagreement was not likely to be resolved before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> and the leaders of the 14 other <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> countries attend a summit meeting in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> May 29-30. `` We will continue to discuss it but we are very firm in our position,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The centerpiece of the summit is celebration of the 40th anniversary of the Western alliance. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said `` we will have a healthy debate'' if a solution remains elusive. But, he said, `` I do n't think it will damage the basic strength of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>.'' Quoting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the spokesman said the president had told the Norwegian leader that the short-range <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> missiles were `` essential'' to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy of deterring an attack by the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact and that `` such systems must be kept up to date.'' Moreover, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> that `` entering into arms control negotiations on short-range nuclear forces with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would be a mistake.'' The statement appeared to rule out negotiations to eliminate the Lances under any circumstances. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said there could be no consideration of such talks at least until after the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> reduced its conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON>, taking an optimistic view, had predicted after seeing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies would find a `` common ground'' between conflicting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and West German positions on the short-range nuclear missiles. `` I tried to listen very seriously to the concerns and the positions of the American administration,'' the Norwegian leader said. While <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> shares the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> view that the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact's edge in conventional weapons should be trimmed, Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> made it clear her government is closer to the West German stand on the missiles. `` I think he knows that,'' she said of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, whose hopes for a successful first summit meeting with the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies, scheduled for Brusssels May 29-30, are clouded by differences with West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to more than triple the range of U.S.-built Lance missiles in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, who is up for re-election next year before a disarmament-inclined electorate, wants the program delayed and negotiations held between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to scale back short-range nuclear rockets. `` I think we will see the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit will find common ground by continuing discussions in the weeks before that meeting,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> said. If not, the Norwegian leader said, the 16 allied leaders could accomplish the task in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. `` There is always something left for political leaders to do,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> said the elements of a compromise should include a `` linkage'' between non-nuclear and nulcear weapons. `` We have to be very clear in our requirements to the Soviets on reducing conventional arms,'' she said. The prime minister said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration felt it had been taken by surprise by the West German demand for speedy negotiations over the Lance missiles. `` But these change are a fact and I think we need to find common ground,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said on Tuesday the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration was considering a compromise in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would develop a non-nuclear missile jointly with the West Germans. This would require a reversal of a decision by <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> in February to stop research and development on the FK90 missile, which was classified as a tactical weapon with a range below 300 miles. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the missile could target <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact airfields and other military installations now targeted by the Lances. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said development of the non-nuclear missile was under consideration at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> and at the Pentagon. `` It would give us greater flexibility,'' he said. Another option under discussion within the alliance is a declaration at the <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> summit meeting May 29-30 proposing to scale back the Lance missiles _ but only after their range is more than tripled and provided the Soviets reduce their short-range rockets, as well. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> said at a news conference Tuesday that `` what we need now is to look for the common ground, to look for what will be a sensible and coherent way of addressing the issues both of arms control and disarmament.'' The prime minister said her government's position is that `` all kinds of weapons'' should be on the table in arms control and disarmament talks. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> has lined up with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in seeking a delay in extending the range of the Lances to about 250 miles. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> also would like to see <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s agenda expanded to deal with environmental and energy problems. `` We will all be hurt by climate and atmosphere changes wherever we live on the globe,'' she said.
