<HEAD>Quayle Trip: A Sporting Chance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sometimes Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s trip to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> seemed more like Wide World of Sports than a diplomatic mission Once, he kept <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s minister of tourism waiting for nearly two hours at the <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> airport because he and his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, wanted to squeeze in some last-minute tennis at a <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> resort in northeast <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s favorite sport is golf, which stood him in good stead in golf-crazy <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. After he played five holes in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> quizzed him on his golf backround. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, a well-above-average golfer, said he first handled a club when he was 10. By the time he was 20, he allowed, he knew he'd never make pro. The Quayles also donned wetsuits and strapped oxygen tanks on their backs to try scuba diving in the brilliant waters of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s coral-rich Great Barrier Reef. They were so hooked on the sport, they opted for a second dive. In <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> jogged around the city's botanical gardens, stopping to chat with the locals. And in an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> tradition, he started his 12-day trip with a 3 a.m. pickup basketball game at <ORGANIZATION> Hickam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. Score: Visitors 23, Home 16.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is vice president now, but the former <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator has n't forgotten his Hoosier roots. Asked by an Australian reporter where the word `` Hoosier'' originated, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> responded: `` That's important. ... Let me answer that ... I'll give you a little advertising here.'' Launching into a description of the state - `` five-and-a-half million people, we do n't produce a lot of wheat'' _ <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> gave one of the many versions of where the word came from. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Hoosiers </ORGANIZATION> were a family who worked on a railroad in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> in the 1800s. `` Anytime that they really wanted to get the job done, he -LRB- the boss -RRB-, would always say, ` Give me my Hoosier gang,' which meant the people from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>.'' `` They were hard-working, effective, brilliant people like you are seeing right here,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said as the crowd roared. So, interjected the questioner, `` It's got nothing to do with ` Who's you mother?''' By coincidence, one of the movies available on the cable channel where <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s staff stayed in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, was `` Hoosiers,'' spelled `` Hossiers'' on the schedule.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 While <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> met officials in government buildings, his wife often went her own way, visiting historic cultural sights. `` If you want to go out and see the country, go with <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told reporters at the start of his 27,000-mile trip. He was right. Mrs. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, traveling abroad with her husband for the first time since he became vice president, toured a sultan's palace in <LOCATION> Jogjakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>; learned about aboriginal art at <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s national gallery in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>; gazed at the emerald <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> inside a gilded temple at the Grand Palace in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, and climbed to the top of the 9th century <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temple at <LOCATION> Borobudur </LOCATION> in central Java There, she stuck her arm though a stone cage to touch the hand of a carved <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> inside. `` It's for success in life,'' she proclaimed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, 42, prides himself on his stamina, but he acknowledged he felt the effects of his `` if it's Wednesday, it must be <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>'' trip at times. On his second day in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, the vice president was asked what surprised him most about the place. `` I suppose the most surprising thing, and I've only been here less that 24 hours, was how tired I was last night,'' he responded. Later, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he'd taken sleeping pills the first couple of nights of the trip to cope with jet lag. Counting four brief stops in cities in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory before he reached <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was visiting 13 places in 12 days, flying 27,000 miles. His itinerary: <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, Site B refugee camp <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The Quayles seemed to survive their trip without any noticeable cultural faux pas. Not that there were n't chances. For example, the visitors' guide to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and handed out to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s entourage, advised the following: `` Do n't stand over a seated Thai when talking to him.'' `` Do n't touch a <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> on the head.'' `` Do n't point or shake your finger at someone. When sitting, do not allow your toes to point directly at another person.'' `` Do stand up when the king's anthem is played at the movie or other public gatherings.''
