<HEAD>Senators Press Hills to Target Japan for Market-Opening Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators urged the nation's top trade negotiator on Wednesday to resist pressure to omit <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> from a target list being developed by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration in an effort to open key world markets to American exports. `` We would be amazed if <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with its whole panoply of trade barriers, were not on the list,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., said at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> trade hearing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> told the senators that the administration would `` use the negotiating tools contained in the 1988 act vigorously but constructively to open markets, combat unfair trade practices and persuade our trading partners to honor agreements.'' `` In administering these provisions, we will act as a surgeon using a scalpel to remove these trade barriers and promote a healthier trading system,'' she said. `` We will not use these tools to butcher the rules of the system we are trying to strengthen.'' At issue is a report from <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, due by the end of the month, that must target specific countries for market-opening action and possible retaliation under the so-called Super 301 section of the 1988 trade law. There reportedly is divided opinion within the administration over whether to include <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Under the Super 301 provision, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative targets key countries for market-opening pressure. If they fail to lower their barriers to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> exports within 15 to 19 months, the trade representative takes retaliatory steps, such as tariffs and quotas, to compensate the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The president does have discretion to abort such steps in some cases. The provision is called Super 301 because it represents an extension of section 301 of the Trade Act, which has long been the basic legal authority under which the president is authorized to retaliate against foreign countries for alleged unfair trade practices. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> is due to unveil her list May 30. `` I strongly support the idea and urge you to include <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the Super 301 category,'' Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, told He said that `` their market is not open to us in any way that it should be.'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., noted that a long-running dispute between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> over semiconductors remains unresolved `` If that is n't grounds for listing under Super 301 what is?'' <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said. Under questioning from Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said that `` great concern has been expressed by some'' officials of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trading partners as the date for the list approaches and there has been a reaction `` among some others -LRB- of -RRB- more belligerence perhaps. `` There is general anxiety,'' she said. Asked by Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., about reports that foreign lobbying has been heavy at her office as other countries strive to stay off the list, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> merely said, `` We've had a good number of visitors. She agreed with the view of Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, that merely lowering barriers overseas is far from the answer to the nation's trade problems. `` We could open all the markets we have enumerated and it would not correct our trade deficit, and I think we make a mistake not to tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people that,'' she said. `` To tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people that if you open all these markets that will take care of the trade deficit _ that is not true.''
