<HEAD>Hospital Association: Health Care Threatened by Worker Shortage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A shortage of health-care workers, such as physical and occupational therapists, is threatening the availability of hospital care, an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> survey said Wednesday. In its survey of 3,001 hospitals, the association found that despite adding overtime, changing compensation programs, setting up on-call staff pools and using contract services, one-fourth of the hospitals said they were forced to cut services. Of the hospitals that cut services, more than 15 percent closed beds or units and almost 13 percent sent patients to other hospitals because they lacked sufficient staff. `` Hospital and patients already feel the effects of personnel shortages,'' said association President <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>. `` If left unchecked, these shortages can threaten our ability to respond to the health-care needs of all Americans.'' The survey found that of 20 personnel categories, hospitals were having the most difficulty recruiting full-time physical therapists, clinical perfusionists _ operators of machines that support or temporarily replace circulatory or respiratory functions _ and occupational therapists. Also in short supply were speech pathologists and respiratory therapists, pharmacists and certified registered-nurse anesthetists. Positions for physical and occupational therapists have a 15 percent to 16 percent vacancy rate. To address the labor shortages, Ms. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said she believed the industry must create, preserve and expand educational opportunities for people interested in pursuing health-care careers. Hospitals also must develop innovative staffing options that lead to greater staff productivity and retention, she said. The survey, conducted from July through December 1988, found that vacancy rates varied according to regions, but physical and occupational therapists are in short supply throughout the country.
