<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The town of <LOCATION> Rantoul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, is the first to receive a federal planning grant from the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to help cope with the upcoming round of military base closings, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The community, located next to the <ORGANIZATION> Chanute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, will receive $ 73,045 `` to help organize a base reuse committee to start planning the civilian conversion of the base property,'' according to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statement. In addition to the federal money, <LOCATION> Rantoul </LOCATION> is contributing money and services worth $ 11,300 and the state of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> $ 10,000 to support the effort. `` The reuse committee will oversee development of a balanced plan for the property covering such uses as aviation, industrial development, housing, education, recreation and possibly health-related activities,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statement said. The grant was made by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adjustment </ORGANIZATION>, which has helped more than 400 communities since 1961 deal with the closure of nearby military facilities. The grant to <LOCATION> Rantoul </LOCATION>, however, is the first since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved a long list of base closings last month under a special procedure set up last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chanute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> is one of 86 bases now set for closure under the program, which was prompted primarily by budget con