<TEXT>
 The chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday for not doing more to stop pesticides banned in this country from showing up in imported food. The government must ensure that foreign buyers of U.S.-made pesticides understand their dangers and protect the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public from imported food contaminated with unsafe pesticides, said Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has failed miserably,'' said <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on environment, energy and natural resources, which has jurisdiction over the agency During a hearing of his subcommittee, <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> inspectors found chlordane, a chemical believed to cause cancer, in two shipments of Honduran beef. `` Our reports show that chlordane is made only in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' but is not allowed to be sold here as pesticide, said <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>. In both cases, most of the Honduran beef had been sold to grocery stores, ground up and purchased by consumers before the chlordane contamination was discovered. <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> criticized the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> for not warning the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> was buying an American-made pesticide that could contaminate beef sold to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It's time for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` to revisit our pesticide export policies,'' he said. During the hearing, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials admitted they ca n't ensure that pesticides outlawed here wo n't show up in imported food. But they also charged that the subcommittee has n't followed its own suggestions for helping other countries better understand the dangers of some pesticides made in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> assistant administrator for policy, planning and evaluation, said the agency was aware more needed to be done. When presented with an internal memo dated April 17, 1987, that outlined improvements needed to better educate foreign buyers and protect <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> consumers, she conceded that none had been followed. But <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> assured <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> would quickly act on the recommendations, as well as those of international negotiators working to establish a policy for worldwide pesticide use. <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s charges against the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> were supported by a report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, an investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has no established procedures for deciding when to notify foreign countries about pesticides the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has designated dangerous to human health. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> also has no standards for determining whether action taken against pesticides in this country are significant enough to warn another nation, according to the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, pesticides that are banned or unregistered domestically can be sold abroad if the foreign buyer provides a statement saying he understands that the product is outlawed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A copy of that statement is provided to the foreign government through the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> does not routinely send out notices to foreign governments when companies voluntarily cancel domestic registrations, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The agency is considering improvements to its present procedures, including those reocmmended by <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>.
