<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett     05-03 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett,680</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Bennett: Drug Punishment Certainty More Crucial than Severity ^By
CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stiff prison sentences are fine, the administration's top drug-control official said Wednesday, but in drug cases `` certainty of punishment is more important than severity.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION>, told several hundred members of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interreligious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> that his approach to the drug problem can be summed up in the words, `` consequences and confrontation.'' `` Those who use, sell and traffic in drugs must be confronted, and they must suffer consequences,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. He is working on a strategy for drug control nationwide, with a report due in early September. While saying there is broad agreement on such consequences as `` seizure of assets, stiffer prison sentences, revocation of bail rights and the death penalty for drug kingpins,'' he added, `` I also find that we lack the resources to assure that consequences always follow crime.'' He called for more prisons and jails and for more investigators, prosecutors and judges, but also said, `` More and tougher action will not be enough. `` I think we need to reorient our process of justice where drugs are concerned, and adopt the principle that certainty of punishment is more important than severity of punishment,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` Those guilty of drug offenses must believe that punishment is inevitable. As long as they do n't, the deterrent effect of incarceration is neutralized.'' After the speech, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he was n't suggesting reduced sentences for drug offenders, including what he termed casual users. `` I am for severe penalties, particularly when a drug crime is severe, but what you have to have is certain punishment,'' he said. `` You should n't make certain punishment hostage to severe punishment. `` What that means is a person that commits a drug crime has to know they're going to be punished. And if you have to sacrifice an extra six months of punishment in order to be sure the person gets some punishment, make sure they get some punishment,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` It would be better in many situations to have everyone that's convicted of drug use to go to jail for a week ... than to just get a third of them going for six months.'' As an example, he cited a practice in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, where he said police arrested drug users, many of them middle-class, and `` put them in jail for a weekend, that's all, just a weekend. For a lot of middle-class users, that is plenty of time. ... They are cured after one weekend in the slammer.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> acknowledged that such an idea would be for state and local governments to carry out and that he, as director of national drug control policy, would not be imposing such regulations on the federal level. But he said local officials have asked him repeatedly during his two months on the job to let them know if there are any good ideas floating around, and the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> example is one he's advocating. Another local example he touted was that of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where `` parents are brought before the juvenile justice court and made to answer for the actions of their children through civil penalties.'' `` This policy establishes the principle that parents ... must bear responsibility for the behavior and the activities of minors in their charge,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. `` Minors who are non-addicted users must be taught early on that they can not behave with impunity, and parents who have effectively turned them loose must learn why the social contract demands that they oversee and control the impulses of their children.'' Asked later if that included jailing parents for their children's transgressions, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said that should occur only in `` extreme cases.'' As for treatment and rehabilitation of drug offenders, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> told the coalition that `` in many cases, rehabilitation is the wrong term to use.'' `` In the case of 15-year-old offenders who have grown up essentially without parents, some therapists I have talked to have found it necessary to serve as substitute parents, complete with a tuck-in and bedtime story at night,'' he said.
</TEXT>
