<HEAD>Producer-Financed Soybean Promotion, Research Program Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was asked Wednesday to set up a $ 60 million soybean research and promotion program financed by a levy on domestic soybean production. Proposed legislation, developed by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, would provide for a nationwide `` checkoff'' similar to programs involving other commodities, including those for dairy, pork and beef producers. Money from a mandatory assessment would pay for farmer-run programs to expand exports, develop new uses for soybeans and promote soybean products through a national advertising campaign. The program would be administered by state and national boards composed of soybean producers. `` This program is and will be farmer-bred, farmer-fed and farmer-led,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Camilla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. At a news conference, Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., said the legislation would give `` American soybean farmers a war chest of their own'' to combat promotional and research efforts of foreign competitors Currently, 26 states have soybean promotion programs generating a total of about $ 15 million, and the national levy would replace those. The proposed rate of assessment would be one-half percent of the net market value of soybeans sold by a farmer _ 50 cents for every $ 100 in sales. Half of the estimated $ 60 million in collections would go to state programs. If the legislation is enacted, the assessment would be implemented and a producer referendum would be held 18 to 36 months later to determine whether it should continue.
</TEXT>
