<HEAD>Bill Proposes Nursing Home Quality Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Uniform national standards on such things as cleanliness and food quality at boarding homes for the elderly would override state regulations and be enforced by surprise inspections under legislation introduced Wednesday by Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>. `` We need to act immediately to end the abuse of our elderly and disabled,'' Pepper, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said in a statement `` This bill seeks to eradicate what is truly a tragedy of epic proportions.'' He said many of the homes visited by congressional inspectors `` were n't fit for roaches, let alone the frail elderly and disabled people who were forced to live there.'' A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on health said Pepper, who has been under hospital care since April 6, signed the legislation last week during a visit to his office and it was formally filed with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> clerk Wednesday. In a subcommittee report released earlier, investigators determined there are more 1 million elderly and disabled residents living in more than 68,000 board and care homes. Pepper said subcommittee investigators conducted unannounced inspections of board and care homes in 10 states and `` found evidence of fraud, waste and abuse in every state.'' Federal and state governments spend an estimated $ 7 billion a year to support elderly and disabled people in the homes, mostly through the federal Supplemental Security Income program.
