<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `About 90 percent ..., to CORRECT that 90 percent
of graduate students, sted all, took part in walkout; SUBS 20th graf, `The
association ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With final exams just two weeks away, a union of 3,200 graduate assistants walked out of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Berkeley </ORGANIZATION> classrooms Wednesday and onto picket lines to press a demand for recognition as employees. `` Hey, hey! Ho, ho! Union busting's got to go!'' sign-carrying teaching and research assistants chanted as they demonstrated at every major entrance to the campus. Their union based here, the Association for Graduate Student Employees, is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, and is the vanguard of a burgeoning movement challenging the traditional view of graduate students as scholars living off stipends. The students say they are underpaid, overworked and often forced to go without health and other benefits. `` This is not a question of mainly getting more money for me; it's a matter of justice,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Martel </PERSON>, a 24-year-old teaching assistant in the political science department. `` We're not a bunch of <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> radicals demanding a change in foreign policy; we just want to exercise a basic <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> right to join a union and have our concerns represented at a bargaining table,'' added <PERSON> Martel </PERSON>, who joined about 200 pickets as classes were to begin. Union representatives claimed hundreds of classes were canceled on the first day of the two-day strike. The university did not check the number of canceled classes, but a <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> spokesman called the protest largely symbolic. About 90 percent ot the 3,200 graduate assistants took part in the walkout, the association claimed. There are about 9,000 graduate students at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. A victory by the <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> students could legitimize similar demands eat many more campuses, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, a member of the association's executive board. `` The movement nationally on this issue is picking up steam,'' <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said. `` We're not making demands in a vacuum.'' In the last 10 years, at least five major universities in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> have recognized graduate student assistants as employees. Teaching assistants at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> won collective bargaining from the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. Their union, affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, is negotiating their second contract. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, the university and its newly organized teaching assistants reached a collective bargaining agreement earlier this year giving assistants a 14 percent pay raise over the next two years. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, the coordinating committe of the teaching assistants' union voted last week to affiliate with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> union has been seeking recognition since 1983. Last week, the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, ruling 2-1 in favor of a university appeal, said a 1979 law forbids graduate students from being treated as employees because their work duties are part of scholarly training. The association plans to appeal to court. At the start of <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>'s school day, <LOCATION> Sproul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION>, where one-fifth of students generally enter, was unusually quiet. Protesters handed out yellow armbands to supporters. `` The teaching assistants are the university when it comes to learning here,'' said undergraduate <PERSON> Cammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Starks </PERSON>, 21, who said her morning classes had been canceled and wore an armband. `` Everything I've learned, I've learned from the assistants, not professors who hardly ever get to know you.'' Anthropology Professor <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Berreman </PERSON>, who joined pickets, said graduate students handle 90 percent of the paper grading. `` I'm here to show them how important they are to faculty,'' he said On Tuesday, 71 professors in 10 departments sent a letter to Chancellor <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON> endorsing the walkout and the association's call for teaching assistants to cancel or reschedule classes. <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> has 1,350 tenured professors. The association said that at least 500 Wednesday and Thursday classes were canceled or rescheduled. According to a selective survey by the association of 307 classes through Wednesday afternoon, 66 percent were canceled, 25 percent were less than half-full, and 9 percent were at capacity. University spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Debley </PERSON> said the results were not necessarily representative of the campus, which has 23,000 undergraduates. He said it's not unusual for some students to skip classes in the final weeks before finals to gain time to prepare papers. <PERSON> Debley </PERSON> said the cost of pay raises and for providing health and other benefits could have a substantial impact on university budgets. According to a study by the association, teaching assistants handle 58 percent of classroom work involving undergraduate students and research assistants do about half the laboratory work. The university contends the work can not be considered employment because it is so intertwined with educational experience, <PERSON> Debley </PERSON> said. Students receive annual stipends from the university or research institutions averaging about $ 10,000 annually. `` It is more of a learning experience than an employment experience,'' <PERSON> Debley </PERSON> said.
