<HEAD>Lawmaker Says US-Japan Reach Tentative Agreement On Driftnet Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have reached a tentative agreement over driftnet fishing in the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Jolene </PERSON> <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>, D-Wash., outlined details of what she said is an agreement that might end the dispute over use of the huge nets She was critical of the pact. An estimated 700 fishing boats from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> use driftnets, which can stretch 35 miles in length and cover more than 30,000 square miles of ocean on any given day. American fishermen claim that vessels from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> use driftnets to illegally snare millions of tons of salmon under the guise of squid fishing. Fishing groups have said the illegal fishing has already impacted salmon runs in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>, D-Wash., released what she said are details of the pact, based on talks with unnamed officials from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fishing industry She said the pact calls for:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ 2 observers stationed aboard Japanese driftnet vessels to monitor their catch. There are an estimated 400 vessels in the Japanese driftnet fleet. _ An increase from four to five in the number of Japanese patrol vessels in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and an increase in patrol days for the vessels from the current 250 per year to 600 per year. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> enforcement officers will be stationed aboard the patrol vessels. _ Stiffer Japanese penalties for ships caught illegally driftnet fishing. _ Marking of all driftnets so the owners of those cast adrift can be identified. _ A ban on the high-seas transfer of fish between Japanese trawlers and freighters, which carry the fish back to port. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> said the Japanese refused to agree to a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> request for a pilot program to place transponders on a dozen or so Japanese vessels. Using satellites, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> could have monitored the movements of the ships. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is considering a transponder test using American vessels, <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> said. Other congressional sources, who asked not to be identified, confirmed most of the details supplied by <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>, but added that the agreement was for only one year and the Japanese have essentially told the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` take it or leave it.'' The sources also said the Japanese have indicated they plan to move the legal driftnet zone slightly northward, though exactly how far remains unclear. The existing driftnet zone was designed to keep fishing vessels far south of the migration routes of North American salmon. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s ambassador for ocean and fisheries, was out of his office and unavailable for comment Wednesday. Earlier this week, <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that an agreement with the Japanese was close. Congressional sources said the agreement has actually been signed by Japanese officials and initialed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators. `` I am extremely apprehensive that this agreement will not be adequate,'' said <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>. `` I am also not sure that this will meet the requirements of the 1987 Driftnet Act.'' Under that act, if <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other countries with driftnet fleets have not entered into monitoring and enforcement agreements with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by June 29, the president could impose trade sanctions. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> said she was upset that the Japanese had refused to agree to a transponder test program. `` We may have negotiated away our ability to put any teeth in our action,'' she said. `` It's absolutely goofy. If they are n't violating any existing agreements, why are they objecting to us placing transponders on their ships? <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> also said she felt the number of observers called for in the agreement falls short of what was needed to provide `` sufficient'' data on the impact of driftnet fishing.
