<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Men Who Claim They Helped Soviet Spy Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two men who wrote a book claiming they helped Soviet spy <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> escape to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> jail 33 years ago were arrested on Wednesday. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON>, 50, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Randle </PERSON>, 55, went to a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police sation at the request of the police and were arrested, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard said. They were then escorted to their homes, <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> in the northern town of <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION>. They were not charged. A police spokesman, speaking anonymously, said they would be granted bail while a report was sent to the Director of Public Prosectuions, who is responsible for deciding on prosecution. Officers from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard's Special Branch, which deals with subversion, were searching <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON>'s home when a reporter telephoned him. `` They are putting things in bags. I've been expecting this, so I gathered some items together and they have been in a pile on the kitchen table for about 10 days, waiting,'' <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON>, an antiques dealer, added that he and <PERSON> Randle </PERSON>, a researcher, expect to go to prison eventually. A new book titled `` The Blake Escape'' by the two men and a TV film about the case described how they harbored <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> after he broke out of Wormwood Scrubs prison in 1966 and how <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> smuggled him out of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in a camper van to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourke </PERSON>, a former fellow prisoner of <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>, directed his escape by radio messages. <PERSON> Bourke </PERSON>, now dead, later wrote a book describing how he was invited to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and treated as a hero by the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> secret police. <PERSON> Bourke </PERSON> did not mention <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> in his book. Last year, they admitted their part in the case to a reporter. <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> was sentenced to 42 years and jailed in 1961 after pleading guilty to spying for the Soviets throughout the 1950s while working for MI6, the British intelligence gathering agency. The sentence _ the longest sentence for espionage ever handed down by a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> court _ was regarded as representing one year for each betrayed agent. At the end of a secret trial, the judge said <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> was suspected of betraying 42 British agents in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> who are believed to have been killed. <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> were founder members with the philosopher <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> of the Committee of 100, which protested nuclear weapons. They met <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> in prison while serving 18-month sentences for organizing a demonstration at a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base. The two men said they helped the spy escape because they felt a 42-year sentence was inhumane. More than 100 lawmakers of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> signed a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> paper demanding <PERSON> Pottle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Randle </PERSON> be prosecuted.
