<HEAD>Partial Resolution of Beef Fight Announced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on Wednesday announced a partial resolution of a contentious trade dispute with the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> over the issue of hormones in American beef. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said that both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> negotiators had agreed to accept the initial recommendations of a task force studying the dispute. That action will allow resumption of sales of about 15 percent of the $ 100 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef which is normally shipped to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. However, a dispute over the other 85 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef exports remains to be resolved, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. Under the agreement, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef producers who wish to export beef not treated with growth hormones to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> may do so. But American officials said they still maintained that <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s ban on imports of beef from cattle raised on growth-producing hormones represented an illegal trade barrier masquerading as a health measure American officials had refused to comply with the ban by certifying Europe-bound beef as hormone-free and instead slapped retaliatory tariffs on European goods valued at about $ 100 million, a sum equal to the lost sales of American beef. However, after the tariffs were imposed on Jan. 1 by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, officials of the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration began to search for a compromise to the dispute. At a meeting on Feb. 18, <LOCATION> Mrs. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> agreed to look for a way to certify as hormone-free as much <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef as possible. At the time, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> indicated it would reduce its $ 100 million in punitive tariffs by the amount of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was willing to accept. The agreement Wednesday follows the recommendations of a task force of officials from both sides established to study the matter. The partial resolution will cover high quality grades of beef being shipped to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but will not cover the other 85 percent of beef trade which includes so-called `` variety meats'' such as livers, tongues and kidneys. Mrs. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said that the task force studying the situation will continue searching for ways to include more American beef and will report back before June 15. In a statement, Mrs. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> called the interim agreement a `` positive step'' toward de-escalating what had become a contentious dispute between <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and one of its largest trading partners. `` To the extent that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef and beef products are shipped to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> under this measure, we will reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retaliatory measures on imports from the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said that while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position remains the same that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> beef containing the hormones presents no health risk, the administration did not want to `` stand in the way of producers who are willing and able to meet the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>'s requirements'' for hormone-free beef. Under the agreement, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> ranchers who want to export hormone-free beef to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will be given a set of requirements that they will have to meet by <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> officials, who will also establish a monitoring system to insure that the beef being shipped does not contain hormones.
