olvement in the killing and refused to answer most police questions. Police alleged that in his final interview, he told an officer, `` You ai n't got enough evidence. Those kids wo n't give evidence in court. No one will talk to you. You ca n't keep me away from them.'' <PERSON> Silcott </PERSON> denied using those words. <PERSON> Silcott </PERSON>'s defenders say police also presented conflicting testimony about his whereabouts during the riot. In 1987 a jury found <PERSON> Silcott </PERSON> guilty, and Judge Sir <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgson </PERSON> sentenced him to a minimum 30 years in prison, calling him `` a very evil and a very dangerous man.'' The judge disclosed that <PERSON> Silcott </PERSON> already was out on bail for another murder when the riot broke out. Lord <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON>, a civil rights campaigner and former judge, condemned the trials as `` a blot on the reputation of British justice.'' In a report, he concluded that `` the whole process from first to last was arbitrary, unfair and not conducive to bringing guilty people to justice.'' <PERSON> Gifford </PERSON> told students Tuesday that there was no evidence to convict <PERSON> Silcott </PERSON>. `` It was a terrible crime, and the more terrible a crime the greater is the emotion and the danger of prejudice, particularly racial prejudice.''
