<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The right-wing military government said Wednesday it was scrapping plans for democratic reforms because the opposition rejected a take-it-or-leave-it proposal. Interior Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> blamed `` intransigent'' opposition leaders in announcing an end to further talks. He said the opposition `` closed out the possibility of a realistic agreement'' on amendments to the 1980 constitution. `` Under the current circumstances, there is no possibility whatsoever of talking again about constitutional changes,'' he told a news conference. Among reform proposals abandoned was one legalizing Marxism. The announcement indicated an abrupt hardening in the position of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s government and a return to an openly antagonistic relationship between authorities and opposition. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and a leader of a 17-party opposition coalition, told his own news conference later that the move means reforms will have to wait until after Dec. 14 elections. `` If the government has said it will make no changes at all, there will be no changes for the time being,'' he said. `` They will have to be done by the future congress and the future government to be elected in December.'' <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> is considered the coalition's most likely choice as presidential candidate. The government on Friday proposed 19 changes to the constitution, including several offered in response to pressures for reform after Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> lost a referendum last October on extending his rule to 1997. Some changes deemed essential by the opposition were left out, however. The referendum loss obliged <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to schedule the elections, and his foes say reforms are needed to make sure the