<HEAD>LaserPhotos PAN4,5,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100,000 opposition backers packed one of the capital's main streets Wednesday to hear candidates predict victory in next week's elections and an end to 21 years of military control. Presidential candidate <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, his voice hoarse, told the crowd <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was on the eve of `` a new republic of which you all will be founding fathers.'' `` I was born free. I am not free. I will be free on May 7,'' shouted <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, the opposition's candidate for the second of two vice-presidential seats in Sunday's balloting. The speeches were interrupted when crowds panicked, once when security guards stopped people from coming too near the candidates and again when an alleged government infiltrator, or `` toad,'' was chased from the area by a mob beating him with sticks. People in the crowd said they saw an unidentified man fire gunshots into the air at one point. Several people were knocked to the ground. Some fainted and were carried away, but no serious injuries were reported. A group of youths snake-danced through the crowd carrying a black coffin with the picture of a smiling Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> pasted on the front and a pineapple affixed on top. `` Pineapple face'' is a derogatory name for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, inspired by his rough complexion. First vice-presidential candidate <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> praised young Panamanians at the rally, saying, `` There are thousands here who have never known liberty but are here to fight for it.'' The chanting, flag-waving crowd was packed so tightly on <LOCATION> Via </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Espana </LOCATION> that at times it was impossible to move. The opposition has accused the government of trying to rig Sunday's election. Earlier Wednesday, opposition leaders warned that Panamanians may react with violence if fraud is evident. `` This is the last peaceful opportunity for change,'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference earlier in the day. <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> also attended the conference. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said the opposition wants to avoid a confrontation with the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, but `` we fear that if the will of the people is violated, there will be a spontaneous reaction.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto ruler, is backing his business associate, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Duque </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaen </PERSON>, for president. The government also has warned that the elections could turn violent. <PERSON> Duque </PERSON> has urged his followers `` to take to the streets ... to defend the vote.'' The government made a public show of handing out weapons April 30 to the `` Dignity Batallions,'' civilians trained to defend <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> against a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said official voter rolls show duplicated names and suspicious increases in the number of voters. He said the registration in some districts doubled. He alleged the number of registered voters on rolls has grown 29 percent since 1984, while the population has increased by only 16 percent. Government officials explained the increases by saying registration procedures have improved. Despite the predictions of fraud, <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said he was confident the opposition's `` margin of victory will be such that it will neutralize the fraud, if the fraud is not accompanied by crude forms of repression.'' The opposition candidates said there is no hope of democracy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> as long as <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who was indicted in the <L