a spokesman played down the violation and said, `` It seems the cease-fire orders have n't been issued yet.'' No casualties were reported. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 Lebanese army soldiers have battled Moslem militiamen and allied Syrian soldiers since March 3. More than 1,000 people have been injured in that time. Ibrahimi and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Abdel-Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jassem </PERSON>, arrived in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> earlier Wednesday seeking to enforce an Arab League-brokered truce that began April 28. It scaled down indiscriminate bombardment of population centers in and around <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. But it was violated repeatedly after three days because <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> rejected the second clause of the accord, refusing to lift a blockade of three illegal militia-run ports. The blockade, through which <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> wanted to restore government authority and gather taxes worth $ 100 million a year, ignited the latest fighting. Druse and Syrian gunners, who outnumber <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces by 3-1, retaliated by firing at <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> ports, then besieged the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> heartland and trapped some 1 million Christians in a 310-square-mile enclave. <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> now has `` accepted to implement the decision adopted by the Arab foreign ministers which calls for lifting all blockades imposed on all air and sea ports.'' <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> airport, the country's only international air transport facility, was closed by Christian shellfire March 12. <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> also agreed to reopen road crossings that link <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Moslem and Christian sectors for three months while the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> brokers a comprehensive settlement. `` I can say the cease-fire has taken effect today after the settlement of the ports dispute. The observer force will begin arriving soon,'' <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON> said, but did not give a date. An aide to <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON> proposed deploying Arab observers at the disputed ports, where <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has charged militias also run guns and drugs. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> agreed to the envoy's compromise. Kuwaiti Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> panel on <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, stressed Wednesday that the observers will be sent only after the cease-fire is consolidated. `` We are not prepared to sacrifice any Arab brethren in the continued shelling and exchange of fire,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> has welcomed the deployment of an Arab observer team, saying it also would monitor the 40,000 Syrian soldiers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, whom Christians accuse of breaking a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate by siding with the Moslems. The observers' presence is expected to loosen <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s grip as <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s sole powerbroker.
