 and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> think tank on superpower relations. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said putting together a defense budget `` will be hard enough to do given the deficit. But the problem is compounded by uncertainty about the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' The chairman pointed out that only the executive branch can negotiate agreements with the Soviets, but a committee `` is in a better position for expansive given-and-take and exploration of new ideas.'' That raised the ire of <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, who wondered why <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't invite <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> `` to give us expert testimony on stopping terrorism. `` <LOCATION> Gorbymania </LOCATION> has struck with a vengenance in the halls of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. We have initiated our own phrase to mimic the Soviets _ ` parrotstroika,''' <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> senator also said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should not be a forum for Soviet propaganda. In response, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said that if <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> `` fears that hearing what the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION> have to say _ and putting them through a grilling on what they have n't talked about publicly _ amounts to making ` the committee process a forum for Soviet propaganda,' I feel sorry for him.'' <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, in a telephone interview late Wednesday, said he did n't `` need help from Soviet military planners Les believes the Soviets are here to be grilled. I expect him to be keenly disappointed.'' Asked if the criticisms would result in any bad feelings, <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> said, `` No. Les and I are good friends. We've worked together for a long time. This is not the first time and it wo n't be the last.''
