<HEAD>Eritrean Rebel Leader Urges U.S. To Help End War With Ethiopia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits to add cycle designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An African rebel leader urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday to help end the protracted war between the strategically placed province of <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and the Soviet-backed government of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Isaias </PERSON> <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON>, Secretary General of the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said he hoped to convey his views to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials and lawmakers, although he declined to say whom he would be meeting <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, who said <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> is the most senior Eritrean rebel leader ever to visit here, also declined to say whether they would meet with him. <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> said he did not have any specific initiatives to offer, but hoped the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would `` contribute to a lasting solution'' for the conflict by helping bring the sides to the negotiating table. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy rejects <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>'s demands for secession from <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, advocating negotiations between the sides to end what has become, at 27 years, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s longest war. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials have occasionally met with members of the <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION>, the largest of several Eritrean groups. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> also maintains ties with the government of Ethiopian Military Chairman <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON>, although relations have deteriorated since <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> switched allegiance to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1977. <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON>'s visit comes at a time when <LOCATION> Mengistu </LOCATION>, suffering economic woes and military defeats to the rebels, is also making overtures to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration. `` <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s prospects are bleaker than ever,'' <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> contended at a seminar sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, an independent think tank. The <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION>, which is backed by several <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> governments but relies mostly on captured <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> weaponry, has claimed significant military victories over the past year. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials believe the organization controls about 75 percent of <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>, which overlooks a key water route to the oil fields of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, but that the government retains control of the province's major ports and cities. Officials here say the government is also under pressure from its main arms supplier, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, to end the costly war. <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, despite claims to the contrary, continues to arm the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> government. Nonetheless, the <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> is `` among the first who hope to benefit'' from recent cooperation between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in resolving regional conflicts around the world. <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> said such superpower cooperation, as evidenced by agreements ending the Soviet occupation of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> occupation of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, has made his organization optimistic about prospects for negotiations with <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> is still holding out for its 1980 proposal to conduct a referendum that would determine whether <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> remains an autonomous part of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> or secedes from it altogether, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> has in the past proposed third-country mediation to end the war with <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> but has spurned proposals for <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to bring the sides together. <PERSON> Afwerki </PERSON> rejected claims that his group is Marxist in nature, calling that a pretext for past `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indifference,'' and said the <ORGANIZATION> EPLF </ORGANIZATION> represented varying economic views and was committed to a free economy.
