<HEAD>Rector of Paris Mosque Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Hocine </PERSON>, rector of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mosque </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and considered the top Moslem religious authority in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, died Wednesday night after suffering a heart attack, officials said. He was 77. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> was evacuated by helicopter Wednesday evening from the <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crillon </ORGANIZATION>, where visiting <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is staying, to the <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> military hospital after the heart attack. A statement issued by the mosque said <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> died at 10:30 p.m., shortly after being admitted to the hospital. It said the rector's body would be returned to his homeland, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, on Friday. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> was made rector of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> mosque in 1982. He often acted as a spokesman for French Moslems, a role disputed by some, and as a liaison between the French government and the Moslem community. As many as 3 million Moslems live in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, making it the nation's second religion after Roman Catholicism. It was not immediately known whether <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> had met with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> at the Crillon. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> chairman was attending a dinner given by Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> at the close of a two-day official visit. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, with his tinted spectacles and astrakhan hat, was a well-known figure to the French media, appearing in occasional television interviews and commenting on political developments affecting the Moslem community. He became for many a soothing and fatherly symbol of a moderate Islam. At the height of the scandal of <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s `` The Satanic Verses,'' <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> advised the French not to pay so much attention to this `` disrespectful writer.'' Iranian leader <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> issued a death sentence on <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, saying he had blasphemed Islam in his book. <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> neither spoke nor understood French when he succeeded <PERSON> Si </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamza </PERSON> <PERSON> Boubakeur </PERSON>, who for years was a powerful but controversial figure at the head of the mosque in the Latin Quarter on the <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. From a notable religious family near Constantine, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> was educated in North African centers of Islamic learning such as <LOCATION> Kerouan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Fez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. He worked for religious reform in French colonial <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> to help return the North African land to its Arab and Islamic character. Following Algerian independence, he spent four years as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. As rector of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Mosque, his human qualities soon won him respect from Algerian Moslems, who make up the largest part of the French Moslem community. He took to opening the doors of the mosque in winter to provide shelter for the homeless. The mosque, inaugurated in 1926, is the largest place of Moslem worship in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.
