<HEAD>Warhol's Red Marilyn Sells For $4 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s portrait, `` Red <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>,'' a 1964 depiction of <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, brought $ 4 million at auction Wednesday, a record for a work by the artist. The previous high for a Warhol painting was $ 3.9 million, said <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s. That painting sold last year, also of the late actress, depicted her face 20 times and is called `` <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> -LRB- Twenty Times -RRB-.'' `` Red Marilyn'' had a presale estimate value of between $ 1.5 million and $ 2 million. The actual selling price was $ 4,070,000, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said the auction Wednesday at <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s fetched $ 31.7 million for 60 works of art. The auction of contemporary art continues Thursday. `` Colored Alphabet,'' an oil and paper collage by <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> sold for $ 3.5 million, the second highest price bid on Wednesday but not a new record for a Johns. Other artist records at the <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction included: _ $ 715,000 for an <PERSON> Ellsworth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> painting, `` Black Triangle With White.'' _ $ 880,000 for a <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motherwell </ORGANIZATION> painting, `` Elegy to the Spanish Republic No. 134.'' All prices include a 10 percent house commission. `` August Day,'' an oil on canvas painting by <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON> sold for $ 2.7 million. A <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> triptych, a series of three drip paintings on three canvasses in black, red and yellow brought $ 2.2 million. `` Things on the Wall'' by <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> sold for $ 1,012,000. The auction Wednesday at <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s is the second day of a 12-day selling spree at that auction house and its rival _ <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. The two houses are expected to sell 4,400 pieces of art for more than $ 500 million. On Tuesday, record prices were set for 27 contemporary artists at <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. Total receipts of $ 78.6 million there set a record for a contemporary art auction. Another Pollock drip painting, `` Number 8, 1950,'' painting sold for $ 11.5 million at the <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s auction. `` Triptych May-June,'' done by <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON> in 1973, inspired by the suicide of the artist's close friend, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyer </PERSON>, fetched $ 6.2 million. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s `` Red <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON>,'' which depicts a ruby-lipped <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> as First Lady in 1963, sold for $ 750,000 _ more than twice its presale estimate. On Saturday, a <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION>'s sale of 20th Century decorative arts will include a two-story town house commissioned in 1950 by Mrs. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s on May 10 and 11 will feature five Monets, seven <PERSON> Picassos </PERSON>, 10 <ORGANIZATION> Renoir </ORGANIZATION> and four works by <PERSON> Degas </PERSON>.
