<HEAD>Misdemeanor Charges Filed Against 9 Companies In L.A. High-rise Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after fire gutted 4 -LCB- floors of the 62-story <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> tower and killed a worker, prosecutors filed 12 misdemeanor charges against nine companies Wednesday in connection with the blaze. Two counts of the complaint filed by the district attorney and city attorney referred to the death of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Handy </PERSON>, 24, a maintenance man who died May 4, 1988, after riding an elevator to the 12th floor, where the fire started, to investigate an alarm. Forty other people suffered smoke inhalation in the city's worst high-rise fire, which caused more than $ 450 million in damage. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Guthman </PERSON> said there is a three-year statute of limitations on filing felony charges. The decision to file misdemeanor charges, he said, was prompted by the misdemeanor statute of limitations which runs out Friday. If convicted, the defendants face various fines ranging from $ 1,000 on municipal violations to $ 10,000 on state labor code violations Among those charged in the complaint were <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pedus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which was in charge of security. The corporations charged in the misdemeanor complaint included those owning part of the building or those involved in its security and maintenance. The charges alleged seven violations of the state Labor Code and five of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Municipal Code, including blocking a fire exit, failing to maintain fire equipment and failing to maintain an accident protection program. The charges also allege failure to call in an alarm and failure to notify the Fire Department of inoperative equipment. Others charged with violations were <ORGANIZATION> Equitable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cosco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maintenance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maintenance </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION>. Cosco was installing fire sprinklers at the time of the fire, and was charged in connection with the closing of water mains in the building. During the blaze a ring of flame roiled around the 12th through 15th floors for nearly four hours, showering streets with glass and flaming debris and chasing people to the roof where 10 were plucked to safety by helicopters. Others fled down smoky stairwells. Thirty-seven maintenance workers and three firemen were treated for smoke inhalation. The cause of the conflagration was never determined because the 2,000-degree fire destroyed clues, but investigators eliminated arson as a possibility. The 859-foot-tall building had no sprinkler system because it was built in 1973, a year before fire codes were modified to require sprinklers. The 62-story tower was the tallest in the city at the time of the fire.
