<HEAD>Edwina Murphy, Who Sued Over Tainted Transfustion, Dead of AIDS Complications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman who sued a hospital after she contracted AIDS through a blood transfusion has died from complications of the disease. <PERSON> Edwina </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, 48, died at her family home last Thursday. She filed suit against <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> in December 1983 after becoming infected with the virus through unscreened blood. Officials later discovered the blood had been donated by a known heroin addict who died two months after <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> received the transfusion. At least three other people have died from the same blood, said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s lawsuit alleges gross negligence and seeks $ 1.5 million in damages. The hospital had fought to keep the case from going to trial, arguing it should be decided through arbitration. In September 1988, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> appellate court overturned a lower court decision ordering the case to trial. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
