<HEAD>Students Protest Defense Research at UMass, Tuition Hikes at CUNY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct overline.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teaching Assistants, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 University of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> students opposing Pentagon-funded research took over campus offices for the third time in two weeks Wednesday in one of several college protests around the nation. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Berkeley </ORGANIZATION>, nearly all the 3,200 graduate research and teaching assistants staged a walkout to demand recognition for their union. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, students who took over buildings at <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> campuses last week to protest a proposed tuition hike continued their occupation despite Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s veto of the proposal late Tuesday. Students, concerned about possible spending cuts, asked <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> to meet them at a `` neutral site'' in <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, up to 175 people gathered among `` for-sale'' signs put up on <ORGANIZATION> Mercer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> for a 24-hour `` read-in'' to protest a decision to close the campus in June 1990. Students at <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> who say a planned memorial to the four students slain by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> there in 1970 is not big enough planned a protest on the 19th anniversary of the shootings Thursday. In <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, about 150 students marched to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> after an afternoon rally at the Student Union. About half that number pushed aside three campus police officers trying to block the entrance to the 2 -LCB- - story annex to the <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towers </ORGANIZATION> `` We did n't think we'd be able to get into that building,'' said organizer <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Leavitt </PERSON>, a 22-year-old junior at the 25,000-student campus. `` We thought they would be smart enough to see the potential target, and they were n't.'' Police closed the building to all but faculty members who work there, and locked a corridor holding the protesters to keep them from taking over more offices. Officers guarded other buildings. As the takeover continued late Wednesday, university administrators agreed to make public all documents relating to the research, and said a panel of students, faculty and administrators would be formed to discuss its future. The announcement followed a meeting of students, faculty and administrators. The two previous takeovers of other campus buildings resulted in 68 arrests. The <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> walkout by over union recognition came with just two weeks to go before final examinations. `` Hey, hey! Ho, ho! Union busting's got to go!'' sign-carrying teaching and research assistants chanted as they demonstrated at every major entrance to the campus. Their union, the Association for Graduate Student Employees, is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>. The students say they are underpaid, overworked and often forced to go without health and other benefits. About 90 percent ot the 3,200 graduate assistants took part in the walkout, the association claimed. There are about 9,000 graduate students at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. According to a selective survey by the association of 307 classes through Wednesday afternoon, 66 percent were canceled, 25 percent were less than half-full, and 9 percent were at capacity. University spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Debley </PERSON> said the results were not necessarily representative of the campus, which has 23,000 undergraduates. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, students released a list of demands that included no staff or faculty layoffs in the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, more social services for students and amnesty for protesters. `` We will not relinquish the buildings at this particular time because Governor <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has not met all of our demands,'' <PERSON> Abdallah </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, said at a news conference at <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` One of our major demands is to meet with <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> reiterated he would not meet with students while sit-ins continued. `` I'll talk to them when they're legal,'' he said in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>. `` If there's anything that education should start with, the first rule is you live by the law.''
