<HEAD>North Carolina Legislature Regulates Fetus Disposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fetuses aborted in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> would be disposed of only through burial, cremation or approved types of incineration unless used for research under a bill enacted Wednesday by the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. The House of Representatives approved the bill 91-0. It cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by a wide margin, and is expected to become law Thursday when signed by Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> and House Speaker <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Mavretic </PERSON>. The bill was the idea of Sen. <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a funeral director. He did not introduce the bill because he said he felt it would appear he had a conflict of interest. It was sponsored by Sen. A.D. Guy. The bill's disposal requirements do not apply to fetuses used for medical research and development of pharmaceuticals. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, a leader in the battle to reduce <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s fund for poor women's abortions, said he never envisoned the fetus-disposal bill as having any effect on the debate over whether abortion should be legal. The bill directs the state <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> to adopt regulations on fetus disposal in accordance with the requirement that fetuses `` be disposed of in a manner limited to burial, cremation or approved hospital type of incineration.''
