<HEAD>ABC Engineers and Technicians Reject Contract Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An overwhelming majority of engineers and technicians who work for <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to reject what the network called its final contract offer, union officials said. The company said it would meet with leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technicians </ORGANIZATION>, but only to reiterate its position. `` We want to meet with the union as soon as possible to make sure the leadership and its members understand that the terms of our final offer will not be renegotiated,'' said company spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Matson </PERSON>. The union's chief negotiator, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, said he would meet with company officials, and expressed optimism they would negotiate further. `` That's what the collective bargaining process is all about,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` We're not in a strike-vote situation yet.'' A dozen of <ORGANIZATION> NABET </ORGANIZATION>'s 18 bargaining units voted to reject the company's proposal, said union spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Krieger </PERSON>. WLS-AM radio news writers, who are considered part of a 19th unit, also rejected the offer. All units must ratify a contract before it can take effect, <PERSON> Krieger </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Matson </PERSON> said the company felt `` sad and dismayed'' about the rejection. The number of workers represented is disputed. <PERSON> Krieger </PERSON> said there are 2,477 workers, while <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> says there are 2,150. The union did not release the vote tally. Union negotiators had recommended rejection of the offer, which was made after a month of negotiations that ended March 31. About 85 percent of the workers are engineers who handle cameras, lights and audio equipment and other technical tasks. The union also represents news writers, mail messengers, receptionists, wardrobe specialists and others. The average engineer makes $ 47,000 in base pay, <PERSON> Krieger </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said that with overtime the average engineer earns about $ 70,000. The rejected contract would have provided a one-time 10 percent ratification bonus if approved by May 15, in lieu of a raise in the first year. The bonus drops to 3 percent if the contract is ratified after May 15. The rejected pact also would have provided 3 percent wage increases in the second and third years and a 5 percent lump sum bonus in the fourth year. The offer also included a virtual guarantee that none of the about 2,000 full-time television employees would be laid off in the contract's first three years. Capital Cities-ABC said the offer would mean the layoffs of 60 or 70 radio engineers soon after ratification. The union put the figure closer to 125. <ORGANIZATION> NABET </ORGANIZATION> last struck <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> for 20 weeks in 1977 and for nine weeks in 1967. The union struck <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 for 17 weeks.
