<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv04   05-03 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 04,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday May 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Equity Credit: Handle With Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Among the many financial innovations of the 1980s, few have achieved as much broad popularity as the home-equity loan. It is n't hard to understand why. Home-equity loans serve as a convenient way to tap one of the nation's greatest pools of wealth. On top of that, changes in the laws have given them a special tax status. In contrast to most other types of consumer borrowing, interest paid on the typical home-equity loan remains fully deductible, within specified limits. But with all their advantages, home-equity loans also carry with them more potential risks and drawbacks than many people realize, financial advisers say. As <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> at the accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Laventhol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horwath </ORGANIZATION> puts it: `` Home-equity loan agreements, like cigarette packages, should carry a consumer warning in large type _ ` Caution! This loan could be hazardous to your financial health.''' The biggest pitfall in home-equity borrowing _ the risk of losing your house if you ca n't keep up with payments _ has been widely publicized, and deservedly so. This point alone makes a powerful case against using home-equity credit for any frivolous or short-term purpose, such as a vacation or a shopping spree. Ideally, the money borrowed should finance an asset with a vaue at least as great as the total cost of the loan, and expected to last at least as long as the term of the loan. The most obvious example of this kind of asset would be improvements to the property itself. `` Say you take out a 10-year home equity loan to finance a new car,'' <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> observes. `` The car is gone long before you've paid off your loan. By stretching the debt over so long a period, you're just racking up huge interest charges.'' This may seem to be plain common sense. But <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> points out that there are some other possible perils with home-equity loans that are n't so readily apparent. Home-equity credit often is touted as an inexpensive way to borrow, since lenders generally charge lower interest rates on loans backed by such solid collateral. Although that may be true in principle, <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> says, appraisal costs, other up-front charges and annual account fees make some equity loans a lot more costly than the stated interest rate suggests. Watch out in particular, he counsels, for deals with bargain-basement `` teaser'' interest rates that can be raised sharply just a few months after the loan is made. In many home-equity deals, borrowers are allowed to pay only interest charges for a period of time without repaying any of the principal. Whatever advantages that may afford, <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> points out, it makes a loan more expensive than a conventional arrangement in which payments cover both interest and part of the principal. That's because the balance due remains at its original, high level. Furthermore, such a setup typically leaves you faced with a `` balloon'' payment at the end of the loan's term, which may or may not be easy to finance at that time. `` If you're seriously considering a home equity loan, shop around,'' <PERSON> Ellentuck </PERSON> concludes. `` Look for a loan that imposes no points on closing, offers a low cap on the increase in your variable interest rate, and charges annual fees of $ 20 or less.'' End advance PM Thurs May 4
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890503-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-89 1307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv04   05-03 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 04,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, May 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Why We Save So Little</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One reason why Americans save so little is the bomb, said the professor. If there's no tomorrow, that is, you'll just be a gone fool This is the latest contribution to the literature of why Americans do n't save more of their income. It is now a massive collection and growing; no academic can retain his reputation without taking a stab at the problem. The bomb thesis has been developed by <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Slemrod </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>. Based on his studies of 20 non-communist nations, the low-saving American registers the highest level of fear of nuclear war. In 1986, he explains, 49 percent of his American respondents felt there was an `` even or better-than-even chance'' of a nuclear war within 10 years. At the same time, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings rate was 19th. Only <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s rate was lower. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, on the other hand, only 15 percent of those surveyed in the same year believed the chance of nuclear war within a decade was 50 percent or better. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s savings rate was bettered only by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Slemrod </PERSON> believes the evidence might compel a lot of economists to revise their views of why Americans save relatively little. In the past, he says, `` a lot of people have been blaming it on taxes and the social security system.'' And, you might add, on dozens of other things. On demographics, for example. A surge of 25-to-34-year-olds has been coursing through the economy. They must buy furniture, houses, cars, children's clothing and such with money that otherwise might have been put into savings. According to the theory, as these yuppies become older they'll transmogrify into couch potatoes They will sit before their television sets, content not to keep buying and traveling. They will save and invest for the future. That's just one notion. Among the others is that the methodology by which savings statistics are amassed is faulty. As some explain it, Americans use their houses as banks, but the statisticians do n't count that as saving. Social Security and private pension plans have been blamed. They make Americans complacent about their futures, it is said, although that notion is receiving a severe jolt from the actual, painful experiences of retirees. There is no end to the possibilities that have been seriously studied at academic institutions, analyzed by elected officials and speculated on by economists. But there are also some very obvious reasons that require no study. Such as: _ In <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, savings are taxed It used to be even worse: Savings were taxed while debt earned the borrower a great tax deduction. In regard to housing debt it remains so. Even credit card debt still gets a small deduction. The tax system in many other countries encourages saving, even exempting some earned interest from the tax collector. That idea caught on strongly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> a decade or so ago with <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounts </ORGANIZATION>. But IRAs have since been weakened. Taxes on interest earnings are deferred, but no longer is there a tax deduction. _ In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, keeping up with the <ORGANIZATION> Joneses </ORGANIZATION> is a much derided but much practiced philosophy of life This is a consumer society, not a saver society. If you do n't think so, examine the basic theme of many advertisements: If your neighbor has something why do n't you? Are n't you as good in every way as your neighbor? Then demonstrate it. Consider some of the other themes: One car is not enough. Neither is one bath in your house. In fact, one house is n't enough; good heavens, what do you do on weekends? Save? Banks are for saving, are n't they? Maybe not, as you might conclude from examining the literature you receive from them. How many seek to have you save with them? How many offer you credit instead? The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personal savings rate rarely exceeds 6 percent, compared with 20 percent or so in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. It is indeed puzzling, and social scientists will question each other about it for many academic years. The answer, however, is far more likely to come directly from the source _ from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> consumer, who may indeed save little because of the bomb, but who also might be borrowing more for the same reason.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, May 4.</NOTE>
