<HEAD>Roxana Zal Plays Jessica McClure's Mother in ABC Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roxana </PERSON> <PERSON> Zal </PERSON> says she formed a quick friendship with <PERSON> Cissy </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> after playing the young mother in the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> movie `` Everybody's Baby: The Rescue of <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>.'' `` We were very excited to meet each other,'' said <PERSON> Zal </PERSON>. `` It was strange at first. A little awkward. Then we got along great. I think we formed a bond. We write to each other. We're keeping in touch. `` Neither of us had any walls up. We both wanted to help each other. <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> took to me, too. She climbed right up on my lap.'' The two-hour movie, airing Sunday on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, is about the rescue of 18-month-old <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> after she fell down an abandoned well near her home in <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, on Oct. 14, 1987. She was trapped 19 feet underground in a space only eight inches wide. `` It's a real ensemble movie,'' said <PERSON> Zal </PERSON>. `` It shows how the whole town came together to save the life of this child.'' <PERSON> Zal </PERSON> said she had talked to <PERSON> Cissy </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> several times on the telephone before she started the role. `` I think it was better that I did n't see her until afterward,'' she said. `` I would have been nervous if she'd been on the set. We tried to make it as accurate as possible, but there may have been a few dramatic changes.'' The movie also stars Beau Bridges as Police Chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Czech </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Hingle </PERSON> as Fire Chief <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> as <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, the victims' assistance volunteer who helped the <ORGANIZATION> McClures </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> as <PERSON> Chip </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON>'s father. The movie was filmed largely on location in <LOCATION> Bellflower </LOCATION>, a city about 12 miles southwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` They made it look just like the original site,'' said <PERSON> Zal </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wunsch </PERSON>, the reporter from KMID-TV who plays himself, said it was so similar it brought back all those terrible thoughts.'' <PERSON> Zal </PERSON>, who won an Emmy in 1984 for her role in `` Something About Amelia,'' said she had followed the story of <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON> and was interested when her agent called about the offer. `` My first thought, however, was that it might be difficult,'' she said. `` Some films based on news events sound great, but the scripts do n't always work out. I knew it would be difficult to turn those 56 hours into a good movie. But the script turned out well, and I liked it. I like the role, too, because I get to play a mother. I've always played daughters and teen-agers before.'' <PERSON> Zal </PERSON> worked on the role while continuing her studies as a second-year student at <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm studying world arts and cultures,'' she said. `` I switched from theater arts. I get dance, music, art history and anthropology. My theater major had too many technical classes and labs. You had to take all the production courses first before you got to the fun stuff. I'm more interested in acting, directing and playwriting. I'm trying to develop my writing skills.'' Her most recent project was `` Goodbye, Miss 4th of July'' for the Disney Channel. It was based on the true story of <PERSON> Niki </PERSON> <PERSON> Janus </PERSON>, a member of a Greek immigrant family who fought back against discrimination by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> in 1917. The movie also starred <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chantal </PERSON> <PERSON> Contouri </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gossett </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. She made her film debut as <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Voight </PERSON>'s daughter in `` Table for Five. She was also in `` Testament,'' `` River's Edge,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schoolbreak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> `` God, The Universe and Hot Fudge Sundaes'' and played the daughter of an alcoholic in the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> movie `` Shattered Spirits.'' `` After the commercial I was in a pilot,'' she said. `` Then I decided I did n't want to do a series and prayed it would not go. I really do n't want to do a series. I would n't be able to go to college if I was in a series. `` I started acting when I was 11. I'd wanted to start when I was 8, but my parents would n't let me. Finally an aunt told them to let me try it or I'd grow up resenting them. I can pick and choose my roles. My parents have provided very well for me and I do n't have to take anything just to pay the bills.'' She said she was considering several things for the summer. `` It's so hard to find a good script and the competition is so tough,'' she said. `` That's why it's good to be in school. I'm not just sitting around waiting for the telephone to ring.''
</TEXT>
