<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drugs and Ripoffs a Blessing To This Test Developer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Testing Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug abuse has been very, very good to <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON>. So has theft. <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON> has built a career out of finding people who steal and use drugs _ and helping prospective employers steer clear of them. With a doctorate in industrial psychology, Lousig-Nont has developed a series of tests he says help companies screen job applicants based on their own admissions of attitudes and behavior. Last year <ORGANIZATION> Lousig-Nont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> sold 300,000 honesty tests, and business is booming. `` There's been a tremendous influx this year because of the anti-polygraph legislation,'' he said, referring to a recent law that bans most private employers' use of lie detector tests. With sales exceeding $ 1 million last year, <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON>'s business has grown at an annual average of 57 percent since he began selling a comparatively crude version of his now-patented honesty tests in 1978 He predicts sales will double by 1990. Lousig-Nont was a police officer in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, in the 1970s when he developed a reputation for interrogating suspects by using a low-key, straightforward approach. His 95 percent confession rate made him a stand-out, he said in an interview. `` I was sort of blown away by the fact that if I asked someone a question, they'd usually give you the answer,'' he said. `` If they lied to you, they became so guilty looking and would start pulling at their collar or something that it was obvious.'' It was that same approach that led him to develop the tests now used by companies nationwide. Persistently surprised at how much people would tell him if he asked, <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON>'s first test contained 100 true-false questions. Since then it has been refined and now is laced with what <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON> called `` control'' questions to help determine whether the applicant is generally truthful. He said the tests provide an assessment of a prospective employee by measuring his or her `` propensity to become involved in job dishonesty.'' The tests, available in English and Spanish, sell for between $ 6 and $ 15 each, including the cost of an evaluation analysis by <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON>'s company. It is substantially cheaper than a urine test to detect drug use. Now 40 and a millionaire, <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON> is one of a few individuals who can go up against much larger test marketers such as <ORGANIZATION> Stanton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Reid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>. His tests have been used by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convenience </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shack </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wackenhut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the national security firm, which has certain rights to market the tests. <ORGANIZATION> Wackenhut </ORGANIZATION> has `` intros into a lot of companies I could n't get my foot in the door,'' <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lousig-Nont </PERSON>'s next project, he said, is to develop a personality profile that will help determine whether an individual is suited for a particular job. For example, an accountant does n't have to be an extrovert, but the trait certainly is useful for a publicist.
</TEXT>
