<SECOND>BC-WKD--Virginia Woolf, Adv 12-14-1st Ld - Writethru, b0844,1227</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 12-14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Virginia Woolf as Incest Survivor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-12 of b0844 of May 1 bgng `Woolf's mother...'
with 3 grafs to CORRECT stepbrothers and stepsisters to half brothers and
half sisters and delete reference to Vanessa's first husband since she
only had one.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 We know <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> the writer, who gave us such ground-breaking novels as `` To the Lighthouse,'' `` Mrs. <PERSON> Dalloway </PERSON>'' and `` The Waves.'' We know <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> the feminist, who wrote the influential essay `` A Room of One's Own,'' and <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> the pacifist, who created `` Thoughts on Peace in an Air Raid.'' We know <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> the diarist, who logged the minutiae of her tortured life, and <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> the suicide, who put a heavy stone in her pocket and waded into the <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ouse </LOCATION>. But until now we have known very little about the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Woolf who was sexually abused throughout her youth. A noted Woolf scholar, <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON>, provides us with the first complete portrait of that woman in `` <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Woolf </LOCATION>: The Impact of Childhood Sexual Abuse on Her Life and Work'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Beacon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, $ 22.95 -RRB-. That Woolf had been abused was no secret _ she talked about it in speeches, letters, conversations and memoirs. But previous biographers have virtually ignored its impact on her life, treating it as an aberration in an otherwise happy Victorian household or perhaps even a hallucination of her `` madness.'' <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON>, a professor of English at <ORGANIZATION> Hunter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, is the first academician to thoroughly examine the abuse in light of modern-day research on incest survivors. `` It's not as if it was hidden as a topic in any of the biographies that have come before,'' <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> said in a recent interview at her Hunter office. `` But the major change is that in the last 10 years the work on incest and child abuse as a field has been so monumental that it enabled someone like me to use that work and to read her life in the context of what we now know the effect of incest and child abuse are.'' A brief outline of <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>'s family and the abuse suffered, based on <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>'s diaries, letters and recorded conversations with others: <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> and Sir <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>'s parents, had each been married before they wed in 1878 <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> were children of <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>'s previous marriage; <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> was a child of Sir <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s first marriage. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> had four children together: <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Thoby </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON>. <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>'s mother died when she was 13 and about that time her half brother, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, 14 years her senior, began sexually molesting her and her sister, <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON>. The abuse continued until <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> was in her early 20s and stopped only when she had a nervous breakdown after her father died and the household was broken up. <PERSON> Stella </PERSON>, <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>'s half sister who took over the running of the household after their mother's death, may have become Sir <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s lover after his wife died Late in her life, <LOCATION> Woolf </LOCATION>, in a period of intense self-analysis while writing her autobiography, suddenly remembered an incident that had apparently been repressed of being molested by her other half brother, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON>, when she was 6, in which he broke her hymen. <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> thinks <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> was devastated by the realization that the abuse began far earlier than she had believed. There is plenty of other evidence of the household as a dysfunctional family: <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION> had an erotic relationship with her sister, <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON>, that lasted into their 20s; <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>'s half sister, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON>, whom the family considered mentally deficient, was locked up in a distant room in the house for years before being trundled off to an asylum; <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>'s brother, <PERSON> Thoby </PERSON>, threw himself out of a window when he was 15; <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> had an affair with <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON>'s husband; after her divorce, <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON> took up with the homosexual lover of her brother <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON>. The list of family entanglements goes on and on and continues into the next generation. <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> reread everything that <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> wrote _ every novel, diary, letter, essay and fragment that has been preserved in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ and isolated every reference to <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>'s childhood or her fictional depictions of children `` It was when I did that that it was all thrown into stark relief, and I saw what she was trying to say,'' said <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON>. Once she learned how incest survivors talk about their experiences, <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>'s sometimes puzzling language suddenly made sense. In a letter to <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON>'s husband, for example, <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> writes almost flippantly about the sexual abuse the two suffered. <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> said that is an example of `` inappropriate response'' that victims of incest often use as a defense mechanism. `` The key to my own beginning to be able to figure it out was learning what the language of incest survivors is, learning the verbal strategies. How survivors of incest tend to create inflated pictures of their parents. ... `` I could n't figure out, for example, for the longest time why <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> wrote these revered portraits of her father. If you take them straight, that's one thing, but if you read how incest survivers typically talk about the family constellation, it makes an enormous amount of sense.'' One of the points DeSalvo makes in her book is that some of the symptoms of the bouts of `` madness'' Woolf suffered throughout her life _ depression, nervousness, irritability, tantrums _ are likely responses to the sexual abuse rather than the congenital condition it is often treated as. <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> was asked whether she ever thought <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON>, with her history of instability, was perhaps an `` unreliable narrator.'' The memory of the abuse by <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> when she was 6, for example, did not surface until <PERSON> Woolf </PERSON> was in her 50s. Can her memory be trusted? `` One of the biggest issues that always comes up in incestuous abuse is the extent to which people falsify memories. The paradigm used to be Freudian -LRB- the theory that patients' reports of sexual abuse were figments of their imaginations and based on desire -RRB-. ... All the recent work that has been done on incest survivors suggest rather the opposite _ that any memories are authentic, and the reason experts say this is that it is so disastrous, even today, to be labeled an incest survivor that no one would falsify that.'' <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> is the editor of `` Melymbrosia,'' an early version of <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>'s novel `` The Voyage Out,'' which she constructed from manuscripts, and co-editor with <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Leaska </PERSON> of `` <PERSON> Vita </PERSON> <PERSON> Sackville-West </PERSON>'s Letters to <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woolf </ORGANIZATION>.'' She has also written a book on <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawthorne </PERSON>. <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON>'s new book, as disturbing as the subject matter is, should be heralded for both its painstakingly thorough research and the delicate and fair handling of such a sensitive subject. This is a scholarly, not a titillating work. At the same time, it is enormously readable and imbued with the fascination and admiration that <PERSON> DeSalvo </PERSON> has for one of the greatest writers of this century.
</TEXT>
