<HEAD>Stock Exchange Chairman: No Current Need for 24-Hour Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> will implement computerized off-hours trading if companies and investment firms want it, but no such demand exists now, says the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Tuesday there has been no interest among <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> stock market participants to extend trading at the world's second-largest exchange beyond the current 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. hours `` The reason we have not done it is that our customers have said they do n't want it,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> told a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION> and Writers. But, he added, `` If there is any sign of interest out there at all we will try at least some off-hours trading.'' In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> surveyed securities brokerages and companies listed on the exchange, <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said, and `` 99 percent of all those people said, ` For God's sake, do n't do it. We are not interested in that now.''' The 197-year-old <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, second in size to the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, recently announced it would meet with customers, traders, institutional investors, listed companies and securities firms to re-gauge demand for off-hours trading. Under such a system, securities theoretically can be bought and sold when the exchange floor is shut down via computers that automatically match buyers and sellers from points around the world. The tiny <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> last month announced plans to start computerized 24-hour trading in the next 19 months. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s two futures markets also have announced they are developing after-hours trading systems <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> played down fears expressed by some securities industry experts that markets in foreign countries could siphon away business from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said the idea of a global market had not yet taken hold, and that overseas `` there's more potential than actual'' competition. `` Global markets and 24-hour markets, despite all the trendy talk, are not there because the customers do n't want them,'' he said. `` In the off-hours market there's not going to be a heck of a lot of orders,'' he added. `` Most pension funds are not going to wait until two o'clock in the morning to make a trade. The major pool of liquidity is going to be when this market opens.'' But <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> conceded that Japanese investors buying more stock in American companies listed on the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> exchange could some day pose a threat. He said 90 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies currently trade in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` It's new money that's never been in this market before. European money has been in this market for years. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s money has never been in this market,'' he said.
