<HEAD>Government Opens Securities Fraud Case Against Singer Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jurors at the securities fraud trial of Singer Co.. Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> are getting a short course in corporate takeovers, tender offers and other Wall Street terminology Before defense and prosecution lawyers began their opening statements to the jury Tuesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> took 10 minutes to explain to the jurors a number of financial terms that will come up repeatedly during the trial. The education was to continue today with a securities law expert expected to be the first government witness. In his opening statement Tuesday, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON> claimed that in 1985 and 1986, when he emerged on the corporate takeover scene, <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> `` sought to build a reputation for himself as a corporate raider'' through a series of lies. `` He lied to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, he lied to the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and he lied to the investing public,'' <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON> told the jury at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` In the past his lies brought him lots of money,'' said <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>, pointing at <LOCATION> Bilzerian </LOCATION>. `` Today they bring him to the bar of justice.'' <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, is accused of conspiracy, violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> dismissed one felony count last month but 11 other counts remain. None of