<HEAD>Nevadans Approve Tax To Cash In On Gold Bonanza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nevadans overwhelmingly approved a $ 52 million tax on miners who are now unearthing a gold bonanza that rivals production during this state's famed Comstock Lode era. Voters also approved a plan to double the money <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> can borrow for new construction. With all votes counted in Tuesday's special election, the two-year mining tax hike won 107,679 to 30,663. The other question won by 74,418 to 63,228. Voter turnout was a low 36 percent. Election officials around the state had predicted turnouts ranging from 30 percent to 40 percent of the more than 383,000 people eligible to vote. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> is the nation's leading producer of gold. During the past eight years, mines here have produced more than 12 million troy ounces of gold with a value of about $ 5 billion. At today's prices, that's equal to the value of all the gold and silver unearthed in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> during the two-decade <PERSON> Comstock </PERSON> <PERSON> Lode </PERSON> era that began in the late 1850s. The mining tax plan was submitted to voters after bitter debate in which Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> accused mining industry lobbyists of deceit in trying to derail his proposal for $ 118 million. The industry accused him of playing `` mine games.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> responded that the industry was trying to give the state `` the mine shaft.'' Casino owners, often targeted for tax hikes because gaming is <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s largest industry, also got into the fray, arguing that it's time to change the tradition in which the mining industry did not pay its fair share of taxes. After <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s plan was rejected in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the $ 52 million plan was endorsed by most of the people who had fought over any higher payments. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> joined in an advertising campaign with mining industry leaders to say that without approval, the state would face fiscal chaos. Had the measure lost, the leaders said, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> would have needed to remain in session an extra month to slash budgets and raise taxes. `` I think it's a positive thing for the state to have these revenues available,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said late Tuesday. He added he planned to meet with legislative leaders before deciding whether any more tax revenues are needed from the miners. Assemblyman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedway </PERSON>, Democratic chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, had opposed the $ 52 million plan. `` The amount they would be paying is just a drop in the bucket to what they should be paying,'' said <PERSON> Sedway </PERSON>. `` It -LRB- gold -RRB- is a non-renewable resource, and will be gone forever.'' The measure allows the state to impose a 5 percent tax on the net proceeds of mines during the next two years. The question resulted from an agreement during the 1987 Legislature between the mining industry, lawmakers and then-Gov. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gourdie </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he hoped passage would end this year's tax raising efforts in the Legislature. `` I'm delighted with the outcome,'' he said. `` I think the people have realized this is a reasonable and fair tax.''
