<HEAD>Bush Gets Tougher S&amp;L Standards in Banking Panel Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, It also, to CORRECT figure to $75 million sted
$75 billion and make it annual</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is getting everything he wanted and more from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to prevent <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls from tapping the taxpayers for another bailout, but only in exchange for new low-income housing initiatives. On a 49-2 vote just before midnight Tuesday, the committee approved <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s $ 90 billion savings and loan plan _ the largest financial bailout in the nation's history _ after spending four days toughening capital standards on the industry and adding a pair of housing components. Only Reps. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, voted no <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the bill did not have enough housing support for the poor and complained about the panel's rejection of his provisions attacking lending discrimination. <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said he wanted still tougher capital standards. As it now stands, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill would require the nation's 3,000 thrifts to put up at least $ 20 billion in new capital over the next five years _ twice as much as a version approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> two weeks ago _ to fulfill <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s promise of `` Never again. It also would divorce what critics had called a too-cozy relationship between S & amp; L regulators and the industry and devote $ 75 million a year to investigating and prosecuting fraud that is blamed for a major portion of the crisis. On a party-line vote, committee Democrats overrode administration objections to set aside some of the property the government is inheriting from failed S & amp; Ls for low-income housing. They also voted to require the industry to subsidize below-market mortgage rates for low-income families. Still, the overall package won praise from the administration. `` This committee exceeded everyone's expectations,'' Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said. `` They've achieved something very close to what we asked for.'' The biggest victory for the administration is a requirement that S & amp; L owners over the next five years reach a level of having at least $ 3 of their own money in `` tangible'' capital at risk for every $ 100 they lend. `` We've moved legislation that will deal with a significant part of the problem ... and passed tough capital standards _ better than the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill and, I would argue, better than the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> bill as well,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N </LOCATION>. The bill still has to go through three other committees _ including one where the erection of a formidable roadblock is anticipated later this month _ before a final vote by the full House. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, the banking committee's chairman who spearheaded the administration's drive for the tougher capital requirements, said industry lobbying efforts to weaken them already have shifted there And after that, new fights over the housing subsidies that were rejected in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as `` social engineering'' are expected to erupt in a conference of leading lawmakers from both houses before a final version is sent to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> this summer for his approval or veto. As proposed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and now approved by both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the plan will pump $ 50 billion over the next three years into a federal insurance fund to pay off depositors whose money was lost through speculative and often fraudulent lending by some 300 to 500 S & amp; Ls. Another $ 40 billion to cover the losses of institutions closed in the past two years plus anticipated failures over the next decade _ and also shore up the insurance fund _ will come largely from new or increased fees on the industry. Altogether, the bailout costs _ including interest _ are expected to total $ 157 billion by the year 2000 and $ 275 billion by the year 2020. The government share will be raised through a complex financing plan that keeps the problem off the federal budget and avoids a tax increase, but at an interest cost to taxpayers of $ 150 billion to $ 200 billion over the next 30 years. That arrangement is likely to be questioned at least one more time by the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, one of three panels yet to review the package. However, the next big showdown will not occur until the bill reaches the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which controls what issues can be revisited on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. The rules panel's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said in a letter last week he strongly opposes parts of the new capital requirements Industry and government records indicate that 14 S & amp; Ls in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> would have to raise a total of $ 700 million to $ 800 million in new capital over the next five years or shrink in size. Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, said he expects the housing provisions in the bill to be attacked on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, along with what he called one `` crystalizing amendment'' to stretch out the implementation of the tougher capital standards. But he predicted the fights there will be few and short. `` Everybody in the country and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> realizes we need to get this enacted and behind us,'' <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said. `` The bill should be signed by the president by the Fourth of July.''
