<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessOutlook     05-03 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Outlook,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed's Heller Sees Slower Growth, Steadying Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s tight-fisted monetary policy can curb inflation and prolong economic growth, but only if business leaders exercise some patience, a central bank official says. `` It takes time for monetary policy to relieve pressure on prices,'' <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> told the mid-year meeting of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday. `` What is needed now is a bit of patience to allow the policy that is in place to work.'' <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, in a luncheon address to about 100 executives, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is not out to take the `` proverbial punch bowl away.'' `` We would just like everyone to drink a bit more slowly so that the party can last a longer time.'' <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, who has been on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s seven-member board of governors since 1986, defended the tight rein the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has kept on the nation's money supply this year. That monetary policy has forced interest rates up in an effort to ease inflationary pressures by slowing business expansion. Recent economic data have indicated the economy is cooling down, but the inflation picture is more clouded. Sharp rises in wholesale and consumer prices earlier this year, along with a more recent surge in oil and gasoline prices, have prompted some economists to predict a new wave of strong inflation. The most pessimistic analysts see both recession and inflation ahead. But <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> foresees neither. In general, he said, the overall outlook `` is for modified growth and subdued inflationary tendencies.'' `` Put simply, I just do not believe that the preconditions for a sustained acceleration in inflation are now in place,'' he said. On the possibility of a recession, he added, `` the imbalances which traditionally precede a recession are not visible and indications are that the current expansion will continue.'' And on the inflation front, he said a second year of drought in the Corn Belt is unlikely and agricultural output should return to normal this year, bringing down food prices. Despite the rise in crude oil prices from about $ 17 to more than $ 20 a barrel since Jan. 1, `` recent history of the global oil market suggests that prices beyond $ 20 a barrel will probably not hold for long,'' <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said. Although economic growth is slowing, he said, the vigorous pace of corporate investment in plant and equipment expenditures is an encouraging sign, as is the promise of a bipartisan congressional agreement for the fiscal year 1990 federal budget. Reducing the federal budget deficit is essential for continued economic growth, <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said. `` Looking beyond the coming year, it is important that this progress will be sustained in future years as well until fiscal responsibility is again the norm.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> is an international network of more than 20,000 senior business executives.
</TEXT>
