<HEAD>Conference Split Over Aid For Developing Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with split over 3rd World financing.
No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 90 countries agreed today to support a ban on ozone-destroying chemicals by the year 2000, but they split over how to help Third World countries pay for safer technology. Delegates from 86 countries and nearly 100 non-governmental organizations at the U.N.-sponsored conference adopted a resolution calling for industrial countries to help developing nations replace equipment emitting harmful chlorofluorocarbons. But it made no specific funding proposals. <PERSON> Mostafa </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON>, head of the U.N. Environment Program, proposed an international climate fund to help Third World countries comply with the program to phase out chemicals that deplete the earth's shield of ozone But industrial countries led by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> objected, favored a bilateral approach. British Environment Minister <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> dismissed <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON>'s idea as `` simplistic. `` It has not been suggested who would run such a fund, how it would operate, on what criteria its funds would be raised, and from whom, and what would happen if they did not contribute,'' <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> told the conference. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the only country to make a solid proposal, offered to contribute 0.1 percent of its gross national income _ about $ 88 million _ to the climate fund, if other industrial nations do the same. <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON> suggested a working group from the 48 countries that ratified the 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Montreal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protocol </ORGANIZATION> draw up a specific funding plan and submit it next year. While politicians discussed finances, scientists questioned whether alternatives are at hand to replace the most harmful chemicals _ the chlorofluorocarbons used for refrigeration, insolvents and other industrial processes. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, of the Alliance for Responsible Chlorofluorocarbon Policy, said the <ORGANIZATION> Montreal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protocol </ORGANIZATION> was based on the assumption the chemicals could be substituted by hydrochlorofluorocarbons and other new and presumably safer variations. The new compounds are the best known replacements, but `` we do n't know enough about them,'' <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> told reporters. `` They can not be used until we have the answers to questions for their safety for the environment,'' said <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, whose alliance is a coalition of hundreds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries cooperating in the search for alternatives. `` There's no way that the deadlines can be met'' if the new chemicals are found to be unusable, he said. Non-governmental organizations said Tuesday's declaration `` does not go far enough,'' according to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. They called for a `` crash program'' to eliminate the chemicals by 1995. The four-day conference, the First Meeting of the Parties to the Montreal Protocol, was to update the 1987 document requiring signatories to halve by 1999 their production of five chlorofluorocarbons and three halons, which break down ozone and increase the risk of skin cancers and eye disease. Annual chlorofluorocarbon production is 1.14 million tons, two-thirds of which is produced by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> produces 12 percent and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> about 10 percent.
