<HEAD>Travelers Earnings Jump 48.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Travelers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday its earnings rose 48.5 percent in spite of a decline in revenue in the first quarter. The insurer said net income rose to $ 98 million, or 96 cents a share, on revenue of $ 3.2 billion, from $ 66 million, or 60 cents a share, on revenue of $ 3.3 billion in the same period a year ago. First-quarter results included net realized investment gains of $ 1 million, compared to realized investment losses of $ 11 million in the first quarter of 1988. The Travelers restated prior results to reflect a new accounting standard. The change resulted in a reduction in reported earnings of $ 7 million in the first quarter of 1989 and $ 6 million in the first quarter of 1988. Under the change, universal life and investment-type contracts are no longer included in premiums and current and future benefits, and realized investment gains and losses are now included in pretax income. `` First-quarter earnings benefited from the continued turnaround in Employee Benefits and improvements in our noninsurance subsidiaries,'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a written statement. Net investment income for the first quarter was $ 869 million, compared to $ 941 million for the same period a year ago. Premiums were $ 2 billion for the quarter, compared to $ 2.1 billion a year ago. Assets at the end of the first quarter were $ 53.9 billion, compared to $ 55 billion a year ago. The decreases reflected the divestiture of some businesses in 1988, the company said.
