<HEAD>Big Three Car and Truck Sales Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car and light truck sales by the nation's Big Three automakers in late April dropped 3 percent, compared with the same period a year ago when sales were moderately strong, the companies said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of 41,487 during the April 21-30 period this year compared with a rate of 42,772 during the same time last year. A 6.2 percent drop in car sales was offset partially by a 2.7 percent increase in light truck sales by the Big Three. For the entire month, when each of the companies offered wide-ranging incentive packages, car and truck sales were up 6.3 percent this year over last April. For the year through April, vehicle sales were down 5.7 percent compared with the same period last year. The companies have been looking closely at sales results after the usually strong March and April buying season got off to a slow start. The incentives are aimed at boosting vehicle sales, which sagged below expectations during the first three months of the year, and at forestalling production cuts later in the year. However, analysts have said they expected the companies to trim their production rates during the second half of the year, mainly through extended model-changeover times during the late summer and early fall. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales suffered the most during late April, running 7.4 percent behind last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s cars sold at an average daily rate of 7,980 this year, compared with a rate of 8,619 during the period last year. For the month, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were up 12.9 percent, and through the first four months of this year, car sales were 0.1 percent over last year's pace. The company's light trucks sold in late April at a rate 6.2 percent below the same period last year and through the first four months of the year sold 2.9 percent under the pace of a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said its car sales were off 6.1 percent in late April, going to a daily rate of 13,666 this year from a rate of 14,560 last year. Sales for the entire month were up 1.2 percent this year, and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> car sales since Jan. 1 were off 10.7 percent. Sales of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s light trucks ran 14.3 percent ahead of the pace the company set during late April last year, and for the year, truck sales were off 1 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> showed the smallest decline in car sales in late April, dropping 4 percent to a daily rate of 4,127 this year, compared with 4,299 last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales for all of April ran 2.9 percent behind last year's level and for the entire year 17 percent behind. Truck sales by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> were down 1.3 percent in late April and up 2 percent for the entire year.
