<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar closed narrowly mixed in light European trading Wednesday. Gold prices rose. Foreign exchange dealers said that on the eve of the Ascension Day holiday, when most European markets will be closed, the dollar held firm despite intervention by central banks, including the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. The central banks have been acting concertedly for days to sell dollars to keep the currency's exchange rate down. One <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> dealer said the dollar's firm tone reflected investor buying but others wondered how long the dollar can continue to resist central banks' intervention. Dealers said the dollar's short-term direction could be determined by the release on Friday of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures for April, an indication of the condition of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy last month. While markets in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were closed for the Constitution Day holiday, the dollar strengthened against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, trading late at 133.93 yen, up from Tuesday's closing 133.85 yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6847 late Wednesday, more expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $ 1.6845. Other late rates for the dollar in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared to Tuesday's late rates: 1.8900 West German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6830 Swiss francs, up from 1.6805; 6.3725 French francs, down from 6.3735; 2.1270 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,379.20 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50; and 1.1830 Canadian dollars, unchanged Gold bullion gained nearly $ 2 in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, The late bid price was $ 379.00 a troy ounce, up from $ 377.30 late Tuesday. The late bid price in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> was $ 377.95 an ounce, up from $ 377.50. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATIO