<HEAD>Administration Renews Threat to Veto Minimum Wage Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House said Wednesday that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will veto compromise legislation worked out by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to raise the mimimum wage from $ 3.35 to $ 4.55 an hour by 1991. Reacting to Tuesday's agreement between <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators on legislation to change the wage rate for the first time in eight years, White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> continues to believe the figure is too high. `` The president's position is the same, and he reiterated that'' during a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators, the spokesman said. `` His first proposal -LRB- for a $ 4.25 top rate -RRB- was his last proposal. ... He is prepared to veto the bill if they send it up.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stance sets up the first showdown on domestic policy involving the new president and the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> several weeks ago told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> there were enough <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> supporters of his position to sustain a veto. An override of a presidential veto requires two-thirds of those present and voting in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> also said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would hold to his earlier promise to veto the bill. `` I just want to set the record straight _ the president will not yield on this,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. In reaching consensus on a final bill so swiftly, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said, Democrats pushing the legislation `` in effect asked for a confrontation with the president.'' It took less than an hour Tuesday for the conferees to complete their work, thanks in large part to staff negotiations conducted during last week's congressional recess. Also contributing to the speedy resolution was that the major elements of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills were the same. Each called for raising the hourly minimum wage from $ 3.35 to $ 4.55 by October 1991 and for allowing employers to pay some new workers a subminimum training wage for two months. On the subminimum, the final product contains language very close to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version, allowing employers to pay new hires 85 percent of the minimum wage if the newcomers have not held a job for more than 60 days. Once an individual held a job for 60 days, he or she would never again be eligible to be paid the training wage. The legislation could reach the White House within two weeks, after passage by the separate houses. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said $ 4.25 an hour is the highest minimum he will accept, and even that support hinges on a six-month subminimum that could be paid to all new hires regardless of past job experience. Democrats sponsoring the legislation said they were prepared to confront <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with the measure and would attempt to override his expected veto, although they concede <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> currently has more than enough votes to stymie an override effort.
