<HEAD>Switch from Pro to Proprietor A Big Step</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> once earned a living by artfully whacking a little ball across expansive green lawns and sandy gullies, seldom thinking about the battles with <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Nature </PERSON> that go into golf course designs. Now that he's switched from pro to proprietor, he thinks of little else. Today, <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colbert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> owns or operates 14 public and private golf courses from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, with the number expected to expand into the 20s by the end of the year. <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> is rolling now, but he's learned the hard way that weather can make or break a good golf operation. `` This whole business evolves around water,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON>, 48, said in an interview. `` You may be plagued with too much or too little. Once a course is built, the only thing left is drainage, drainage, drainage _ whether it's yours or the Lord's. `` With our courses in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, the problem is too much water. In <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, it's too little.'' The exception was in 1984, when a rare <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> flood swamped a course where <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON>'s fledgling company had spent $ 1 million in remodeling work. `` It took $ 1.5 million and two years to fix it up,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said of damage to the old county-run <ORGANIZATION> Winterwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Course </ORGANIZATION>. `` That was our welcome to the golf course business.'' Today <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON>'s company has 500 employees at courses in nine states. <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> credits a bad back and a decade of duty on the 10-member PGA Tour Policy Board with nudging him into the golf course business. He served with the leaders of giant corporations, learning how to build companies and golf courses. By the time he left the board in 1984, the organization had built 12 TPC -LRB- The Players Club -RRB- courses. The courses are used as a PGA tournament course once a year, and the remainder of the year as public or private courses. They are operated by the PGA tour and `` are very good profit centers for the tour,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said. `` Being involved in the building of these courses peeked my interest in golf courses,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> recalled. <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> won his first pro title in 1969. By the time nagging back problems forced him to the sidelines 18 years later, he had won eight tournaments and more than $ 1.5 million in prize money. `` I did n't play half the time,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said of a four-year span beginning in 1976, when the back problems intensified. `` It looked like my career was over.'' A native of <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> grew up in the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Prairie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> and attended <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> on a football scholarship from 1959 to 1964, honing his golf skills as well. He called on old friend <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogler </PERSON>, who'd run the <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Country </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> for 23 years, when he cut a deal with the city of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> to take over the city course in 1981. `` I'd been a touring pro,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said. `` I did n't know much about the operational end of things.'' <PERSON> Fogler </PERSON>, who had twice served as <ORGANIZATION> PGA </ORGANIZATION> vice president, took over the management of the company, concentrating on construction and remodeling of courses. He remains a key to the company's operations, utilizing four decades of expertise in the golf course business The company took on its second project in 1983, <LOCATION> Clark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Winterwood </LOCATION> course It spent $ 1 million remodeling the course, located on the east side of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. A disastrous flood that swamped Las Vegas in 1984 caused $ 1.5 million damage to the course, and left a two-year rebuilding challenge. `` The second one almost killed us,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said. `` We had to get No. 3 -LRB- <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> -RRB-, No. 4 -LRB- <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dimas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- and No. 5 -LRB- <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> -RRB- to pay for No. 2. It was kind of like <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s Law took over. Whatever could go wrong did.'' Today <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON>'s company owns or operates courses in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. He declined to give a dollar value of his company. Besides long hours in his Las Vegas office and trips around the country checking out new course opportunities, he also serves as sportcaster analyst for the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> network </ORGANIZATION> at 18 golf tournaments a year. `` We look for problems,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said his search for new properties. `` We look for shortcomings. If we can identify and solve them, we're a serious buyer. We think more of a product, many times, than the people who own it. `` The art of this trade is buying something and making a profit. We'll take a bad facility as long as we know we can make it better.'' Did he ever dream he'd be a major player in the golf course business? `` I wish I could say I was that smart, but too many people know me,'' <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> laughed. `` I saw a tiny hole and I went through that door.''
