<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance for release Sunday, May 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Firms in New Round of Post-Crash Cutbacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic in AP Access under WALLEMPLOY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen months after the stock market crashed and took thousands of jobs with it, Wall Street still is feeling the aftershocks. Investor mistrust and high interest rates have triggered a recession in the securities industry, forcing a second wave of cutbacks at firms awash in profits in the mid-1980s. Despite rising prices that have pushed many stocks to post-crash highs, securities firms have reported weak first-quarter earnings or outright losses and slashed payrolls by about 2,600 workers in the last month. The cutbacks have pushed Wall Street layoffs to more than 25,000 since the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 508 points on Oct. 19, 1987, the largest single-day decline in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> history. `` At long last after a year of much lower levels of profitability, they realized they have to take the bulls by the horns and do something,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Perrin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lipper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's just like when you and I get a toothache, we take a day or two before we go see the dentist.'' The staff reductions are blamed on slow business in all segments, from low volume on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, to a dive in stock and bond underwriting, to declining merger activity. They also represent what Wall Street strategists like to call a `` correction'' _ a counter-reaction to a hiring frenzy from 1982 to 1987 in which securities firms expanded by 20 percent to 30 percent annually and fresh-faced business-school graduates made six-figure salaries. `` Some firms expanded a couple years ago like it was never going to end,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON>, who follows Wall Street for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` There's too much capacity and we're going through this painful retraction.'' Business is so bad that the Wall Street Journal, diary of the financial world, recently published a five-part series titled `` Wall Street's Recession,'' illustrated by cobwebs on a street sign in lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. Some symptoms of Wall Street's malaise: _ Total employment by NYSE-member brokerages has fallen from a peak of 262,100 employees in September 1987 to about 236,000 today, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association of brokerages The firms had hired more than 100,000 workers from the end of 1981 to the crash. _ Average daily trading volume on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> was 159 million shares in March, compared with a 1987 average of nearly 189 million shares and 1988 average of about 162 million shares _ Merger activity, an important source of business for Wall Street, has fallen to its lowest level in more than two years, according to <ORGANIZATION> IDD </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial reporting service In the first quarter of 1989, 708 deals worth $ 49.6 billion were completed, vs. 996 deals worth $ 101.7 billion in the previous quarter, IDD figures show. Even discounting last year's $ 25 billion <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> buyout, the biggest takeover in history, the value of completed deals was off about 25 percent. _ Fees generated by underwriting new issues of corporate stocks and bonds have plummeted In the first quarter of 1989, 305 new issues generated fees of $ 554.7 million, less than half the 692 new issues and fees of $ 1.35 billion in the same 1988 period, according to <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is selling its entire retail brokerage division of 2,300 workers, partly because of its bad image from an insider trading scandal but more from generally bad business Further large cuts are expected in <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> bond units. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> laid off 200 employees, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> dropped 30 professionals and <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reportedly has let go dozens of bond traders. Analysts forecast another 5,000 to 10,000 layoffs in coming months. `` We are in the midst of a very serious, chronic crisis,'' <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutfreund </PERSON>, whose firm lost $ 28 million in the first quarter, told a recent meeting sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> Some analysts said the public also has learned from the 1987 crash _ which Wall Streeters euphemistically have taken to calling a `` market break'' _ the lesson that the volatile nature of the market may not be worth the risk. With yields of 9 percent or more on money market funds and certificates of deposit, individual investors are steering clear of the riskier stock market. But for securities firms, commissions on money market investments made for customers are far lower than for stocks. `` Now we're just not addressing the issue of overcapacity. Now the revenues just are n't coming in,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a midsized <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> securities firm. Overall, <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON> said commission-generated revenues are down about 35 percent across the board. `` The public has generally decided to stay on the sidelines and take advantage of the high yields with the minimum amount of risk,'' he said. `` If you can get 9 or 10 percent on a risk-free basis, there's no point for someone with limited resources to speculate in the stock market.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cloonan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said the average stock holding among the 105,000 members of his organization has fallen 6 percent in the last two years, to about 29 percent of portfolios. `` The industry just kept spinning on their best day and best month and that's not how the world works,'' he said. But if business is so bad, why have some stock-market price barometers reached post-crash highs, with the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average poking through the 2,400 mark? Analysts attribute the rise to a strong dollar luring foreign investment into the market and to cautious trading by investors still participating. Also, they said recent corporate mergers and takeovers have sharply increased the value of some stocks. A still-strong economy has put corporate earnings about where they should be, analysts said. But without large numbers of transactions, Wall Street's firms do n't necessarily profit. Higher rent and salary costs from the boom days also have hurt securities firms. `` There is less volume in firms that have higher overheads,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief economist with <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` They find their profit margins on each trade are even lower than before. Ouch! Ouch!''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
