<HEAD>Arguments On Validity Of Bhopal Disaster Law End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday concluded hearing arguments on the legality of a law that empowered the government to represent all victims of the <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION> gas disaster, news reports said. A five-judge panel, headed by judge <PERSON> Sabyasachi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukharji </PERSON>, did not say when it will give its verdict on a group of petitions that sought to strike down the Parliament-approved law on grounds of unconstitutionality. The government, armed with the law, reached a $ 470 million settlement on Feb. 14 with <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. For compensation to the victims and survivors of the disaster The settlement will be scrapped if the panel upholds the petitions and declares the law unconstitutional.
