<HEAD>Late Buying Surge Sends Oil Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil and wholesale home heating oil futures finished higher Wednesday, lifted by a late spurt of buying on news that the disruption in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil production will last longer than than previously expected. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, gained 30 cents to settle at $ 20.10 a barrel, after a loss of 86 cents on Tuesday. Heating oil for June delivery was buoyed by the crude oil buying and ended the session up 0.25 cent at 47.86 cents a gallon. The contract had slipped 1.85 cents in the previous session. Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the June contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 1.86 cents lower at 69.39 cents a gallon following Tuesday's loss of 1.36 cents. Market participants were in a selling mood for much of the day and prices were weak. But, as the session was drawing to a close, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said repairs on its Cormorant Alpha platform in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> were likely to take longer than anticipated, delaying the resumption of operations until later this month. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s platform was damaged by an explosion April 18, causing the shutdown of a transportation and production system for Brent crude, a key international grade of crude oil. The disruption has taken about 470,000 barrels a day off the world crude market. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> said that May 26 was a reasonable date on which to expect operations to return to normal but a resumption could take place as early as May 18. There had been speculation in the market that the resumption might occur next week. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON>, an energy broker at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said crude and heating oil futures also derived strength from continued selling in the gasoline futures pits. Gasoline prices had been bid steadily higher recently in anticipation of possible shortages due to the Exxon oil spill off the Alaskan coast in March and the seasonal increase in demand. <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said trading volume Wednesday was moderate.
