<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar firmed Wednesday against most major currencies in quiet worldwide trading even though central banks intervened to push down its value. Gold prices moved higher. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $ 377.40 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up $ 1.05 from late Tuesday. Currency dealers said reported dollar selling by a handful of central banks, including the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, failed to dampen the market's overriding bullish sentiment toward the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. `` At best you can say it's holding the dollar from going higher,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` What we have here is a confrontation between the market and the central banks.'' Worldwide demand for the dollar has been high in recent weeks due to the continued strength of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy and relatively high American interest rates, which make dollar-denominated investments more attractive. Some dealers said the short-term direction of the dollar could be determined later this week, with Friday's release of April unemployment data. The markets were closed Wednesday in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for the Constitution Day holiday. But in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> the dollar strengthened against the Japanese yen, trading at 133.93 yen, up from Tuesday's closing 133.85 yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Later, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 134.295 yen from 134.275 Tuesday. Most European markets will be closed on Thursday for the the Ascension Day holiday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6847, more expensive for buyers than Tuesday's late $ 1.6845. Sterling fetched $ 1.6820 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, up from $ 1.68055. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared to Tuesday's rates, included: 1.89325 West German marks, up from 1.8919; 1.68705 Swiss francs, up from 1.68425; 1.18415 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18125; 6.3905 French francs, down from 6.3950; and 1,383.05 Italian lire, down from 1,383.25. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared to Tuesday: 1.8900 West German marks, up from 1.8875; 1.6830 Swiss francs, up from 1.6805; 6.3725 French francs, down from 6.3735; 2.1270 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,379.20 Italian lire, down from 1,379.50; and 1.1830 Canadian dollars, unchanged. On the Comex in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery rose to $ 378.40 a troy ounce from $ 377.80 Tuesday. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 377.95 an ounce from $ 377.50, and in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, to $ 379.00 an ounce from $ 377.30. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 376.55 an ounce, up from $ 375.95. Silver prices were mixed. On the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Comex </LOCATION>, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $ 5.635 a troy ounce from $ 5.617 Tuesday. But silver was unchanged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 5.65 an ounce.
