<HEAD>Wheat Prices Respond To Soviet Grain Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, with wheat prices up strongly following the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> announcement of additional subsidized grain sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. On other markets, cotton prices rose, energy futures were mostly higher, livestock futures were up and pork futures were mixed. Precious metals also were mixed. Wheat settled 1 cent to 11 cents higher with the contract for May delivery at $ 4.37 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent to 2 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 2.76 a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 2 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 1.87 cents a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 12 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 7.46 -RCB- a bushel. Wheat opened lower at the start of trading, surprising a market that expected a strong start for wheat futures. `` There were a lot of people who thought the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> business was already reflected in prices,'' said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Today's action showed that any kind of business outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be positive'' for the market. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration announced Tuesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will sell 1.5 million metric tons of wheat to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under the export bonus program. Soybeans futures rallied after mid-sesssion, helped along by continued strength in May soybean demand. `` With farmer preoccupation with field work, there is not a lot of soybeans moving to processors or to exporting channels,'' <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON> said. Corn was up modestly, with fairly good rains in Western corn-producing states weighing heavily on the market. Cotton futures prices rose sharply on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on reports of severe damage to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s cotton crop. The rally also was stimulated by commission house and local buying, said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, a cotton specialist for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> suffered losses in crops and livestock following four days of heavy rain and snow. `` This particular <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> problem has been with us for two weeks,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. `` But the news services have just begun to point it out and strengthened new crop orders.'' Cotton settled 1.04 cents to 1.33 cents higher with May at 66.33 cents a pound. Energy futures were mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as gasoline prices came under pressure in the wake of a <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report of increased imports. `` People were taking profits,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritterbusch </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Carson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOC