<HEAD>America West Confident about Purchase Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which has grown in six years to the 10th-largest air carrier in the nation, has no qualms about extending itself to the Northeast. `` We consider this one of the most profitable opportunities in our industry,'' Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> told a news conference Wednesday after announcing a $ 726 million offer for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' Northeast shuttle operation. <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> estimated his airline would need to hire 800 employees to run the shuttle. He said he expected annual revenue of $ 300 million to $ 400 million from the operation. <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> offered $ 390 million cash for the shuttle, with the balance in cash and debt assumption on 10 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757 aircraft, a press release said. However, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said the other $ 336 million included 21 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727s. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> does not want the 727s but would dispose of them as a credit back to Eastern or in other ways, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. The offer had to be made in haste, because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> had scheduled a May 12 hearing on the $ 365 million offer for the shuttle from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection March 9, and <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> must approve any sale of assets. If successful in its bid, <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> would operate the shuttle from its headquarters in this <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> suburb. `` This would improve our visibility on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, and it fits right into our specialty, which is high-frequency service in high-density markets,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is the nation's largest airline without any union-represented employees, and <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said the operation would be `` an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> operation, with <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> employees.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees would be interviewed for possible rehiring. Asked if he expected opposition from labor, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said he did n't think so, because the 800 jobs represent only a fraction of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s workforce. `` I think Eastern employees would be very enthusiastic,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said, `` because, first, the fringe benefits at <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> compare favorably with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s, and, second, the environment at <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is very good.'' In the last year, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> has applied for service to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and has ordered 25 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-300s or 757s for delivery between 1992 and 1995. Despite the $ 800 million order, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> was far from over-leveraged. The firm's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banker, <ORGANIZATION> Wertheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schroder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has assured company officers that the financing could be accomplished, he said. `` This seems like a large chunk. It's not,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. `` This is a $ 900 million company ... We've always been adequately financed, and we've never had a cash problem. We're well suited to take advantage of these opportunities.'' Started in mid-1983 with 280 employees and three 737s, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> today has about 8,500 employees and 70 planes. It serves 47 cities. It carried 12.7 million passengers last year, turning a $ 9.4 million profit on revenue of $ 775.7 million. In the first quarter of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> posted a $ 10.1 million profit.
