f its assets, take control of its patents and close its <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> plants. New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Colt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday it wanted to sell the troubled firearms division to concentrate on its aerospace, automotive and industrial services operations. Colt has not put a price on the division, but industry analysts have said it probably is worth $ 150 million to $ 200 million. The <ORGANIZATION> UAM </ORGANIZATION> represents about 1,100 workers who walked out three years ago. The firearms division has staffed its <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> plants mostly with non-union replacement workers, although some union members have crossed picket lines and returned to work. About 800 workers remain on strike. About 650 strikers voted unanimously Tuesday night to pursue the buyout, <PERSON> Madore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brecher </PERSON>, deputy commissioner for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, said the department has specialists who can advise employees on how to obtain financing for such buyouts, although he warned the buyouts face enormous difficulties. `` The track record is spotty,'' he said. `` There have n't been that many successful ones in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. The ingredients really require that you have a very patient seller, a seller that for one reason or another is motivated to work with employees.''
