<HEAD>New Coleman Co. President Named</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coleman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s former president, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, was brought back by the new owner of the outdoor recreation products manufacturer Wednesday to take that post again. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, grandson of the founder of the company, announced Tuesday that Wall Street takeover strategist <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> had fired him as president, chief executive and board chairman. A <ORGANIZATION> Coleman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> prepared statement Wednesday said <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> resigned. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 58, left <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> in January 1988 to become vice chairman and chief financial officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Fleming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He was chairman of the <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> executive committee from 1985 to 1987 after serving as president from 1971. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> is a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regents </ORGANIZATION> and was an unsuccessful candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nomination for governor in 1986. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> MacAndrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was appointed <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> chairman Wednesday. He said he would serve as liaison with <ORGANIZATION> MacAndrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION>, which is wholly owned by <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> and is <ORGANIZATION> Coleman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s new parent corporation. The investment firm also owns <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Perelman </PERSON> bought <ORGANIZATION> Coleman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> six weeks ago for $ 545 million <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>'s offices will remain in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> will keep his office at <ORGANIZATION> MacAndrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION>' Midwestern headquarters in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> is the world's top manufacturer of outdoor recreation products, including <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> lanterns. Record sales of $ 657.9 million and record earnings of $ 24.5 million were recorded in 1988.
