<HEAD>Ogilvy First-Quarter Earnings Up 10.6 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the advertising agency holding company under threat of a hostile takeover, said Wednesday its first-quarter profit rose 10.6 percent over the same 1988 period. <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 3.8 million, or 26 cents a share, on revenue of $ 197.7 million. That compared with earnings of $ 3.43 million, or 24 cents a share, on revenue of $ 191.1 million in the first quarter last year. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> company attributed the gains to strong overseas performances. It said foreign advertising revenues increased 12.6 percent while domestic advertising revenues were flat. <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, which owns <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, the big <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> advertising firm, made an unsolicited $ 730 million bid for <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> last week. <PERSON> Ogilvy </PERSON>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worldwide </ORGANIZATION>, said it wants to remain independent. <PERSON> Ogilvy </PERSON>, the world's fifth-largest ad holding company, said quarterly advertising revenues increased 5 percent to $ 123.6 million from $ 117.7 million a year ago. Its public relations division, which includes <ORGANIZATION> Adams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Rhinehart </PERSON>, showed a 30 percent revenue rise, to $ 12.99 million. Its marketing research division revenue declined 10 percent, while other areas suffered a 23 percent drop, principally from divested operations.
