<HEAD>Textile Caucus Forms Task Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional allies of the textile industry, undaunted by setbacks in recent years, formed a task force Wednesday to search for new means to combat foreign inroads in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. `` We know that the textile and apparel workers that we represent need their jobs,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Tenn </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Textile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>. `` We will have to find creative legislative solutions to slow the flood of imports that is threatening their jobs.'' <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already has made it clear that he will not back omnibus legislation to aid the textile industry. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has passed such measures in recent years but sponsors have been unable to muster enough votes to override presidential vetoes. Instead of putting all of their efforts into one bill, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> said, textile lawmakers would `` pursue many avenues to assist the textile and apparel industry ... Our legislative activities will be much more diverse than they have been in recent years.'' As examples, she cited a bill introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga., that would eliminate a scheduled 50 percent cut in tariffs on textiles and apparels imported from <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> Initiative countries Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hefner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, may offer measures involving military apparel, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> said in a statement released by her office. Besides <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, other members of the task force are Reps. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Moakley </PERSON>, D-Mass.
