<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-USTrade 1stLd-Writethru f0084 05-03 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-US Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0084,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Cites 42 U.S. Trade Barriers; Criticizes 1988 Trade Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Its release ...,' to CORRECT that U.S. report
released Friday, sted Tuesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday released its 1989 report on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade barriers, singling out 42 regulations and trade practices that it said impedes imports from the 12 European Economic Community nations. The barriers include quantitative restrictions, export subsidies, customs barriers, public procurement policies, countervailing duties, anti-dumping procedures and tax policies, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> report said. Its release came five days after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration released its report on foreign trade practices it considers unfair. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Claus </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehlermann </PERSON> said the timing of the release of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> report was not linked to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> report. He said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> report was an annual event and its release simply `` coincided'' with the report by the Office of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Special Trade Representative. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> report criticized the 1988 U.S. Fair Trade Practices Act which, it said, will `` make it more likely that unilateral action will be taken to redress allegedly unfair trade practices,'' `` Such unilateral action ... without authorization from the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade is illegal.'' The report also cited the `` Buy American'' provision of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Act that `` has created permanent discrimination in favor of <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. products.'' The clause provides for action by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Administration against foreign countries which discriminate against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products or services in government procurement, including a ban against `` offending'' countries. Another category of restrictions includes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> measures which have been found to violate international trading rules, and in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has neither modified nor offered compensation to its trade partners for trade damage caused. As examples the report cites the `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> failure'' to implement findings of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> on the illegality of the `` Superfund'' oil levy and the `` non-conformity'' of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system of customs users' fees.
</TEXT>
