<HEAD>USAir Buys Up To 40 Planes from McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 1.3 billion deal Wednesday with <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to buy 20 of its MD-82 aircraft and take options on 20 more. The first two of the new planes would be delivered in September 1992 and the remainder of the firm orders and options, if taken, would be delivered to <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> at the rate of one per month starting in January 1993. The planes will carry about 143 passengers, including an eight-seat first-class section. Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's ninth-largest airline, is a long-time operator of <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> aircraft. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s fleet currently includes 31 Md-80s acquired through the 1988 merger of <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION>, and 74 smaller DC-9's, which also were made by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> ordered 18 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 jetliners and took options on 36 more in a deal with a potential value of about $ 1.7 billion. That transaction brings <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s current <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 orders to 68 aircraft, which will be delivered between now and 1992, plus 96 options, which would be delivered between 1992 and 1995, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> also has ordered 20 <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> 100 jets and holds options on 20 more. First delivery is scheduled for June. <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> is a Dutch aircraft manufacturer.
