<HEAD>Report: KKR Interested In Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> leveraged buyout firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has indicated an interest in acquiring <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, according to a report published Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> formally told <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> of its interest in a bid, the Wall Street Journal reported, quoting unidentified people familiar with the takeover battle. The notification Tuesday came as part of a bidding procedure <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> set up in response to oil billionaire <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' offer, the Journal said. If <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> pursues a bid, it would be the firm's largest known buyout effort since it bought <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for a record $ 25 billion in February, according to the Journal. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> refused comment on <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION>'s apparent interest, the newspaper said. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION>'s disclosure came in response to a deadline set by <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s investment banker, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the Journal said Bidders will next gain access to confidential company data as well as meetings with company management in return for signing a confidentiality agreement. Also on Tuesday, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> put his hostile $ 2.7 billion bid for <ORGANIZ