<HEAD>Bush Plan Now Before Committee Chairmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `The risk ...,' to UPDATE
with Brady comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to rescue the S & amp; L industry faces potential challenges from two powerful <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee chairmen after receiving a strong vote of support from the banking panel. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> capped four days of debate by approving the plan on a 49-2 vote Tuesday minutes before midnight. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had passed its own version of the bill last week. The legislation provides $ 157 billion over the next decade, most of it from taxpayers, to close or merge more than 500 failed institutions. It also would put <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L regulators under more direct administration control, increase spending to uncover fraud at S & amp; Ls and, in the key reform, require S & amp; L owners to risk more of their own capital when they make loans. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is particularly pleased with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill's capital provisions and is calling for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to swiftly complete the legislative process and put a finished bill on the president's desk. `` The risk now is delay,'' said Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, one of the architects of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan. The bill has `` gone through so far without major changes. ... If someone wanted to tinker with major components, we would argue that would be unwarranted and very costly.'' In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> indicated the administration would be working to modify some provisions of the bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> before the measure clears <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> singled out changes in the administration's proposals for setting up the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a new federal agency to dispose of repossessed assets of insolvent S & amp; Ls, including a provision which would require that some of the property be sold to low-income people at a discount. `` We do have serious concerns about the nature and direction of amendments which reconfigure the <ORGANIZATION> Resoution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The committee has made substantial modifications which alter the original design and intent of the administration proposal,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. `` We are particularly concerned about provisions that would divert resources needed for savings and loan resolutions to housing subsidies.'' Staff aides to the banking committee are expected to take until the end of next week to put the panel's bill in proper form and write a report accompanying the legislation. Other committees with an interest in parts of the measure would then get a week to produce alternatives, leaving a slim chance that the full House would before Memorial Day. Administration officials are also happy that both the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, so far, have stuck with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s complicated mechanism for keeping $ 50 billion in <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L spending out of the budget deficit. However, both Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, and Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, disagree with major provisions of the <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, in a speech last month, said he believes the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> financing mechanism wastes about $ 150 million a year because it inflates the government's borrowing costs. He's being urged by Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a member of the banking committee, to pursue the issue by including the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L spending in the budget deficit, but exempting it from the automatic cuts under Gramm-Rudman. `` If nothing else, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> can push it and back off and collect a few chits from the administration,'' said an industry lobbyist who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` He's got absolutely nothing to lose. It makes him a player on a very important issue.'' Pepper, whose panel governs debate on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, is pushing for looser capital rules, arguing that it is unfair to take away accounting breaks given to S & amp; Ls in the early 1980s in exchange for their takeover of ailing institutions. The legislation requires S & amp; L owners to risk $ 3 of `` real money'' or `` tangible'' capital for every $ 100 they lend _ double the requirement of the bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last month. The capital would act as a buffer to absorb losses before government deposit insurance kicks in. Pepper is likely to insist that the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> get a chance to reconsider the capital provisions.
