<HEAD>Cuomo Signs Poison Pill Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corporate directors will be able to use a `` poison pill'' to ward off unwanted takeover bids in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> under a bill signed into law Wednesday by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. Companies in other states can enact a poison pill, or anti-takeover plan, on their own. But legislation was needed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> because of a court decision last year that barred companies from treating the shares of a would-be acquirer different from those of other shareholders. The state had given that power to directors, but it expired April 1. The new law gives boards of directors facing a hostile takeover a chance to buy time to evaluate and react to the offers. By using a poison pill, those directors could make it more expensive for an outsider to buy a controlling portion of stock. At the same time, most poison pills allow stockholders of the company to buy more shares at a cheaper price. The new law takes effect immediately and expires July 1. Between now and then, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> are expected to work on some sort of permanent poison pill measure. Poison pills generally have been supported by management and Fortune 500 companies while they largely have been opposed by the securities industry and takeover entrepreneurs. `` Passage of this bill removes an incentive for people to leave <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the state's largest business lobbying group. The bill was approved unanimously in the Democratic-controlled state Assembly earlier Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
