<HEAD>Company Fined for Shipping Hazardous Waste Without Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANITE CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> waste-disposal company shipped a barge containing toxic levels of lead and cadmium overseas without required government approval, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has proposed a $ 51,750 fine. <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metallurgical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Granite </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, which failed to get <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s permission to export the material, is the first company hit with a fine under 1986 hazardous-waste export laws, the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> EPA is committed to ensuring that this country's hazardous waste problems are not simply relocated to other countries,'' said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Regional Administrator <PERSON> Valdus </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamkus </PERSON>, who also proposed a $ 12,700 fine against <ORGANIZATION> Beelman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Truck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Libory </LOCATION>, which is accused of accepting the shipment without proper documentation The Triangle shipment to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> was one of thousands last year by businesses seeking to avoid the expense of complying with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hazardous-waste laws, the <ORGANIZATION> Post-Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> reported. But for Triangle, the matter did not end when the ship containing its wastes docked this year in <LOCATION> Bilbao </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, toxic-waste exporters must notify the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> and, working through the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, gain approval from the importing nation before shipment. In Triangle's case, the company notified the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> but the ship set sail before Spanish approval was granted, the <PERSON> Post-Dispatch </PERSON> said. Triangle President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wegryzn </PERSON> acknowledged the materials were not shipped with <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s approval, but said he believed notifying the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> was sufficient. The materials were not highly toxic chemical wastes, said officials of the company, which takes metal wastes from steel mills, foundries and smelters and then resells them. On Dec. 28, about 750 cubic yards of metal waste and contaminated dirt from a 1984 Triangle warehouse fire was trucked to a barge on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and sent to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the newspaper said. The ship containing the waste arrived in <LOCATION> Bilbao </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, on Feb. 11 and the waste was trucked to Er Cosa, a company that reclaims copper. Er <PERSON> Cosa </PERSON> official <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Boveda </PERSON> said government approval was not required in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to receive the shipment he characterized as routine. The law requiring approval of the receiving nation went into effect in November 1986 _ the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> step to address concerns about toxic exports. Heavy fines and even jail sentences can be imposed for willful violations.
</TEXT>
