<HEAD>Three Takeshita Ministers in Washington; Trade Hotline Plan Unveiled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade minister told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials Tuesday his government plans to open trans-Pacific hotlines to help <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> enterprises boost exports to his country, a Japanese official reported. <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON>, minister of international trade and industry, informed <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> of the project, said <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Shingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamagami </PERSON>. Under the plan, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exporters or potential exporters would be invited to call in questions, problems or complaints directly to the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> MITI ministry, overseer of the country's global trade, using circuits available at Japanese government commercial offices in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and three other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities, he said. Complaints of Japanese import barriers and other red tape are a major source of trade friction between the two countries, aggravated by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last year of $ 52 billion, which after a modest drop is again rising. Details such as whether the hotlines would be for voice conversation or data exchange were not yet available, the spokesman said. There was no immediate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reaction. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other countries enjoying large trade surpluses with <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are lobbying vigorously to avoid being targeted by the end of this month for potential retaliation under 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade legislation. In another development, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> was quoted by a Japanese official as warning <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON> that rising <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> protectionist pressure will increase tension between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, challenging the two countries to manage their relations more effectively in the coming years. <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON> <PERSON> Muraoka </PERSON>, deputy <ORGANIZATION> MITI </ORGANIZATION> minister, briefing Japanese reporters, added that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was optimistic that `` effective and proper management will be possible.'' Three ministers of Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s cabinet were in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Tuesday even though the prime minister plans to resign later this month because of involvement in an influence scandal Besides <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON> they were Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hata </PERSON> and <PERSON> Masahisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>, director-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Officials of both governments said the visits were planned before <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> announced he would step down, and reflected the Japanese decision to conduct normal government operations during the transition. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> himself is on a previously-scheduled tour of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>.
