<HEAD>House Banking Committee Approves Bush S&amp;L Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with committee vote.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday voted 49-2 approval of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to spend $ 157 billion over 10 years to bail out the savings and loan industry from what has been described as the worst financial crisis since the Depression. The bill also would put <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L regulators under more direct administration control, spend $ 75 million a year on investigating and prosecuting fraud at S & amp; Ls and, in the key reform, require S & amp; L owners to risk more of their own money when they make loans. The only dissenting votes, cast just before midnight after a 14-hour session, were from Reps. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said he would have preferred the bill to provide more housing help for poor people and anti-discrimination provisions. <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said he wanted tougher capital standards. The legislation requires S & amp; L owners to risk $ 3 of `` real money'' or `` tangible'' capital for every $ 100 they lend _ double the requirement of the bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last month. The capital would act as a buffer to absorb losses before government deposit insurance kicks in. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and one of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal's architects, praised the bill, saying, `` This committee exceeded everyone's expectations. ... Despite all the criticism of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan, the plain fact is it's gone through pretty much intact.'' `` This is a good bill. ... We all have reason to be proud,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, the committee's chairman. `` We will move this bill on the fast track as fast as House rules allow.'' After the banking panel completes its report on the bill, probably by the end of next week, at least two other committees _ Ways and <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> _ will have one week to review sections within their jurisdiction. Then, depending on how long the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> devotes to debate and action, a joint House-Senate conference committee could resolve differences between the two chambers and put the bill on the president's desk by the July 4 recess, five months after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made his proposal. The administration has endorsed the capital provisions of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, but Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is objecting, arguing it is unfair to take away capital breaks given to S & amp; Ls in the early 1980s in exchange for their takeover of ailing institutions Pepper's committee sets the rules governing debate on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor and committee members and their aides said they expect he will insist the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> get the chance to amend the capital standards. Most of the cost of the bailout will be born by taxpayers, the rest by the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L industry. However, $ 50 billion of the spending in the next three years will be excluded from the budget deficit through a complicated plan for borrowing the money, helping <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> meet his `` no new taxes pledge.'' Two provisions in the House legislation, not adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, are aimed at helping poor people obtain housing. One, offered by Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., and adopted 33-18, requires the new government agency that will liquidate failed S & amp; Ls _ the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ to offer poor people and non-profit groups at least a three-month option to buy low-priced residential properties owned by failed S & amp; Ls Two Republicans joined the 31 Democrats on the panel in passing the amendment. The 18 Republicans opposing it argued that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s proposal would dangerously restrict the government's ability to sell property from failed S & amp; Ls, open the government to lawsuits and eventually add to the taxpayer cost of the bailout <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, however, said his plan affected only $ 2 billion to $ 3 billion of the $ 200 billion to $ 300 billion in real estate the government will inherit from sick institutions and argued that it was a modest way to channel a few of the benefits of the massive S & amp; L bill to the public. A provision offered by <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and adopted last week requires the S & amp; L industry, through the regional <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION>, to provide $ 75 million a year to pay for reduced-rate mortgages for poor people. However, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel on Tuesday defeated a pair of amendments aimed at encouraging banks to do a better job of serving poor people and minorities. On a 27-23 vote with seven Democrats joining all 20 Republicans, the panel rejected an amendment by <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> that would have forced banks and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to publicly disclose federal regulators' ratings on how well they serve poor and minorities neighborhoods By a 30-21 vote, with 10 Democrats joining 20 Republicans, it voted against an amendment requiring regulators to report information on mortgage lending by race, age and gender. `` If you think for a second that discrimination does n't exist in financial institutions, then we are living in <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>, because it happens every day,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N </LOCATION>. Opponents said public disclosure of ratings kept by banking regulators would be misinterpreted by depositors and used by civil rights and community groups to create mischief. In other action Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee: _ Expanded the board overseeing the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from three members to five members, including Housing and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> and a private real estate expert <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had wanted a three-member board headed by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and including Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>. The committee also added <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> as a non-voting member He likely will be in charge of the day-to-day task of administering the cleanup. _ Voted 33-16 to adopt an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., to require banks and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls with assets of more than $ 150 million to obtain independent audits of their financial _ Defeated, 26-23, an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, that would have permitted regulators to revoke special accounting breaks granted to acquirors of failed S & amp; Ls in 1988
